eceived_by_Joker_(2019_film)"}
{"title_page": "Omar Hamdi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name          = Omar Hamdi \"Malva\"\n| image         = Omar Hamdi.jpg|\n| image_size    = \n| birth_date    = 1952\n| birth_place   = Tell Nayif, [[Al-Hasakah Governorate]], [[Syria]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|2015|10|18|1952}}\n| death_place   = [[Vienna]], [[Austria]]\n| occupation    = Painter\n}}\n'''Omar \"Malva\" Hamdi''' was a [[Syrian Kurd]]ish artist. From 1978 to 2015, he lived and worked in [[Vienna]], Austria.\n\n== Biography ==\nOmar \"Malva\" Hamdi was a Syrian Kurdish artist. Born in 1952 in [[Al-Hasakah Governorate|Al-Hasakah]], [[Syria]], he worked as a graphic artist for the Syrian Press, where he also wrote articles on an Artistic Criticism. He settled in Vienna in 1978 and was awarded the Austrian Nationality, he was a member of the General Federation of Austrian Artists and the UNESCO, and a member of the K\u00fcnstlerhaus \u2013 Wien.\n\nHis works of Art are widely exhibited in several art Galleries, including in particular, Arnot Gallery New York, which acted as a representative gallery of his works.\n\nHis works are acquired by art collectors and dealers, art galleries and exhibitions, museums, banks and Ministries of Culture, in addition to a large number of private property acquisitions in America, Canada, Austria, Germany, France, Italy, the Netherlands, Japan, Sri Lanka, and Russia.\n\nMany of his works have been printed in postcards and posters by several publishing houses and are being distributed in numerous countries worldwide.\n\nHis life was devoted to full-time artistic work.\n\n==Death==\nHe died in [[Vienna]] on 18 October 2015.<ref>[http://www.huffpostarabi.com/2015/10/18/story_n_8324462.html \u0648\u0641\u0627\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0646\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0648\u0631\u064a \u0639\u0645\u0631 \u062d\u0645\u062f\u064a \"\u0645\u0627\u0644\u0641\u0627\" \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0645\u0633\u0627 \u0639\u0646 \u0639\u0645\u0631 \u0646\u0627\u0647\u0632 63 \u0639\u0627\u0645\u0627]</ref>\n\n== One-Man Exhibitions \"Selection\" ==\n* 1976\u20131977 \u2013 People's Art Hall at Damascus, National Museum of Aleppo.\n* 1987 -Vienna, Palffy Palace \"Art Salon\"\n* 1989 \u2013 Vienna, Austrian Central Bank; Art Gallery Chicago; Lyzon Art Gallery Tennessee, Nashville; Gallery Kral, San Francisco; Gallery Arnot, New York; Gallery Ambassador, New York.\n* 1990 \u2013 Gallery L'Atelier, Vienna; Gallery Celeste, Vienna; Art House, G\u00f6ttingen, Germany.\n* 1991 \u2013 Gallery Frankenstein, Berlin.\n* 1992 \u2013 Wally Findlay Galleries, New York and Paris.\n* 1993 \u2013 Gallery Art Forum, International Contemporary Art, Vienna; AI-Sayed Art Gallery/Assad Library, Damascus.\n* 1994\u20131998 \u2013 Wally Findlay Galleries, New York, Chicago, Palm Beach, Florida.\n* 2000 \u2013 Green Art Gallery \u2013 Dubai.\n* 2000 \u2013 Wally Findlay Gallery \u2013 Palm Beach. 2002 \u2013 Rochan Gallery \u2013 Jeddah.\n\n== International and Group Exhibitions \"Selection\" ==\n* 1980\u20131992 \u2013 Exhibitions of the General Federation of Austrian Artists, in Austria and abroad.\n* 1985 \u2013 World Exhibition of the United Nations Office, Vienna.\n* 1989 \u2013 Art Festival Messepalast, Vienna; The First Arab Art Festival; Art House, G\u00f6ttingen, Germany.\n* 1985\u20131993 \u2013 The Annual World Art Fair, Frankfurt, Germany.\n* 1989 \u2013 International Fair of Contemporary Arts (Madrid Arco 89), Spain.\n* 1990 \u2013 International Fair of Contemporary Arts (Milano EXPO 90), Italy.\n* 1991 \u2013 Art Jonction International, Nice, France.\n* 1992 \u2013 Bolognafiere (Contemporary Art Festival), Bologna, Italy; Auro Art, Verona; K\u00fcnstlerhaus, Graz; EXPO Sevilla, Spain; Friendship and Peace Festival, Latakia, Syria.\n* 1993 \u2013 International Fair of Contemporary Art (Budapest Art Expo 93). *1993 \u2013 Gallery Breitenbach, Una, Germany.\n* 1994\u20131997 \u2013 International Art Fair, Frankfurt, Germany; Second International Festival of Sharjah.\n* 1999 \u2013 Informelle Tendenzen im \"K\u00fcnstlerhaus\", Vienna.\n* 2001 \u2013 Cairo, Biennale.\n* 2001 \u2013 Artuell, Beirut / Atassi Gallery Damas 2002.\n* 2002 \u2013 History Museum Vienna \u2013 Rathaus / New York Art Fair.\n* 2003 \u2013 National Museum Cracow, Poland.\n* 2003-Tehran Museum of Modern Arts\n* 2004 Art NY \u2013 USA\n\n==Books and articles on his works==\n* \"Malva\" Omar Hamdi, Life and Color, in Arabic, Damascus, 1976.by Janet Hanna Korkiss\n* \"Malva\" Omar Hamdi, Life and Work, in German, Vienna 1987, by Dr. S. Kaiser.\n* Malva, A Critical Study, in English and German by Nikolai Meikofski, published in 1991 by the Art Gallery, New York.\n* Malva, Impressionist Works, in English, published by Gallery Arnot, New York, 1991; in German by Gallery L'Atelier, A Critical and Analytical Study by Andre Manzano.\n* Malva, Omar Hamdi, 20 years of Oil Painting, Art Forum, Vienna, 1994.\n* Bachar \u2013 Malva, Atlas Production, 1992, in French and English, for the Bolognafiere, Italy. \u2013 Dictionary of World Artistic Criticism, 1999 in English, Flash Art Publishing.\n* International Directory of Arts, Galleries and Museums, 1991\u20131992, in German, Art Address, Frankfurt.\n* Several wall annual Calendars and exhibition-catalogues.\n* A Volume of 12 Paintings, published by the International Aid Organization in Venice, Italy, Comune di Padova, Progetto Giovanni, 1992.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.omarhamdimalva.com/index.html Omar Hamdi Malva Website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamdi, Omar}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Syrian painters]]\n[[Category:Syrian Kurdish people]]\n[[Category:Syrian emigrants to Austria]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name          = Omar Hamdi \"Malva\"\n| image         = Omar Hamdi.jpg|\n| image_size    = \n| birth_date    = 1952\n| birth_place   = Tell Nayif, [[Al-Hasakah Governorate]], [[Syria]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|2015|10|18|1952}}\n| death_place   = [[Vienna]], [[Austria]]\n| occupation    = Painter\n}}\n'''Omar \"Malva\" Hamdi''' was a [[Syrian Kurd]]ish artist. From 1978 to 2015, he lived and worked in [[Vienna]], Austria.\n\n== Biography ==\nOmar \"Malva\" Hamdi was a Syrian Kurdish artist. Born in 1952 in [[Al-Hasakah Governorate|Al-Hasakah]], [[Syria]], he worked as a graphic artist for the Syrian Press, where he also wrote articles on an Artistic Criticism. He settled in Vienna in 1978 and was awarded the Austrian Nationality, he was a member of the General Federation of Austrian Artists and the UNESCO, and a member of the K\u00fcnstlerhaus - Wien.\n\nHis works of Art are widely exhibited in several art Galleries, including in particular, Arnot Gallery New York, which acted as a representative gallery of his works.\n\nHis works are acquired by art collectors and dealers, art galleries and exhibitions, museums, banks and Ministries of Culture, in addition to a large number of private property acquisitions in America, Canada, Austria, Germany, France, Italy, the Netherlands, Japan, Sri Lanka, and Russia.\n\nMany of his works have been printed in postcards and posters by several publishing houses and are being distributed in numerous countries worldwide.\n\nHis life was devoted to full-time artistic work.\n\n==Death==\nHe died in [[Vienna]] on 18 October 2015.<ref>[http://www.huffpostarabi.com/2015/10/18/story_n_8324462.html \u0648\u0641\u0627\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0646\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0648\u0631\u064a \u0639\u0645\u0631 \u062d\u0645\u062f\u064a \"\u0645\u0627\u0644\u0641\u0627\" \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0645\u0633\u0627 \u0639\u0646 \u0639\u0645\u0631 \u0646\u0627\u0647\u0632 63 \u0639\u0627\u0645\u0627]</ref>\n\n== One-Man Exhibitions \"Selection\" ==\n* 1976\u20131977 - People's Art Hall at Damascus, National Museum of Aleppo.\n* 1987 -Vienna, Palffy Palace \"Art Salon\"\n* 1989 - Vienna, Austrian Central Bank; Art Gallery Chicago; Lyzon Art Gallery Tennessee, Nashville; Gallery Kral, San Francisco; Gallery Arnot, New York; Gallery Ambassador, New York.\n* 1990 - Gallery L'Atelier, Vienna; Gallery Celeste, Vienna; Art House, G\u00f6ttingen, Germany.\n* 1991 - Gallery Frankenstein, Berlin.\n* 1992 - Wally Findlay Galleries, New York and Paris.\n* 1993 - Gallery Art Forum, International Contemporary Art, Vienna; AI-Sayed Art Gallery/Assad Library, Damascus.\n* 1994\u20131998 - Wally Findlay Galleries, New York, Chicago, Palm Beach, Florida.\n* 2000 - Green Art Gallery - Dubai.\n* 2000 - Wally Findlay Gallery - Palm Beach. 2002 - Rochan Gallery - Jeddah.\n\n== International and Group Exhibitions \"Selection\" ==\n* 1980\u20131992 - Exhibitions of the General Federation of Austrian Artists, in Austria and abroad.\n* 1985 - World Exhibition of the United Nations Office, Vienna.\n* 1989 - Art Festival Messepalast, Vienna; The First Arab Art Festival; Art House, G\u00f6ttingen, Germany.\n* 1985\u20131993 - The Annual World Art Fair, Frankfurt, Germany.\n* 1989 - International Fair of Contemporary Arts (Madrid Arco 89), Spain.\n* 1990 - International Fair of Contemporary Arts (Milano EXPO 90), Italy.\n* 1991 - Art Jonction International, Nice, France.\n* 1992 - Bolognafiere (Contemporary Art Festival), Bologna, Italy; Auro Art, Verona; K\u00fcnstlerhaus, Graz; EXPO Sevilla, Spain; Friendship and Peace Festival, Latakia, Syria.\n* 1993 - International Fair of Contemporary Art (Budapest Art Expo 93). *1993 - Gallery Breitenbach, Una, Germany.\n* 1994\u20131997 - International Art Fair, Frankfurt, Germany; Second International Festival of Sharjah.\n* 1999 - Informelle Tendenzen im \"K\u00fcnstlerhaus\", Vienna.\n* 2001 - Cairo, Biennale.\n* 2001 - Artuell, Beirut / Atassi Gallery Damas 2002.\n* 2002 - History Museum Vienna - Rathaus / New York Art Fair.\n* 2003 - National Museum Cracow, Poland.\n* 2003-Tehran Museum of Modern Arts\n* 2004 Art NY - USA\n\n==Books and articles on his works==\n* \"Malva\" Omar Hamdi, Life and Color, in Arabic, Damascus, 1976.by Janet Hanna Korkiss\n* \"Malva\" Omar Hamdi, Life and Work, in German, Vienna 1987, by Dr. S. Kaiser.\n* Malva, A Critical Study, in English and German by Nikolai Meikofski, published in 1991 by the Art Gallery, New York.\n* Malva, Impressionist Works, in English, published by Gallery Arnot, New York, 1991; in German by Gallery L'Atelier, A Critical and Analytical Study by Andre Manzano.\n* Malva, Omar Hamdi, 20 years of Oil Painting, Art Forum, Vienna, 1994.\n* Bachar - Malva, Atlas Production, 1992, in French and English, for the Bolognafiere, Italy. - Dictionary of World Artistic Criticism, 1999 in English, Flash Art Publishing.\n* International Directory of Arts, Galleries and Museums, 1991-1992, in German, Art Address, Frankfurt.\n* Several wall annual Calendars and exhibition-catalogues.\n* A Volume of 12 Paintings, published by the International Aid Organization in Venice, Italy, Comune di Padova, Progetto Giovanni, 1992.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.omarhamdimalva.com/index.html Omar Hamdi Malva Website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamdi, Omar}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Syrian painters]]\n[[Category:Syrian Kurdish people]]\n[[Category:Syrian emigrants to Austria]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omar_Hamdi"}
{"title_page": "Tim Holt", "text_new": "{{Short description|American actor}}\n{{For|other people with the same name|Timothy Holt (disambiguation){{!}}Timothy Holt}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Tim Holt\n| image         = Tim Holt Western.jpg\n| caption       = Holt in 1948\n| birth_name    = Charles John Holt III\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1919|02|05}}\n| birth_place   = [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1973|02|15|1919|02|05}}\n| death_place   = [[Shawnee, Oklahoma|Shawnee]], [[Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| resting_place = Memory Lane Cemetery <br> [[Harrah, Oklahoma|Harrah]], [[Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| education     = [[Culver Academies|Culver Military Academy]]\n| occupation    = [[Actor]]\n| years_active  = 1927\u20131971\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Virginia Ashcroft|1938|1944|end=divorced}} <br> {{marriage|Alice Harrison|1944|1952|end=divorced}} <br> {{marriage|Birdee Stephens|1952|1973|end=died}}\n| children      = 4\n| parents       = [[Jack Holt (actor)|Jack Holt]] <br> Margaret Woods\n| relatives     = [[Jennifer Holt]] (sister)\n}}\n\n'''Charles John''' \"'''Tim'''\" '''Holt III''' (February 5, 1919 \u2013 February 15, 1973) was an [[Americans|American]] actor. He was a popular [[Western (genre)|Western]] star during the 1940s and early 1950s, appearing in forty-six [[B movie|B]] westerns released by [[RKO Pictures]].\n\nIn a career spanning more than four decades, Holt is best remembered for his roles in the films ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' (1942) and ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre (film)|The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]'' (1948).\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Jack Holt & Son.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Tim Holt and his father, actor Jack Holt (1921)]]\nTim Holt was born Charles John Holt III on February 5, 1919, in [[Beverly Hills, California]], the son of actor [[Jack Holt (actor)|Jack Holt]] and Margaret Woods.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|title=Tim Holt |work=The New York Times |date= |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/33051/Tim-Holt/biography |accessdate=October 12, 2012}}</ref>  During his early years, he accompanied his father on location, even appearing in an early silent film.<ref name=\"b-westerns\">{{cite web|title=Tim Holt |publisher=B-Westerns |url=http://www.b-westerns.com/holt1.htm |accessdate=October 12, 2012}}</ref> He was the inspiration for his father's book, ''Lance and His First Horse''.\n\nHolt was educated at [[Culver Military Academy]] in [[Culver, Indiana]], graduating in 1936.<ref name=\"b-westerns\"/> One of his classmates was [[Budd Boetticher]] who recalled Holt \"used to walk around in our suite of rooms there\u2026and he often had on his .38 revolvers and holster. He\u2019d walk up and down the hall in his bathrobe and practice drawing his guns. He\u2019d say, \u2018I\u2019m going to be a western star some day\u2019.\"<ref name=\"stempel\">{{cite web|url=http://offscreen.com/view/tim-holt-and-the-b-western|title=Tim Holt and the B Western|publisher=}}</ref> Immediately after graduation he went to work in the [[Hollywood]] film business.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\n==Acting career==\n===Walter Wanger===\nHolt was signed to a contract by [[Walter Wanger]] in January 1937.<ref>Graham, Sheilah. \"Schulberg Casts Sylvia Sidney in Krasna Feature\". ''Los Angeles Times'' (1923\u2013Current file). 07 January 1937: 8.</ref> Wanger was going to use him in ''Blockade'', but that film was postponed.<ref>\"Screen News Here and in Hollywood: Plans to Produce 'Personal History' Are Abandoned for the Present by Wanger \u2013 'Tropic Holiday' to Open, Bob Burns and Martha Raye to Be Featured in Picture at Paramount This Morning Of Local Origin, Special to the New York Times\". ''New York Times'' (1923\u2013Current file). 29 June 1938: 15.</ref>\n\nInstead he made his debut as [[Anne Shirley (actress)|Anne Shirley]]'s suitor in ''[[Stella Dallas (1937 film)|Stella Dallas]]'' (1937) for [[Sam Goldwyn]] \u2013 the same role that another film star's son, Douglas Fairbanks Jr., had played in the 1925 version.<ref>{{cite news|author=Schallert, Edwin|title=James Foran, Brother of Dick, Will Make Debut as Comedy Star: John Howard Latest Choice for 'Drummond'|work=Los Angeles Times|date=14 June 1937|page= 6}}</ref> When told he was given the role his father Jack said, \"Fine. Let's have one good actor in the family.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Star's Son Good Actor|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=27 Feb 1941|page= 12}}</ref> Wanger then cast him in ''[[I Met My Love Again]]'' (1938) and used him for a Technicolor Western, ''Gold is where you find It''. In the latter the ''Los Angeles Times'' said Holt \"confirms the favourable impression he gave\" in ''Stella Dallas''.<ref>Color Film Success at Box Office Lusk, Norbert|work=Los Angeles Times|date=19 Feb 1938|page=8}}</ref>\n\nRKO borrowed him for a western ''[[The Renegade Ranger]]'' (1938) supporting George O'Brien, then a leading star of B-westerns. Wanger wanted to star Holt opposite Henry Fonda and [[Louise Platt]] in an adaptation of [[Vincent Sheean]]'s ''Personal History''; however after the problems Wanger had making ''Blockade'' he decided to postpone the project. (It was later filmed as ''Foreign Correspondent''.) He lent Holt to Paramount to play the juvenile lead in ''[[Sons of the Legion]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=SCREEN NEWS HERE AND IN HOLLYWOOD: Plans to Produce 'Personal History' Are Abandoned for the Present by Wanger TROPIC HOLIDAY' TO OPEN Bob Burns and Martha Raye to Be Featured in Picture at Paramount This Morning Of Local Origin Special to THE NEW YORK TIMES..|work= New York Times|date=29 June 1938|page=15}}</ref> then RKO asked for him again in ''[[The Law West of Tombstone]]'', supporting [[Harry Carey (actor)|Harry Carey]].\n\nWanger then used Holt in the role of young Lieutenant Blanchard in the 1939 classic ''[[Stagecoach (1939 film)|Stagecoach]]''. At Universal he appeared in a story of his old alma mater, Culver Military Academy, ''[[The Spirit of Culver]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=COMINGS AND GOINGS.... NEWS OF STAGE AND SCREEN: Culver Opus Given Expert Supervision Gen. Gignilliat, Head of Academy, Handling Technique|author=Hopper, Hedda|work=Los Angeles Times|date=19 Feb 1939|page=C3}}</ref>\n\nHis contract with Wanger expired. RKO signed Holt to a seven-year contract in December 1938.<ref>Holt played young Lieutenant Blanchard in the 1939 classic ''[[Stagecoach (1939 film)|Stagecoach]]''.</ref><ref>\"Screen News Here and in Hollywood: Dick Powell, Joan Blondell to Leave Warners \u2013 Miss Lindsay in Mystery Play \u2013 Two Foreign Films Today 'Little Flower,' Made in France, and the Italian, 'Amore in Quarantena,' Will Open, Miss Lindsay Gets Lead, Coast Scripts Of Local Origin, Special to The New York Times\". ''New York Times'' (1923\u2013Current file). 12 December 1938: 26.</ref><ref name=Mott>Mott, Robert. \"Tim Holt, Actor in Western Films, Dies\", ''The Washington Post''. 17 February 1973: B6.</ref>\n\n===RKO Pictures===\n[[File:Fifth Avenue Girl 1939.JPG|thumb|upright=1.2|Lobby card for ''[[5th Ave Girl|5th Avenue Girl]]'' (1939)]]\n[[File:Laddie lobby card 3.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Lobby card for ''[[Laddie (1940 film)|Laddie]]'' (1940)]]\nRKO gave Holt his first lead, in the B-film ''[[The Rookie Cop]]''. It was popular and RKO put him in ''[[The Girl and the Gambler]]'', opposite [[Leo Carrillo]]. He was then cast as the romantic lead for the studio's biggest star, [[Ginger Rogers]], in ''[[5th Avenue Girl]]'' (1939). It was popular and the ''Los Angeles Times'' said Holt \"does unusually well in this\"<ref>{{cite news|title=FIFTH AVENUE GIRL' HITS HIGH SPOTS OF MIRTH, BUT UNEVEN|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=17 Aug 1939|page=8}}</ref> although the ''New York Times'' thought he \"seems a trifle young to be running a great corporation\".<ref>{{cite news|title=THE SCREEN: Slight Light Comedy Is RKO's Fifth Avenue Girl,' With Ginger Rogers, at the Radio City Music Hall|author=FRANK S|work=NUGENT. New York Times|location=New York, N.Y|date=25 Aug 1939|page=12}}</ref>\n\nHe was meant to play the eldest son in ''[[Three Sons]]'' (1939) with Edward Ellis<ref>{{cite news|title=DRAMA: Betty Field Awarded New Paramount Lead|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=15 June 1939|page=8}}</ref> but he was withdrawn and replaced by [[William Gargan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=SCREEN NEWS HERE AND IN HOLLYWOOD: Universal to Start 'One Hour to Live,' 'Missing Evidence' and 'Rio' on Monday 'WATERFRONT' AT GLOBE 'To the Victor,' 'Orage' and 'La Kermesse Heroique' Among Films Listed for Today Raft Signs With Warner Spewaks to Write for McCarey|author=DOUGLAS W CHURCHILL Special to THE NEW YORK TIMES..|work= New York Times|date=15 July 1939|page=14}}</ref> He was also meant to star in a Western, ''Silver City'', with [[Betty Grable]], but it was not made.<ref>{{cite news|title=SCREEN NEWS HERE AND IN HOLLYWOOD: Three Pictures Are Placed on RKO Schedule--Cukor May Direct 'Susan and God' MAINTAIN FILM OUTPUT Columbia Studios Will Spend $5,000,000 More This Year on Production, Cohn Says Ruby Keeler Out of Film George Cukor May Direct|author=DOUGLAS W CHURCHILL Special to THE NEW YORK TIMES..|work= New York Times|date=12 Sep 1939|page=35}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1940 it was announced Holt and [[Ginger Rogers]] would be reunited in an adaptation of ''[[The Enchanted Cottage (play)|The Enchanted Cottage]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Americans to Sponsor Production in England: Durbin British Winner New Ameche, Faye Film Sandy's Sex 'Decided' Newcomer Awarded Role Gail Patrick Assigned|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=4 Jan 1940|page=13}}</ref> The film was not made until [[The Enchanted Cottage (1945 film)|several years later]] with different stars. Instead he was assigned to play Fritz Robinson in the studio's expensive adaptation of ''Swiss Family Robinson'' (1940). He also played the lead in ''Laddie'' (1940); the ''Los Angeles Times'' called him \"engaging and capable\".<ref>{{cite news|title='Laddie' Engaging Picture|author=G K|work=Los Angeles Times|date=13 Sep 1940|page=21}}</ref> ''Swiss Family Robinson'' was a financial failure and ''Laddie'' was not particularly popular.\n\n====Western star====\nDuring the late 1930s, [[George O'Brien (actor)|George O'Brien]] had made a number of low budget Westerns for RKO. Holt later recalled, \"I believe George O\u2019Brien quit over money so RKO needed another Western star and I was put forward.\"<ref name=\"interview\"/>\n\nIn early 1940, RKO announced Holt would make six low budget B-Westerns, starting with ''Wagon Train'' with Martha O'Driscoll.<ref>{{cite news|title=53 FEATURE FILMS SCHEDULED BY RKO: 1940\u201341 Plans Announced at Sales Convention of Firm Now in Session Here 190 SHORTS ON PROGRAM Gallup Survey of the Audience Interest in Pictures Is Being Conducted for Company Plans Research Institute Film by Orson Welles}}</ref> O'Driscoll and Holt were meant to reteam in ''Sir Piegan Passes'' but it was not made.<ref>{{cite news|title=SCREEN NEWS HERE AND IN HOLLYWOOD: 'Kiss Me Again' Purchased by Ernst Lubitsch, Producer for United Artists 'GHOST BREAKERS' OPENING Paramount Attraction Starts Today--'Spies in the Air' Is Rialto Offering Special to THE NEW YORK TIMES..|work= New York Times|date=3 July 1940|page=15}}</ref> Instead Holt appeared in ''[[The Fargo Kid]]''.\n\nUniversal borrowed him to play [[Charles Boyer]]'s son in ''Back Street'' (1941). The ''Los Angeles Times'' said Holt had \"some splendid scenes towards the end\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Censor-Daring Theme Well Presented|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=5 Feb 1941|page=A10}}</ref> Then it was back to Westerns: ''[[Robbers of the Range]]'' (1941), ''[[Along the Rio Grande]]'' (1941), ''[[Cyclone on Horseback]]'' (1941) and ''[[Six-Gun Gold]]'' (1941).\n\nHolt usually played a cowboy who had one or two friends, who occasionally sang. From 1940\u201342 he made 18 Westerns. His first sidekick was [[Ray Whitley (singer-songwriter, born 1901)|Ray Whitley]], who was slightly older than Holt, and who would usually sing a song or two in each film. The other sidekick was a character \"Whopper\" played by [[Emmett Lynn]] and then [[Lee White (actor)|Lee White]]. 1942 they were replaced by [[Cliff Edwards]] as Ike.\n\nAuthor Tom Stempel later recalled:\n<blockquote>Holt, unlike many other B western stars, played characters not named Tim Holt. From his debut in 1934 [[Gene Autry]] always played \"Gene Autry\" and after 1941 [[Roy Rogers]] always played \"Roy Rogers,\" but Holt's names varied, even if the basic character he played is the same...  In these early films Tim's jobs were diverse. While [[Hopalong Cassidy]] was always the foreman of the Bar 20 Ranch, Tim played a cowboy, a Treasury agent, a Texas Ranger, or a number of other occupations. The characters were pretty much the same: Tim, with his boyish good looks, is drawn into situations where he must right some wrongs. Holt had a charming personality on the screen, which made him one of the top western stars from 1940 to 1943.<ref name=\"stempel\"/></blockquote>\n\nThe Westerns proved popular and Holt wound up making six more: ''[[The Bandit Trail]]'' (1941), ''[[Dude Cowboy]]'' (1941), ''[[Riding the Wind]]'' (1942), ''[[Land of the Open Range]]'' (1942), ''[[Come on Danger]]'' (1942) and ''[[Thundering Hoofs]]'' (1942).\n\n====''The Magnificent Ambersons''====\n[[File:The-Magnificent-Ambersons-7.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|[[Joseph Cotten]], [[Anne Baxter]] and Tim Holt in ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' (1942)]]\n\nHolt's career received a boost in September 1941<ref>{{cite news|title=Previews Reveal Fitful Start for New Season: 'Yank' Leads in Potency Welles Casts Tim Holt Costumes Tempt Power Good Things for Ginger Goldwyn Lot Hyphenated|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=18 Sep 1941|page=A11}}</ref> when [[Orson Welles]] cast him as the lead in his second film, ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' (1942).  \"It was a lucky decision\", Welles later said, calling Holt \"one of the most interesting actors that's ever been in American movies\".<ref name=\"Welles TIOW\">{{cite book |last1=Welles |first1=Orson |authorlink1=Orson Welles |last2=Bogdanovich |first2=Peter |authorlink2=Peter Bogdanovich |last3=Rosenbaum |first3=Jonathan |authorlink3=Jonathan Rosenbaum |title=[[This is Orson Welles]] |publisher=HarperCollins |location=New York |date=1992 |isbn=0-06-016616-9}}</ref>{{Rp|113}} The ''Washington Post'' thought Holt \"gives an excellent account of himself\". The ''New York Times'' said he \"draws out all the meanness in George's character which is precisely what the role demands.\"<ref>{{cite news|title='The Magnificent Ambersons,' Welles's Film From Novel by Tarkington, Opens at Capitol -- 'The Big Street' at Palace|author=T.M.P.. |work=New York Times|date=14 Aug 1942|page=13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Magnificent Ambersons' Suffer Decline at Keith's: New Orson Welles Film a Glorified Tragedy That Sacrifices Dramatic Power to New Photographic Splendor and Odd Technique|author=|work=The Washington Post|date=17 July 1942|page=12}}</ref> (In 1965 Welles wanted to reshoot the ending with those of the original cast still alive, including Holt, but it did not eventuate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alexander Signed for POW Movie|author=|work=Los Angeles Times|date=10 Dec 1965|page=d19}}</ref>)\n\nRKO announced they had purchased two stories for Holt, ''Five of Spades'' (which became ''[[The Avenging Rider]]'') and ''Adventures of Salt Valley''. He was always announced for ''There Goes Lona Henry''.<ref>{{cite news|title=DRAMA: Welles to Act Turk Spy in 'Journey Into Fear' Paramount Signs McCrea 'Spitfire' Release Set Subjects Named for Holt Lindsay Slate Crowded Brent Returning Monday|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=7 Jan 1942|page=8}}</ref> Holt was going to enter the army, so RKO quickly put him in six more Westerns: ''[[Bandit Ranger]]'' (1942), ''[[Red River Robin Hood]]'' (1942), ''[[Pirates of the Prairie]]'' (1942), ''[[Fighting Frontier]]'' (1943), ''[[Sagebrush Law]]'' (1943) and ''[[The Avenging Rider]]'' (1942).<ref name=\"rko story\">Richard Jewell & Vernon Harbin, ''The RKO Story.'' New Rochelle, New York: Arlington House, 1982. p175</ref>\n\nHis entry into the [[U.S. Army Air Forces]] was delayed long enough so that Holt could star in ''[[Hitler's Children (1943 film)|Hitler's Children]]'' (1943).<ref>{{cite news|title=SCREEN NEWS HERE AND IN HOLLYWOOD: United Artists to Take Over 11 Finished Paramount Films and Distribute Them NEW PICTURE AT CARNEGIE 'Loves of Edgar Allan Poe' Will Open Today -- 'You Can't Take It With You' Revived By Telephone to THE NEW YORK TIMES..|work= New York Times|date=19 Sep 1942|page=9}}</ref> He was called to active duty during the making of the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=HEDDA HOPPER Says: New Picture Brings Fame to Producer|author=|work=Los Angeles Times|date=28 Mar 1943|page=C2}}</ref> However it was one of RKO's most profitable movies during the war.\n\n====War service====\nHolt became a decorated combat veteran of World War II, flying in the [[Asiatic-Pacific Theater|Pacific Theatre]] with the [[United States Army Air Forces]] as a [[B-29]] bombardier.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> He was wounded over Tokyo on the last day of the war and was awarded a Purple Heart.<ref>Hopper, Hedda. \"Looking at Hollywood\". ''Los Angeles Times'' (1923\u2013Current file). 18 October 1945: 10.</ref>  He was also a recipient of the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]].<ref>http://www.39th.org/39th/aerial/62nd/crew59dfc.html \u2013 retrieved August 30, 2016.</ref><ref>http://airforce.togetherweserved.com/usaf/servlet/tws.webapp.WebApps?cmd=ShadowBoxProfile&type=Person&ID=120796 retrieved August 20, 2016</ref>\n\n===Post-war===\n[[File:Tim Holt in The Treasure of the Sierra Madre trailer.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Tim Holt in the trailer for ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre (film)|The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]'' (1948)]]\nFollowing the war, Holt returned to films and went back to RKO. According to his biographer David Rothel, \"No more was he the callow, youthful cowboy with big, silly grin on his face. Now he exuded a steady, serious no-nonsense type of mature cowboy who was less impulsive, more contemporary, and somewhat \u2018world weary.\"<ref name=\"stempel\"/><ref>Rothel, David. ''Tim Holt'' (1994). Madison, North Carolina: Empire Publishing Company</ref> Tom Stempel argues that \"While Holt had lost his baby fat during the war, he still had a wonderful grin and cute dimples. He used the mixture of charm and seriousness very well.\"<ref name=\"stempel\"/>\n\nHis post-war career began well when 20th Century Fox borrowed him to play [[Virgil Earp]] alongside [[Henry Fonda]]'s [[Wyatt Earp]] in the [[John Ford]] western ''[[My Darling Clementine]]'' (1946). For RKO he appeared in a series of [[Zane Gray]] adaptations: ''[[Thunder Mountain (1947 film)|Thunder Mountain]]'' (1947),<ref>{{cite news|title=Ford Closes Four-Film Deal; 'Fugitive' First|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=2 Oct 1946|page=A3}}</ref> ''[[Under the Tonto Rim (1947 film)|Under the Tonto Rim]]'' (1947) and ''[[Wild Horse Mesa (1947 film)|Wild Horse Mesa]]'' (1947). He also made ''[[Western Heritage]]'' (1947), which was an original screenplay. The budgets were around $100,000 a film, making them among the more expensive B Westerns.<ref>{{cite news|title=Horse Operas Western Films Are Hollywood's Sure-Fire Financial Winners: Range From $40,000 'Oaters' To $1.5 Million 'Epics'; Are 25% of Film Output Action, Danger and Chase Horse Operas: Western Films Are Hollywood's Financial Winners|author=JOSEPH W|work=TAYLOR Staff Correspondent of THE WALL STREET JOURNAL. Wall Street Journal|location=New York, N.Y|date=15 Apr 1948|page=1}}</ref>\n\n====''The Treasure of the Sierra Madre''====\nHolt was next borrowed by Warner Bros for the role for which he is probably best remembered \u2014 that of Bob Curtin to [[Humphrey Bogart]]'s Fred C. Dobbs in [[John Huston]]'s ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre (film)|The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]'' (1948), about two friends who team up to prospect for gold, only to have greed tear apart their partnership. Holt's father also appeared in a small part.  Tim Holt tended to be overshone in reviews by Bogart and [[Walter Huston]]. However the ''Chicago Daily Tribune'' said he was very likeable\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Hustons Do Superb Job in This Film: TREASURE OF THE SIERRA MADRE\" THE CAST|author=TINEE, MAE|work=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=19 Mar 1948|page=a7}}</ref> The ''Los Angeles Times'' said Holt \"gives a rare and sincere impression of character in his performance.\"<ref>{{cite news|title='Treasure' Manifests Adult Power|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=15 Jan 1948|page=18}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''Los Angeles Times'', Holt's casting in ''Madre'' impressed RKO studio chief [[Dore Schary]] who announced \"expanding plans\" for the actor, looking to cast him in films other than Westerns. He also promised a bigger budget for Holt's Westerns such as ''[[The Arizona Ranger]]'' (1948), which cast him opposite his father.<ref>{{cite news|title=DRAMA AND FILM: Colbert Quits Capra Feature, Hepburn Cast|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=11 Oct 1947|page=A5}}</ref> However the films remained undistinguished: ''[[Guns of Hate]]'' (1948), ''[[Indian Agent (film)|Indian Agent]]'' (1948) and ''[[Gun Smugglers]]'' (1948).\n\nHis most frequent director was [[Lesley Selander]] and his sidekick in more than 25 of these movies was [[Richard Martin (RKO actor)|Richard Martin]]. Martin played Chito Jose Gonzales Bustamente Rafferty, a character created by writer Jack Wagner for the [[Bombardier (film)|1943 film ''Bombardier'']] and who had appeared in some [[Robert Mitchum]] westerns before being put into Tim Holt films. Stempel:\n<blockquote>The chemistry between Holt and Martin was immediate. Tim was entertained by Chito's constant pursuit of the ladies, which gave Holt a variety of reactions to play: amusement, surprise, slight irritation, bafflement at the hopelessness of Chito's attempted conquests. Unlike Hopalong Cassidy's young sidekick Lucky, who just mooned after girls, Chito was active, which was a lot more interesting to watch, especially with Tim's reactions. Chito was not just a lovesick fool, but also ready for action. As he explained his name, his mother was Spanish, and the Spanish is for loving, and his father was Irish, which is for fighting. Chito performed the crucial functions of a B western movie sidekick: he was somebody with whom the hero could discuss the plot, and he provided some comedy relief. In the 47-52 series, the comic relief is verbal rather than visual, and often a part of the story. The directors can shoot both Chito's flirting and Tim's reaction in one shot. Unlike other B westerns, such as those Holts with Cliff Edwards, the movie does not have to stop while the comic does his routine. It makes for much smoother flowing films.<ref name=\"stempel\"/></blockquote>\nIn 1948 Tim Holt also featured as the hero of a series of comic books<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westernclippings.com/comics/timholt_comicbookcowboys.shtml|title=Tim Holt - Comic Book Cowboys, by Boyd Magers|first=Donna|last=Magers|website=www.westernclippings.com}}</ref>\n\nHowever that year ''[[Brothers in the Saddle]]'' (1948) recorded a loss of $35,000<ref name=\"stempel\"/> as the growth of TV and decline in cinema audiences started to cut into Holt's market.\n\n===Later Movies===\nDore Schary left RKO in 1948 and the new management was not keen to cast Holt in anything other than Westerns: ''[[Rustlers (1949 film)|Rustlers]]'' (1949), ''[[Stagecoach Kid]]'' (1949), ''[[Masked Raiders]]'' (1949), ''[[The Mysterious Desperado]]'' (1949) and ''[[Riders of the Range (1949 film)|Riders of the Range]]'' (1949). The latter lost $50,000.<ref>Richard Jewell & Vernon Harbin, ''The RKO Story.'' New Rochelle, New York: Arlington House, 1982. p240</ref>\n\nThe Westerns continued: ''[[Dynamite Pass]]'' (1950), ''[[Storm over Wyoming]]'' (1950), ''[[Rider from Tucson]]'' (1950), ''[[Border Treasure]]'' (1950) and ''[[Rio Grande Patrol]]'' (1950). ''[[Law of the Badlands]]'' (1951) was the cheapest Tim Holt vehicle since the war years, made for $98,000, but still recorded a loss of $20,000.<ref>Richard Jewell & Vernon Harbin, ''The RKO Story.'' New Rochelle, New York: Arlington House, 1982. p255</ref>\n\nAfter ''[[Gunplay (film)|Gunplay]]'' (1951), ''[[Saddle Legion]]'' (1951) had a higher quality female lead \u2013 [[Dorothy Malone]] \u2013 and then Holt unexpectedly appeared in an \"A\", supporting [[Robert Mitchum]] and [[Jane Russell]] in ''[[His Kind of Woman]]'' for director [[John Farrow]].\n\nIn September 1950 it was announced Holt would support [[Montgomery Clift]] for director [[Nicholas Ray]] in ''[[The Flying Leathernecks]]'' (1951) but the film was made without either actor.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tim Holt Leatherneck; Directors Pick Huston; King Bros. Celebrating|author=Scheuer, Philip K|work=Los Angeles Times|date=5 Sep 1950|page=A11}}</ref>\n\nInstead it was back to Westerns: ''[[Pistol Harvest]]'' (1951), ''[[Hot Lead]]'' (1951), ''[[Overland Telegraph (film)|Overland Telegraph]]'' (1951), ''[[Trail Guide]]'' (1952), ''[[Road Agent (1952 film)|Road Agent]]'' (1952), ''[[Target (1952 film)|Target]]'' (1952), and finally ''[[Desert Passage (film)|Desert Passage]]'' (1952). The latter lost $30,000 so it was decided to end the series.<ref name=\"stempel\"/>\n\nHe made a TV appearance for ''[[Chevron Theatre]]''.\n\n==Later career==\nHolt had been to Oklahoma in 1947 with a rodeo, and met the woman who became his final wife. When his movie series ended he decided to move to Oklahoma for good. \"I never did like Hollywood that much\u2026 there was nothing magical about it for me\", he said.<ref name=\"interview\">{{cite web|url=https://fiftieswesterns.wordpress.com/2013/11/12/tim-holt-tuesday-2-john-booker-interviews-tim-holt-1970/|title=Tim Holt Tuesday #2: John Brooker Interviews Tim Holt, 1970|date=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe was absent from the screen for five years until he starred in a [[horror film]], ''[[The Monster That Challenged the World]]'', in 1957, Holt said it \"wasn\u2019t too bad a picture at all\".<ref name=\"interview\"/> Over the next 16 years, he appeared in only two more motion pictures as well as an episode of ''The Virginian''. He was going to make a sequel to ''Treasure of the Sierra Madre'' with [[Nick Adams (actor, born 1931)|Nick Adams]] but Adams died.<ref name=\"interview\"/>\n\nHowever he kept busy managing theatres and making personal appearances.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> He got a degree in animal nutrition from Iowa, worked as a builder, produced rodeos, staged and performed Western music jamborees, and worked as an advertising manager for a radio station from 1962 onwards.<ref name=Mott/> Holt later said of this period:\n<blockquote>Do you realize that this is the first time in my life that I can make my own decisions and do what I want to do? First it was my parents who told me what to do, then RKO told me what to do, then I went into the service and Uncle Sam told me what to do. I came back out and RKO still told me what to do. This is the first time I have not been under somebody's thumb in my life.[http://comicvine.gamespot.com/red-mask/4005-1345/] <ref name=\"stempel\"/></blockquote>\n\n==Personal life==\nHolt was married three times and had four children: three sons (one from his first marriage) and a daughter.\n\nTim Holt died from [[bone cancer]] on February 15, 1973<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19730216&id=OYMuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=qqEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4730,4332280|title=The Montreal Gazette - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com}}</ref> in [[Shawnee, Oklahoma]], where he had been managing a [[radio station]]. He was interred in the Memory Lane Cemetery in [[Harrah, Oklahoma]]. The street where he and his wife had lived in Harrah was subsequently renamed Tim Holt Drive in his honor.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nRobert Mott of the ''Washington Post'' later said of Holt:\n<blockquote>Holt was the hero, strong and silent and always more comfortable in the presence of boots and saddles, horses and he-men, than with the heroine \u2013 though he almost invariably ended up marrying her... Like many sons of famous entertainers, Tim Holt never achieved the stature of his father, and projected a bland image in contrast  with the elder Holt's strong characterisation.<ref name=Mott/></blockquote>\nIn 1991, Tim Holt was inducted posthumously into the [[Western Performers Hall of Fame]] at the [[National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum]] in [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]]. In 1992, the [[Golden Boot Awards]] honored Holt for his lifetime contributions to western cinema.\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[French Dressing (1927 film)|French Dressing]]'' (1927) (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Vanishing Pioneer]]'' (1928) as John Ballard, Age 7\n* ''[[History Is Made at Night (1937 film)|History Is Made at Night]]'' (1937) as S.O.S. Radio Operator (uncredited)\n* ''[[Stella Dallas (1937 film)|Stella Dallas]]'' (1937) as Richard Grosvenor\n* ''[[I Met My Love Again]]'' (1938) as Budge Williams\n* ''[[Gold Is Where You Find It]]'' (1938) as Lance Ferris\n* ''[[The Renegade Ranger]]'' (1938) as Larry Corwin\n* ''[[Sons of the Legion]]'' (1938) as Steven Scott\n* ''[[The Law West of Tombstone]]'' (1938) as Ted aka The Tonto Kid\n* ''[[Stagecoach (1939 film)|Stagecoach]]'' (1939) as Lieutenant Blanchard\n* ''[[The Spirit of Culver]]'' (1939) as Capt. Wilson\n* ''[[The Rookie Cop]]'' (1939) as Clem Maitland\n* ''[[The Girl and the Gambler]]'' (1939) as Johnny Powell\n* ''[[5th Ave Girl]]'' (1939) as Tim Borden\n* ''[[Laddie (1940 film)|Laddie]]'' (1940) as Laddie Stanton\n* ''[[Swiss Family Robinson (1940 film)|Swiss Family Robinson]]'' (1940) as Fritz Robinson\n* ''[[Wagon Train (1940 film)|Wagon Train]]'' (1940) as Zack Sibley\n* ''[[The Fargo Kid]]'' (1940) as The Fargo Kid\n* ''[[Back Street (1941 film)|Back Street]]'' (1941) as Richard Saxel\n* ''[[Along the Rio Grande]]'' (1941) as Jeff\n* ''[[Robbers of the Range]]'' (1941) as Jim Drummond aka Curly Yantis\n* ''[[Cyclone on Horseback]]'' (1941) as Stan Bradford\n* ''[[Six Gun Gold]]'' (1941) as Don Cardigan\n* ''[[The Bandit Trail]]'' (1941) as Steve Haggerty\n* ''[[Dude Cowboy]]'' (1941) as Terry McVey\n* ''[[Riding the Wind]]'' (1942) as Clay Stewart\n* ''[[Land of the Open Range]]'' (1942) as Dave Walton\n* ''[[Come on Danger]]'' (1942) as Jack Mason\n* ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' (1942) as George Minafer\n* ''[[Thundering Hoofs]]'' (1942) as Bill Underwood aka Bill Dawson\n* ''[[Bandit Ranger]]'' (1942) as Clay Travers\n* ''[[Red River Robin Hood]]'' (1942) as Jim Carey\n* ''[[Pirates of the Prairie]]'' (1942) as Deputy Marshal Larry Durant\n* ''[[Hitler's Children (1943 film)|Hitler's Children]]'' (1943) as Lieutenant Karl Bruner\n* ''[[Fighting Frontier]]'' (1943) as Kit Russell\n* ''[[Sagebrush Law]]'' (1943) as Tom Weston\n* ''[[The Avenging Rider]]'' (1943) as Brit Marshall\n* ''[[My Darling Clementine]]'' (1946) as [[Virgil Earp]]\n* ''[[Thunder Mountain (1947 film)|Thunder Mountain]]'' (1947) as Marvin Hayden\n* ''[[Under the Tonto Rim (1947 film)|Under the Tonto Rim]]'' (1947) as Brad Canfield\n* ''[[Wild Horse Mesa (1947 film)|Wild Horse Mesa]]'' (1947) as Dave Jordan\n* ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre (film)|The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]'' (1948) as Bob Curtin\n* ''[[Western Heritage]]'' (1948) as Ross Daggert\n* ''[[The Arizona Ranger]]'' (1948) as Bob Morgan\n* ''[[Guns of Hate]]'' (1948) as Bob Banning\n* ''[[Indian Agent (film)|Indian Agent]]'' (1948) as Dave Taylor\n* ''[[Gun Smugglers]]'' (1948) as Himself\n* ''[[Brothers in the Saddle]]'' (1949) as Tim Taylor\n* ''[[Rustlers (1949 film)|Rustlers]]'' (1949) as Dick McBride\n* ''[[Stagecoach Kid]]'' (1949) as Dave Collins\n* ''[[Masked Raiders]]'' (1949) as Himself\n* ''[[The Mysterious Desperado]]'' (1949) as Himself\n* ''[[Riders of the Range (1949 film)|Riders of the Range]]'' (1950) as Kansas Jones\n* ''[[Dynamite Pass]]'' (1950) as Ross Taylor\n* ''[[Storm Over Wyoming]]'' (1950) as Dave Saunders\n* ''[[Rider from Tucson]]'' (1950) as Dave Saunders\n* ''[[Border Treasure]]'' (1950) as Ed Porter\n* ''[[Rio Grande Patrol]]'' (1950) as Kansas\n* ''[[Law of the Badlands]]'' (1951) as Dave Saunders\n* ''[[Saddle Legion]]'' (1951) as Dave Saunders\n* ''[[Gunplay (film)|Gunplay]]'' (1951) as Himself\n* ''[[His Kind of Woman]]'' (1951) as Bill Lusk\n* ''[[Pistol Harvest]]'' (1951) as Tim\n* ''[[Hot Lead]]'' (1951) as Himself\n* ''[[Overland Telegraph (film)|Overland Telegraph]]'' (1951) as Himself\n* ''[[Trail Guide]]'' (1952) as Himself\n* ''[[Road Agent (1952 film)|Road Agent]]'' (1952) as Himself\n* ''[[Target (1952 film)|Target]]'' (1952) as Himself\n* ''[[Desert Passage (film)|Desert Passage]]'' (1952) as Himself\n* ''[[Chevron Theatre]]'' (1953, TV series, \"Adventure in Java\")\n* ''[[The Monster That Challenged the World]]'' (1957) as Lt. Cmdr. John 'Twill' Twillinger\n* ''[[The Yesterday Machine]]'' (1963) as Police Lt. Partane\n* ''[[The Virginian (TV series)|The Virginian]]'' (1969 TV show, \"A Woman of Stone\") as Abe Landeen\n* ''[[This Stuff'll Kill Ya!]]'' (1971) as Agent Clark (final film role)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Box office ranking==\nFor a number of years Holt was voted by US exhibitors as among the most popular Western stars in the country.\n* 1949 \u2013 4th<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article130795375 |title=WANTS PLASTER CAST OF GRABLE LEGS. |newspaper=[[The News (Adelaide)|The News]] |location=Adelaide |date=14 January 1950 |accessdate=4 January 2016 |page=8 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n* 1951 \u2013 3rd<ref>{{cite news|title=Public Pays Best For Escapist Fare|author=Richard L Coe|work=The Washington Post|location=Washington, D.C|date=29 Dec 1951|page=12}}</ref>\n* 1952 \u2013 5th<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article57310529 |title=COMEDIANS TOP FILM STAR POLL. |newspaper=[[The Morning Bulletin]] |location=Rockhampton, Qld. |date=27 December 1952 |accessdate=4 January 2016 |page=1 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n{{Commons category|Tim Holt}}\n* {{iMDb name|392529}}\n* {{Find a Grave|6512496}}\n* [http://theautry.org/the-colt-revolver-in-the-american-west/western-entertainers?artifact=93.141.4 The Colt Revolver in the American West\u2014Tim Holt's Single Action Army]\n* [http://offscreen.com/view/tim-holt-and-the-b-western Tom Stempel, \"Tim Holt and the B Western\", ''Off Screen Magazine'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holt, Tim}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Beverly Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Deaths from bone cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:United States Army Air Forces officers]]\n[[Category:RKO Pictures contract players]]\n[[Category:Male Western (genre) film actors]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American actor}}\n{{For|other people with the same name|Timothy Holt (disambiguation){{!}}Timothy Holt}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Tim Holt\n| image         = Tim Holt Western.jpg\n| caption       = Holt in 1948\n| birth_name    = Charles John Holt III\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1919|02|05}}\n| birth_place   = [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1973|02|15|1919|02|05}}\n| death_place   = [[Shawnee, Oklahoma|Shawnee]], [[Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| resting_place = Memory Lane Cemetery <br> [[Harrah, Oklahoma|Harrah]], [[Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| education     = [[Culver Academies|Culver Military Academy]]\n| occupation    = [[Actor]]\n| years_active  = 1927\u20131971\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Virginia Ashcroft|1938|1944|end=divorced}} <br> {{marriage|Alice Harrison|1944|1952|end=divorced}} <br> {{marriage|Birdee Stephens|1952|1973|end=died}}\n| children      = 4\n| parents       = [[Jack Holt (actor)|Jack Holt]] <br> Margaret Woods\n| relatives     = [[Jennifer Holt]] (sister)\n}}\n\n'''Charles John''' \"'''Tim'''\" '''Holt III''' (February 5, 1919 \u2013 February 15, 1973) was an [[Americans|American]] actor. He was a popular [[Western (genre)|Western]] star during the 1940s and early 1950s, appearing in forty-six [[B movie|B]] westerns released by [[RKO Pictures]].\n\nIn a career spanning more than four decades, Holt is best remembered for his roles in the films ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' (1942) and ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre (film)|The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]'' (1948).\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Jack Holt & Son.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Tim Holt and his father, actor Jack Holt (1921)]]\nTim Holt was born Charles John Holt III on February 5, 1919, in [[Beverly Hills, California]], the son of actor [[Jack Holt (actor)|Jack Holt]] and Margaret Woods.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|title=Tim Holt |work=The New York Times |date= |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/33051/Tim-Holt/biography |accessdate=October 12, 2012}}</ref>  During his early years, he accompanied his father on location, even appearing in an early silent film.<ref name=\"b-westerns\">{{cite web|title=Tim Holt |publisher=B-Westerns |url=http://www.b-westerns.com/holt1.htm |accessdate=October 12, 2012}}</ref> He was the inspiration for his father's book, ''Lance and His First Horse''.\n\nHolt was educated at [[Culver Military Academy]] in [[Culver, Indiana]], graduating in 1936.<ref name=\"b-westerns\"/> One of his classmates was [[Budd Boetticher]] who recalled Holt \"used to walk around in our suite of rooms there\u2026and he often had on his .38 revolvers and holster. He\u2019d walk up and down the hall in his bathrobe and practice drawing his guns. He\u2019d say, \u2018I\u2019m going to be a western star some day\u2019.\"<ref name=\"stempel\">{{cite web|url=http://offscreen.com/view/tim-holt-and-the-b-western|title=Tim Holt and the B Western|publisher=}}</ref> Immediately after graduation he went to work in the [[Hollywood]] film business.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\n==Acting career==\n===Walter Wanger===\nHolt was signed to a contract by [[Walter Wanger]] in January 1937.<ref>Graham, Sheilah. \"Schulberg Casts Sylvia Sidney in Krasna Feature\". ''Los Angeles Times'' (1923\u2013Current file). 07 January 1937: 8.</ref> Wanger was going to use him in ''Blockade'', but that film was postponed.<ref>\"Screen News Here and in Hollywood: Plans to Produce 'Personal History' Are Abandoned for the Present by Wanger \u2013 'Tropic Holiday' to Open, Bob Burns and Martha Raye to Be Featured in Picture at Paramount This Morning Of Local Origin, Special to the New York Times\". ''New York Times'' (1923\u2013Current file). 29 June 1938: 15.</ref>\n\nInstead he made his debut as [[Anne Shirley (actress)|Anne Shirley]]'s suitor in ''[[Stella Dallas (1937 film)|Stella Dallas]]'' (1937) for [[Sam Goldwyn]] \u2013 the same role that another film star's son, Douglas Fairbanks Jr., had played in the 1925 version.<ref>{{cite news|author=Schallert, Edwin|title=James Foran, Brother of Dick, Will Make Debut as Comedy Star: John Howard Latest Choice for 'Drummond'|work=Los Angeles Times|date=14 June 1937|page= 6}}</ref> When told he was given the role his father Jack said, \"Fine. Let's have one good actor in the family.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Star's Son Good Actor|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=27 Feb 1941|page= 12}}</ref> Wanger then cast him in ''[[I Met My Love Again]]'' (1938) and used him for a Technicolor Western, ''Gold is where you find It''. In the latter the ''Los Angeles Times'' said Holt \"confirms the favourable impression he gave\" in ''Stella Dallas''.<ref>Color Film Success at Box Office Lusk, Norbert|work=Los Angeles Times|date=19 Feb 1938|page=8}}</ref>\n\nRKO borrowed him for a western ''[[The Renegade Ranger]]'' (1938) supporting George O'Brien, then a leading star of B-westerns. Wanger wanted to star Holt opposite Henry Fonda and [[Louise Platt]] in an adaptation of [[Vincent Sheean]]'s ''Personal History''; however after the problems Wanger had making ''Blockade'' he decided to postpone the project. (It was later filmed as ''Foreign Correspondent''.) He lent Holt to Paramount to play the juvenile lead in ''[[Sons of the Legion]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=SCREEN NEWS HERE AND IN HOLLYWOOD: Plans to Produce 'Personal History' Are Abandoned for the Present by Wanger TROPIC HOLIDAY' TO OPEN Bob Burns and Martha Raye to Be Featured in Picture at Paramount This Morning Of Local Origin Special to THE NEW YORK TIMES..|work= New York Times|date=29 June 1938|page=15}}</ref> then RKO asked for him again in ''[[The Law West of Tombstone]]'', supporting [[Harry Carey (actor)|Harry Carey]].\n\nWanger then used Holt in the role of young Lieutenant Blanchard in the 1939 classic ''[[Stagecoach (1939 film)|Stagecoach]]''. At Universal he appeared in a story of his old alma mater, Culver Military Academy, ''[[The Spirit of Culver]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=COMINGS AND GOINGS.... NEWS OF STAGE AND SCREEN: Culver Opus Given Expert Supervision Gen. Gignilliat, Head of Academy, Handling Technique|author=Hopper, Hedda|work=Los Angeles Times|date=19 Feb 1939|page=C3}}</ref>\n\nHis contract with Wanger expired. RKO signed Holt to a seven-year contract in December 1938.<ref>Holt played young Lieutenant Blanchard in the 1939 classic ''[[Stagecoach (1939 film)|Stagecoach]]''.</ref><ref>\"Screen News Here and in Hollywood: Dick Powell, Joan Blondell to Leave Warners \u2013 Miss Lindsay in Mystery Play \u2013 Two Foreign Films Today 'Little Flower,' Made in France, and the Italian, 'Amore in Quarantena,' Will Open, Miss Lindsay Gets Lead, Coast Scripts Of Local Origin, Special to The New York Times\". ''New York Times'' (1923\u2013Current file). 12 December 1938: 26.</ref><ref name=Mott>Mott, Robert. \"Tim Holt, Actor in Western Films, Dies\", ''The Washington Post''. 17 February 1973: B6.</ref>\n\n===RKO Pictures===\n[[File:Fifth Avenue Girl 1939.JPG|thumb|upright=1.2|Lobby card for ''[[5th Ave Girl|5th Avenue Girl]]'' (1939)]]\n[[File:Laddie lobby card 3.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Lobby card for ''[[Laddie (1940 film)|Laddie]]'' (1940)]]\nRKO gave Holt his first lead, in the B-film ''[[The Rookie Cop]]''. It was popular and RKO put him in ''[[The Girl and the Gambler]]'', opposite [[Leo Carrillo]]. He was then cast as the romantic lead for the studio's biggest star, [[Ginger Rogers]], in ''[[5th Avenue Girl]]'' (1939). It was popular and the ''Los Angeles Times'' said Holt \"does unusually well in this\"<ref>{{cite news|title=FIFTH AVENUE GIRL' HITS HIGH SPOTS OF MIRTH, BUT UNEVEN|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=17 Aug 1939|page=8}}</ref> although the ''New York Times'' thought he \"seems a trifle young to be running a great corporation\".<ref>{{cite news|title=THE SCREEN: Slight Light Comedy Is RKO's Fifth Avenue Girl,' With Ginger Rogers, at the Radio City Music Hall|author=FRANK S|work=NUGENT. New York Times|location=New York, N.Y|date=25 Aug 1939|page=12}}</ref>\n\nHe was meant to play the eldest son in ''[[Three Sons]]'' (1939) with Edward Ellis<ref>{{cite news|title=DRAMA: Betty Field Awarded New Paramount Lead|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=15 June 1939|page=8}}</ref> but he was withdrawn and replaced by [[William Gargan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=SCREEN NEWS HERE AND IN HOLLYWOOD: Universal to Start 'One Hour to Live,' 'Missing Evidence' and 'Rio' on Monday 'WATERFRONT' AT GLOBE 'To the Victor,' 'Orage' and 'La Kermesse Heroique' Among Films Listed for Today Raft Signs With Warner Spewaks to Write for McCarey|author=DOUGLAS W CHURCHILL Special to THE NEW YORK TIMES..|work= New York Times|date=15 July 1939|page=14}}</ref> He was also meant to star in a Western, ''Silver City'', with [[Betty Grable]], but it was not made.<ref>{{cite news|title=SCREEN NEWS HERE AND IN HOLLYWOOD: Three Pictures Are Placed on RKO Schedule--Cukor May Direct 'Susan and God' MAINTAIN FILM OUTPUT Columbia Studios Will Spend $5,000,000 More This Year on Production, Cohn Says Ruby Keeler Out of Film George Cukor May Direct|author=DOUGLAS W CHURCHILL Special to THE NEW YORK TIMES..|work= New York Times|date=12 Sep 1939|page=35}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1940 it was announced Holt and [[Ginger Rogers]] would be reunited in an adaptation of ''[[The Enchanted Cottage (play)|The Enchanted Cottage]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Americans to Sponsor Production in England: Durbin British Winner New Ameche, Faye Film Sandy's Sex 'Decided' Newcomer Awarded Role Gail Patrick Assigned|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=4 Jan 1940|page=13}}</ref> The film was not made until [[The Enchanted Cottage (1945 film)|several years later]] with different stars. Instead he was assigned to play Fritz Robinson in the studio's expensive adaptation of ''Swiss Family Robinson'' (1940). He also played the lead in ''Laddie'' (1940); the ''Los Angeles Times'' called him \"engaging and capable\".<ref>{{cite news|title='Laddie' Engaging Picture|author=G K|work=Los Angeles Times|date=13 Sep 1940|page=21}}</ref> ''Swiss Family Robinson'' was a financial failure and ''Laddie'' was not particularly popular.\n\n====Western star====\nDuring the late 1930s, [[George O'Brien (actor)|George O'Brien]] had made a number of low budget Westerns for RKO. Holt later recalled, \"I believe George O\u2019Brien quit over money so RKO needed another Western star and I was put forward.\"<ref name=\"interview\"/>\n\nIn early 1940, RKO announced Holt would make six low budget B-Westerns, starting with ''Wagon Train'' with Martha O'Driscoll.<ref>{{cite news|title=53 FEATURE FILMS SCHEDULED BY RKO: 1940\u201341 Plans Announced at Sales Convention of Firm Now in Session Here 190 SHORTS ON PROGRAM Gallup Survey of the Audience Interest in Pictures Is Being Conducted for Company Plans Research Institute Film by Orson Welles}}</ref> O'Driscoll and Holt were meant to reteam in ''Sir Piegan Passes'' but it was not made.<ref>{{cite news|title=SCREEN NEWS HERE AND IN HOLLYWOOD: 'Kiss Me Again' Purchased by Ernst Lubitsch, Producer for United Artists 'GHOST BREAKERS' OPENING Paramount Attraction Starts Today--'Spies in the Air' Is Rialto Offering Special to THE NEW YORK TIMES..|work= New York Times|date=3 July 1940|page=15}}</ref> Instead Holt appeared in ''[[The Fargo Kid]]''.\n\nUniversal borrowed him to play [[Charles Boyer]]'s son in ''Back Street'' (1941). The ''Los Angeles Times'' said Holt had \"some splendid scenes towards the end\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Censor-Daring Theme Well Presented|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=5 Feb 1941|page=A10}}</ref> Then it was back to Westerns: ''[[Robbers of the Range]]'' (1941), ''[[Along the Rio Grande]]'' (1941), ''[[Cyclone on Horseback]]'' (1941) and ''[[Six-Gun Gold]]'' (1941).\n\nHolt usually played a cowboy who had one or two friends, who occasionally sang. From 1940\u201342 he made 18 Westerns. His first sidekick was [[Ray Whitley (singer-songwriter, born 1901)|Ray Whitley]], who was slightly older than Holt, and who would usually sing a song or two in each film. The other sidekick was a character \"Whopper\" played by [[Emmett Lynn]] and then [[Lee White (actor)|Lee White]]. 1942 they were replaced by [[Cliff Edwards]] as Ike.\n\nAuthor Tom Stempel later recalled:\n<blockquote>Holt, unlike many other B western stars, played characters not named Tim Holt. From his debut in 1934 [[Gene Autry]] always played \"Gene Autry\" and after 1941 [[Roy Rogers]] always played \"Roy Rogers,\" but Holt's names varied, even if the basic character he played is the same...  In these early films Tim's jobs were diverse. While [[Hopalong Cassidy]] was always the foreman of the Bar 20 Ranch, Tim played a cowboy, a Treasury agent, a Texas Ranger, or a number of other occupations. The characters were pretty much the same: Tim, with his boyish good looks, is drawn into situations where he must right some wrongs. Holt had a charming personality on the screen, which made him one of the top western stars from 1940 to 1943.<ref name=\"stempel\"/></blockquote>\n\nThe Westerns proved popular and Holt wound up making six more: ''[[The Bandit Trail]]'' (1941), ''[[Dude Cowboy]]'' (1941), ''[[Riding the Wind]]'' (1942), ''[[Land of the Open Range]]'' (1942), ''[[Come on Danger]]'' (1942) and ''[[Thundering Hoofs]]'' (1942).\n\n====''The Magnificent Ambersons''====\n[[File:The-Magnificent-Ambersons-7.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|[[Joseph Cotten]], [[Anne Baxter]] and Tim Holt in ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' (1942)]]\n\nHolt's career received a boost in September 1941<ref>{{cite news|title=Previews Reveal Fitful Start for New Season: 'Yank' Leads in Potency Welles Casts Tim Holt Costumes Tempt Power Good Things for Ginger Goldwyn Lot Hyphenated|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=18 Sep 1941|page=A11}}</ref> when [[Orson Welles]] cast him as the lead in his second film, ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' (1942).  \"It was a lucky decision\", Welles later said, calling Holt \"one of the most interesting actors that's ever been in American movies\".<ref name=\"Welles TIOW\">{{cite book |last1=Welles |first1=Orson |authorlink1=Orson Welles |last2=Bogdanovich |first2=Peter |authorlink2=Peter Bogdanovich |last3=Rosenbaum |first3=Jonathan |authorlink3=Jonathan Rosenbaum |title=[[This is Orson Welles]] |publisher=HarperCollins |location=New York |date=1992 |isbn=0-06-016616-9}}</ref>{{Rp|113}} The ''Washington Post'' thought Holt \"gives an excellent account of himself\". The ''New York Times'' said he \"draws out all the meanness in George's character which is precisely what the role demands.\"<ref>{{cite news|title='The Magnificent Ambersons,' Welles's Film From Novel by Tarkington, Opens at Capitol -- 'The Big Street' at Palace|author=T.M.P.. |work=New York Times|date=14 Aug 1942|page=13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Magnificent Ambersons' Suffer Decline at Keith's: New Orson Welles Film a Glorified Tragedy That Sacrifices Dramatic Power to New Photographic Splendor and Odd Technique|author=|work=The Washington Post|date=17 July 1942|page=12}}</ref> (In 1965 Welles wanted to reshoot the ending with those of the original cast still alive, including Holt, but it did not eventuate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alexander Signed for POW Movie|author=|work=Los Angeles Times|date=10 Dec 1965|page=d19}}</ref>)\n\nRKO announced they had purchased two stories for Holt, ''Five of Spades'' (which became ''[[The Avenging Rider]]'') and ''Adventures of Salt Valley''. He was always announced for ''There Goes Lona Henry''.<ref>{{cite news|title=DRAMA: Welles to Act Turk Spy in 'Journey Into Fear' Paramount Signs McCrea 'Spitfire' Release Set Subjects Named for Holt Lindsay Slate Crowded Brent Returning Monday|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=7 Jan 1942|page=8}}</ref> Holt was going to enter the army, so RKO quickly put him in six more Westerns: ''[[Bandit Ranger]]'' (1942), ''[[Red River Robin Hood]]'' (1942), ''[[Pirates of the Prairie]]'' (1942), ''[[Fighting Frontier]]'' (1943), ''[[Sagebrush Law]]'' (1943) and ''[[The Avenging Rider]]'' (1942).<ref name=\"rko story\">Richard Jewell & Vernon Harbin, ''The RKO Story.'' New Rochelle, New York: Arlington House, 1982. p175</ref>\n\nHis entry into the [[U.S. Army Air Forces]] was delayed long enough so that Holt could star in ''[[Hitler's Children (1943 film)|Hitler's Children]]'' (1943).<ref>{{cite news|title=SCREEN NEWS HERE AND IN HOLLYWOOD: United Artists to Take Over 11 Finished Paramount Films and Distribute Them NEW PICTURE AT CARNEGIE 'Loves of Edgar Allan Poe' Will Open Today -- 'You Can't Take It With You' Revived By Telephone to THE NEW YORK TIMES..|work= New York Times|date=19 Sep 1942|page=9}}</ref> He was called to active duty during the making of the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=HEDDA HOPPER Says: New Picture Brings Fame to Producer|author=|work=Los Angeles Times|date=28 Mar 1943|page=C2}}</ref> However it was one of RKO's most profitable movies during the war.\n\n====War service====\nHolt became a decorated combat veteran of World War II, flying in the [[Asiatic-Pacific Theater|Pacific Theatre]] with the [[United States Army Air Forces]] as a [[B-29]] bombardier.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> He was wounded over Tokyo on the last day of the war and was awarded a Purple Heart.<ref>Hopper, Hedda. \"Looking at Hollywood\". ''Los Angeles Times'' (1923\u2013Current file). 18 October 1945: 10.</ref>  He was also a recipient of the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]].<ref>http://www.39th.org/39th/aerial/62nd/crew59dfc.html \u2013 retrieved August 30, 2016.</ref><ref>http://airforce.togetherweserved.com/usaf/servlet/tws.webapp.WebApps?cmd=ShadowBoxProfile&type=Person&ID=120796 retrieved August 20, 2016</ref>\n\n===Post-war===\n[[File:Tim Holt in The Treasure of the Sierra Madre trailer.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Tim Holt in the trailer for ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre (film)|The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]'' (1948)]]\nFollowing the war, Holt returned to films and went back to RKO. According to his biographer David Rothel, \"No more was he the callow, youthful cowboy with big, silly grin on his face. Now he exuded a steady, serious no-nonsense type of mature cowboy who was less impulsive, more contemporary, and somewhat \u2018world weary.\"<ref name=\"stempel\"/><ref>Rothel, David. ''Tim Holt'' (1994). Madison, North Carolina: Empire Publishing Company</ref> Tom Stempel argues that \"While Holt had lost his baby fat during the war, he still had a wonderful grin and cute dimples. He used the mixture of charm and seriousness very well.\"<ref name=\"stempel\"/>\n\nHis post-war career began well when 20th Century Fox borrowed him to play [[Virgil Earp]] alongside [[Henry Fonda]]'s [[Wyatt Earp]] in the [[John Ford]] western ''[[My Darling Clementine]]'' (1946). For RKO he appeared in a series of [[Zane Gray]] adaptations: ''[[Thunder Mountain (1947 film)|Thunder Mountain]]'' (1947),<ref>{{cite news|title=Ford Closes Four-Film Deal; 'Fugitive' First|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=2 Oct 1946|page=A3}}</ref> ''[[Under the Tonto Rim (1947 film)|Under the Tonto Rim]]'' (1947) and ''[[Wild Horse Mesa (1947 film)|Wild Horse Mesa]]'' (1947). He also made ''[[Western Heritage]]'' (1947), which was an original screenplay. The budgets were around $100,000 a film, making them among the more expensive B Westerns.<ref>{{cite news|title=Horse Operas Western Films Are Hollywood's Sure-Fire Financial Winners: Range From $40,000 'Oaters' To $1.5 Million 'Epics'; Are 25% of Film Output Action, Danger and Chase Horse Operas: Western Films Are Hollywood's Financial Winners|author=JOSEPH W|work=TAYLOR Staff Correspondent of THE WALL STREET JOURNAL. Wall Street Journal|location=New York, N.Y|date=15 Apr 1948|page=1}}</ref>\n\n====''The Treasure of the Sierra Madre''====\nHolt was next borrowed by Warner Bros for the role for which he is probably best remembered \u2014 that of Bob Curtin to [[Humphrey Bogart]]'s Fred C. Dobbs in [[John Huston]]'s ''[[The Treasure of the Sierra Madre (film)|The Treasure of the Sierra Madre]]'' (1948), about two friends who team up to prospect for gold, only to have greed tear apart their partnership. Holt's father also appeared in a small part.  Tim Holt tended to be overshone in reviews by Bogart and [[Walter Huston]]. However the ''Chicago Daily Tribune'' said he was very likeable\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Hustons Do Superb Job in This Film: TREASURE OF THE SIERRA MADRE\" THE CAST|author=TINEE, MAE|work=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=19 Mar 1948|page=a7}}</ref> The ''Los Angeles Times'' said Holt \"gives a rare and sincere impression of character in his performance.\"<ref>{{cite news|title='Treasure' Manifests Adult Power|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=15 Jan 1948|page=18}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''Los Angeles Times'', Holt's casting in ''Madre'' impressed RKO studio chief [[Dore Schary]] who announced \"expanding plans\" for the actor, looking to cast him in films other than Westerns. He also promised a bigger budget for Holt's Westerns such as ''[[The Arizona Ranger]]'' (1948), which cast him opposite his father.<ref>{{cite news|title=DRAMA AND FILM: Colbert Quits Capra Feature, Hepburn Cast|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=Los Angeles Times|date=11 Oct 1947|page=A5}}</ref> However the films remained undistinguished: ''[[Guns of Hate]]'' (1948), ''[[Indian Agent (film)|Indian Agent]]'' (1948) and ''[[Gun Smugglers]]'' (1948).\n\nHis most frequent director was [[Lesley Selander]] and his sidekick in more than 25 of these movies was [[Richard Martin (RKO actor)|Richard Martin]]. Martin played Chito Jose Gonzales Bustamente Rafferty, a character created by writer Jack Wagner for the [[Bombardier (film)|1943 film ''Bombardier'']] and who had appeared in some [[Robert Mitchum]] westerns before being put into Tim Holt films. Stempel:\n<blockquote>The chemistry between Holt and Martin was immediate. Tim was entertained by Chito's constant pursuit of the ladies, which gave Holt a variety of reactions to play: amusement, surprise, slight irritation, bafflement at the hopelessness of Chito's attempted conquests. Unlike Hopalong Cassidy's young sidekick Lucky, who just mooned after girls, Chito was active, which was a lot more interesting to watch, especially with Tim's reactions. Chito was not just a lovesick fool, but also ready for action. As he explained his name, his mother was Spanish, and the Spanish is for loving, and his father was Irish, which is for fighting. Chito performed the crucial functions of a B western movie sidekick: he was somebody with whom the hero could discuss the plot, and he provided some comedy relief. In the 47-52 series, the comic relief is verbal rather than visual, and often a part of the story. The directors can shoot both Chito's flirting and Tim's reaction in one shot. Unlike other B westerns, such as those Holts with Cliff Edwards, the movie does not have to stop while the comic does his routine. It makes for much smoother flowing films.<ref name=\"stempel\"/></blockquote>\nIn 1948 Tim Holt also featured as the hero of a series of comic books<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westernclippings.com/comics/timholt_comicbookcowboys.shtml|title=Tim Holt - Comic Book Cowboys, by Boyd Magers|first=Donna|last=Magers|website=www.westernclippings.com}}</ref>\n\nHowever that year ''[[Brothers in the Saddle]]'' (1948) recorded a loss of $35,000<ref name=\"stempel\"/> as the growth of TV and decline in cinema audiences started to cut into Holt's market.\n\n===Later Movies===\nDore Schary left RKO in 1948 and the new management was not keen to cast Holt in anything other than Westerns: ''[[Rustlers (1949 film)|Rustlers]]'' (1949), ''[[Stagecoach Kid]]'' (1949), ''[[Masked Raiders]]'' (1949), ''[[The Mysterious Desperado]]'' (1949) and ''[[Riders of the Range (1949 film)|Riders of the Range]]'' (1949). The latter lost $50,000.<ref>Richard Jewell & Vernon Harbin, ''The RKO Story.'' New Rochelle, New York: Arlington House, 1982. p240</ref>\n\nThe Westerns continued: ''[[Dynamite Pass]]'' (1950), ''[[Storm over Wyoming]]'' (1950), ''[[Rider from Tucson]]'' (1950), ''[[Border Treasure]]'' (1950) and ''[[Rio Grande Patrol]]'' (1950). ''[[Law of the Badlands]]'' (1951) was the cheapest Tim Holt vehicle since the war years, made for $98,000, but still recorded a loss of $20,000.<ref>Richard Jewell & Vernon Harbin, ''The RKO Story.'' New Rochelle, New York: Arlington House, 1982. p255</ref>\n\nAfter ''[[Gunplay (film)|Gunplay]]'' (1951), ''[[Saddle Legion]]'' (1951) had a higher quality female lead \u2013 [[Dorothy Malone]] \u2013 and then Holt unexpectedly appeared in an \"A\", supporting [[Robert Mitchum]] and [[Jane Russell]] in ''[[His Kind of Woman]]'' for director [[John Farrow]].\n\nIn September 1950 it was announced Holt would support [[Montgomery Clift]] for director [[Nicholas Ray]] in ''[[The Flying Leathernecks]]'' (1951) but the film was made without either actor.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tim Holt Leatherneck; Directors Pick Huston; King Bros. Celebrating|author=Scheuer, Philip K|work=Los Angeles Times|date=5 Sep 1950|page=A11}}</ref>\n\nInstead it was back to Westerns: ''[[Pistol Harvest]]'' (1951), ''[[Hot Lead]]'' (1951), ''[[Overland Telegraph (film)|Overland Telegraph]]'' (1951), ''[[Trail Guide]]'' (1952), ''[[Road Agent (1952 film)|Road Agent]]'' (1952), ''[[Target (1952 film)|Target]]'' (1952), and finally ''[[Desert Passage (film)|Desert Passage]]'' (1952). The latter lost $30,000 so it was decided to end the series.<ref name=\"stempel\"/>\n\nHe made a TV appearance for ''[[Chevron Theatre]]''.\n\n==Later career==\nHolt had been to Oklahoma in 1947 with a rodeo, and met the woman who became his final wife. When his movie series ended he decided to move to Oklahoma for good. \"I never did like Hollywood that much\u2026 there was nothing magical about it for me\", he said.<ref name=\"interview\">{{cite web|url=https://fiftieswesterns.wordpress.com/2013/11/12/tim-holt-tuesday-2-john-booker-interviews-tim-holt-1970/|title=Tim Holt Tuesday #2: John Brooker Interviews Tim Holt, 1970|date=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe was absent from the screen for five years until he starred in a [[horror film]], ''[[The Monster That Challenged the World]]'', in 1957, Holt said it \"wasn\u2019t too bad a picture at all\".<ref name=\"interview\"/> Over the next 16 years, he appeared in only two more motion pictures as well as an episode of ''The Virginian''. He was going to make a sequel to ''Treasure of the Sierra Madre'' with [[Nick Adams (actor, born 1931)|Nick Adams]] but Adams died.<ref name=\"interview\"/>\n\nHowever he kept busy managing theatres and making personal appearances.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> He got a degree in animal nutrition from Iowa, worked as a builder, produced rodeos, staged and performed Western music jamborees, and worked as an advertising manager for a radio station from 1962 onwards.<ref name=Mott/> Holt later said of this period:\n<blockquote>Do you realize that this is the first time in my life that I can make my own decisions and do what I want to do? First it was my parents who told me what to do, then RKO told me what to do, then I went into the service and Uncle Sam told me what to do. I came back out and RKO still told me what to do. This is the first time I have not been under somebody's thumb in my life.[http://comicvine.gamespot.com/red-mask/4005-1345/] <ref name=\"stempel\"/></blockquote>\n\n==Personal life==\nHolt was married three times and had four children: three sons (one from his first marriage), and a daughter.\n\nTim Holt died from [[bone cancer]] on February 15, 1973<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19730216&id=OYMuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=qqEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4730,4332280|title=The Montreal Gazette - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com}}</ref> in [[Shawnee, Oklahoma]], where he had been managing a [[radio station]]. He was interred in the Memory Lane Cemetery in [[Harrah, Oklahoma]]. The street where he and his wife had lived in Harrah was subsequently renamed Tim Holt Drive in his honor.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nRobert Mott of the ''Washington Post'' later said of Holt:\n<blockquote>Holt was the hero, strong and silent and always more comfortable in the presence of boots and saddles, horses and he-men, than with the heroine \u2013 though he almost invariably ended up marrying her... Like many sons of famous entertainers, Tim Holt never achieved the stature of his father, and projected a bland image in contrast  with the elder Holt's strong characterisation.<ref name=Mott/></blockquote>\nIn 1991, Tim Holt was inducted posthumously into the [[Western Performers Hall of Fame]] at the [[National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum]] in [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]]. In 1992, the [[Golden Boot Awards]] honored Holt for his lifetime contributions to western cinema.\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col}}\n* ''[[French Dressing (1927 film)|French Dressing]]'' (1927) (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Vanishing Pioneer]]'' (1928) as John Ballard, Age 7\n* ''[[History Is Made at Night (1937 film)|History Is Made at Night]]'' (1937) as S.O.S. Radio Operator (uncredited)\n* ''[[Stella Dallas (1937 film)|Stella Dallas]]'' (1937) as Richard Grosvenor\n* ''[[I Met My Love Again]]'' (1938) as Budge Williams\n* ''[[Gold Is Where You Find It]]'' (1938) as Lance Ferris\n* ''[[The Renegade Ranger]]'' (1938) as Larry Corwin\n* ''[[Sons of the Legion]]'' (1938) as Steven Scott\n* ''[[The Law West of Tombstone]]'' (1938) as Ted aka The Tonto Kid\n* ''[[Stagecoach (1939 film)|Stagecoach]]'' (1939) as Lieutenant Blanchard\n* ''[[The Spirit of Culver]]'' (1939) as Capt. Wilson\n* ''[[The Rookie Cop]]'' (1939) as Clem Maitland\n* ''[[The Girl and the Gambler]]'' (1939) as Johnny Powell\n* ''[[5th Ave Girl]]'' (1939) as Tim Borden\n* ''[[Laddie (1940 film)|Laddie]]'' (1940) as Laddie S