{"title_page": "Cathay Williams", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name = Cathay Williams\n|image = Cathay Williams Only Woman Buffalo Soldier U.S. Army.jpg\n|caption = Painting of Cathay Williams by William Jennings from the U.S. Army Profiles of Bravery\n|birth_date=September 1844\n|death_date= {{death year and age|1893|1842}}\n|birth_place=[[Independence, Missouri]]\n|death_place=[[Trinidad, Colorado]]\n|resting_place = \n|residence = \n|nationality= American\n|citizenship = \n| other_names = John Williams, William Cathay\n|occupation    = soldier, cook, seamstress\n|placeofburial=\n|placeofburial_label= \n|nickname=\n|module= {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n|allegiance = {{flag|United States of America}}\n|serviceyears= 1866-1868\n|rank= private\n|commands= \n|unit= 38th U.S. Infantry Regiment, U.S. Army (Buffalo soldier)\n| battles =\n|relations=\n|laterwork=}}\n| years_active              = \n| employer                  =  U.S. government, self-employed\n| known_for                 = \n| notable_works             = \n| style                     = \n| influences                = \n| influenced                = \n| home_town                 = \n| title                     = \n| movement                  = \n| religion                  = <!-- Bonney was not a member of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.  See D. Michael Quinn reference  -->\n| denomination              =\n| parents                   = \n| spouse                    =\n| children                  = \n| family                    = \n| relatives                 =\n| awards                    = \n| signature                 = \n| signature_alt             = \n| signature_size            = \n| website                   = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| footnotes                 = \n}}\n\n'''Cathay Williams''' (September 1844 &ndash; 1893) was an [[African-American]] soldier who enlisted in the [[United States Army]] under the pseudonym '''William Cathay'''. She was the first [[Black people|Black]] woman to enlist, and the only documented to serve in the United States Army posing as a man.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jWPL8OrbbacC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Cathy Williams: From Slave to Female Buffalo Soldier|last=Tucker|first=Phillip Thomas|date=2002-01-01|publisher=Stackpole Books|isbn=9780811703406|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWilliams was born in Independence, Missouri, to a free man and a woman in slavery, making her legal status also that of a slave. During her adolescence, Williams worked as a house slave on the Johnson plantation on the outskirts of Jefferson City, Missouri. In 1861 Union forces occupied Jefferson City in the early stages of the [[American Civil War|Civil War]]. At that time, captured slaves were officially designated by the Union as \"contraband,\" and many were forced to serve in military support roles such as cooks, laundresses, or nurses.\n\n==American Civil War==\nIt is possible that Cathay Williams was present at the [[Battle of Pea Ridge]] and the [[Red River Campaign]]. There is no evidence, however, that supports any claims to her service in the Civil War, although a soldier named \"Finis Cathay\" did enlist in the 32nd Missouri Infantry as early as 1862 and participated in most of the major campaigns in the west, including the Siege of Vicksburg and Sherman's March to the Sea, before helping to force Joseph E. Johnston's last Confederate army into surrender in North Carolina. This unit's history parallels many of the wartime stories told of Cathay Williams, including its presence in Washington, D.C., at the final Grand Review on May 24, 1865.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/civilwar/search-soldiers-detail.htm?soldierId=044C118C-DC7A-DF11-BF36-B8AC6F5D926A|title=Soldier Details - Cathay, Finis E|website=www.nps.gov}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. Army service==\nDespite the prohibition against women serving in the military, Cathay Williams enlisted in the United States Regular Army under the false name of \"William Cathay\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Amazons to Fighter Pilots - A Biographical Dictionary of Military Women|last=Pennington|first=Reina|publisher=Greenwood Press|year=2003|isbn=0-313-32708-4|location=Westport, Connecticut|pages=482\u2013483}}</ref> on November 15, 1866, at [[St. Louis, Missouri]], for a three-year engagement, passing herself off as a man. She was assigned to the [[38th Infantry Regiment (United States)|38th United States Infantry Regiment]] after she passed a cursory medical examination.<ref name=\":0\" /> Only two others are known to have been privy to the deception, her cousin and a friend, both of whom were fellow soldiers in her regiment.\n\nShortly after her enlistment, Williams contracted smallpox, was hospitalized and rejoined her unit, which by then was posted in [[New Mexico]]. Possibly due to the effects of smallpox, the New Mexico heat, or the cumulative effects of years of marching, her body began to show signs of strain. She was frequently hospitalized. The post surgeon finally discovered she was a woman, and informed the post commander. She was discharged from the Army by her commanding officer, Captain Charles E. Clarke, on October 14, 1868.\n\n==Post-military service years==\nCathay Williams went to work as a cook at [[Fort Union, New Mexico]], and later moved to [[Pueblo, Colorado]]. Williams married, but it ended disastrously when her husband stole her money and a team of horses. Williams had him arrested. She next moved to [[Trinidad, Colorado]], where she made her living as a seamstress. She may also have owned a boarding house. It was at this time that Williams' story first became public. A reporter from St. Louis heard rumors of an African-American woman who had served in the army, and came to interview her. Her life and military service narrative was published in ''The St. Louis Daily Times'' on January 2, 1876.\n\n[[File:Cathay Williams Pension 002.jpg|thumb|right|U.S. Army Pension records for Cathay Williams]]\n\nIn late 1889 or early 1890, Cathay Williams entered a local hospital where she remained for some time, and in June 1891, applied for a disability pension based on her military service. The nature of her illness and disability are unknown.  There was precedent for granting a pension to female soldiers. [[Deborah Sampson]] in 1816, [[Anna Maria Lane]], and Mary Hayes McCauley (better known as [[Molly Pitcher]]) had been granted pensions for their service in the [[American Revolutionary War]].\n\n==Declining health and death==\nIn September 1893, a doctor employed by the [[Pension Bureau|U.S. Pension Bureau]] examined Cathay Williams. Despite the fact that she suffered from [[neuralgia]] and [[diabetes]], she had all her toes amputated, and could only walk with a crutch, the doctor decided she did not qualify for disability payments. Her application was rejected.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Kwrf0SAM0hQC&lpg=PA33&ots=W0Jkx63pl2&dq=%22Female%20Buffalo%20Soldier%22%20by%20William%20Jennings&pg=PA33#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Voices of the Buffalo Soldier: Records, reports, and recollections of military life and service in the West'']. Edited by Frank N. Schubert. Albuquerque: University of New Mexico Press, 2003, p. 33.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.archives.gov/id/20848612|title=Disapproved Pension Application File for Cathay Williams (aka William Cathay), 38th U.S. Infantry Regiment, Company A (SO-1032593)|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe exact date of Williams' death is unknown, but it is assumed she died shortly after being denied a pension, probably sometime in 1893. Her simple grave marker would have been made of wood and deteriorated long ago. Thus her final resting place is now unknown.\n\n==Honors==\nIn 2016, a bronze bust of Cathay Williams, featuring information about her and with a small rose garden around it, was unveiled outside the [[Richard Allen Cultural Center]] in Leavenworth, Kansas.<ref>{{cite web|last=Davismirandadavis |first=Miranda |url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/local/article91412232.html |title=Monument to female Buffalo Soldier is dedicated in Leavenworth &#124; The Kansas City Star |publisher=Kansascity.com |date=2016-07-22 |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the Private Cathay Williams monument bench was unveiled on the Walk of Honor at the [[National Infantry Museum]].<ref>{{cite news  |url=https://www.wtvm.com/story/37527852/buffalo-soldiers-honor-first-female-documented-us-army-soldier/|title=Buffalo Soldiers honor first female, documented U.S. Army soldier |work=WTVM |date=17 February 2018 |accessdate=8 April 2020|last=Gunn|first=Olivia }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of African American firsts|African-American firsts]]\n*[[List of wartime crossdressers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.goarmy.com/bhm/profiles_williams.jsp | title=Profiles in Courage: Cathay Williams aka William Cathay |last=|first=| year=2008 | publisher=United States Army | author= | work=Heroes Among Us | accessdate=2008-11-13 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080616094119/http://www.goarmy.com/bhm/profiles_williams.jsp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-06-16}}\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.blackpast.org/?q=aaw/williams-cathay-1850 | title=Williams, Cathay (1850- ) | year=2008 | publisher=BlackPast.org  | author= Ramona L. Rand-Caplan (ed.)| work=African American History in the American West | accessdate=2008-11-13}}\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.buffalosoldier.net/CathayWilliamsFemaleBuffaloSoldierWithDocuments.htm | title=Female Buffalo Soldier- With Documents | date=25 June 2006 |website=| publisher=Buffalo Soldier.net | author=Stanford L. Davis | accessdate=2007-07-30}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.aframnews.com/html/2003-03-26/lead3.htm|title=William Cathay|date=3 September 2005|work=African-American News & Issues|accessdate=2007-01-15|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927151552/http://www.aframnews.com/html/2003-03-26/lead3.htm|archivedate=27 September 2007}}\n*{{cite web | url=https://www.poets.org/poetsorg/poem/ballad-cathay-williams-william-cathay | title=The Ballad of Cathay Williams William Cathay | year=2012 |website=| publisher=Poets.org  | author=Shane McCrae | accessdate=2012-11-27}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.army.mil/africanamericans/profiles/williams.html African Americans in the U.S. Army, Profiles of Bravery: Cathay Williams - U.S. Army website]\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last1=Glasrud |first1=Bruce |last2=Searles |first2=Michael |title=Buffalo soldiers in the West : a Black soldiers anthology |date=2007 |publisher=College Station, Tex. |location=Texas A & M University Press |isbn=978-1-60344-449-1 |edition=1st |oclc=607825144 }}\n\n{{Refend}}\n{{Buffalo Soldiers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Cathy}}\n[[Category:1844 births]]\n[[Category:1892 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American female military personnel]]\n[[Category:People from Independence, Missouri]]\n[[Category:African Americans in the American Old West]]\n[[Category:African Americans in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:African-American chefs]]\n[[Category:American slaves]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Soldiers]]\n[[Category:People of Missouri in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:People of the American Old West]]\n[[Category:Female wartime cross-dressers in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:American women chefs]]\n[[Category:Chefs from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Chefs from Missouri]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name = Cathay Williams\n|image = Cathay Williams Only Woman Buffalo Soldier U.S. Army.jpg\n|caption = Painting of Cathay Williams by William Jennings from the U.S. Army Profiles of Bravery\n|birth_date=September 1844\n|death_date= {{death year and age|1893|1842}}\n|birth_place=[[Independence, Missouri]]\n|death_place=[[Trinidad, Colorado]]\n|resting_place = \n|residence = \n|nationality= American\n|citizenship = \n| other_names = John Williams, William Cathay\n|occupation    = soldier, cook, seamstress\n|placeofburial=\n|placeofburial_label= \n|nickname=\n|module= {{Infobox military person|embed=yes\n|allegiance = {{flag|United States of America}}\n|serviceyears= 1866-1868\n|rank= private\n|commands= \n|unit= 38th U.S. Infantry Regiment, U.S. Army (Buffalo soldier)\n| battles =\n|relations=\n|laterwork=}}\n| years_active              = \n| employer                  =  U.S. government, self-employed\n| known_for                 = \n| notable_works             = \n| style                     = \n| influences                = \n| influenced                = \n| home_town                 = \n| title                     = \n| movement                  = \n| religion                  = <!-- Bonney was not a member of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.  See D. Michael Quinn reference  -->\n| denomination              =\n| parents                   = \n| spouse                    =\n| children                  = \n| family                    = \n| relatives                 =\n| awards                    = \n| signature                 = \n| signature_alt             = \n| signature_size            = \n| website                   = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| footnotes                 = \n}}\n\n'''Cathay Williams''' (September 1844 &ndash; 1893) was an [[African-American]] soldier who enlisted in the [[United States Army]] under the pseudonym '''William Cathay'''. She was the first [[Black people|Black]] woman to enlist, and the only documented to serve in the United States Army posing as a man.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jWPL8OrbbacC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Cathy Williams: From Slave to Female Buffalo Soldier|last=Tucker|first=Phillip Thomas|date=2002-01-01|publisher=Stackpole Books|isbn=9780811703406|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWilliams was born in Independence, Missouri, to a free man and a woman in slavery, making her legal status also that of a slave. During her adolescence, Williams worked as a house slave on the Johnson plantation on the outskirts of Jefferson City, Missouri. In 1861 Union forces occupied Jefferson City in the early stages of the [[American Civil War|Civil War]]. At that time, captured slaves were officially designated by the Union as \"contraband,\" and many were forced to serve in military support roles such as cooks, laundresses, or nurses.\n\n==American Civil War==\nIt is possible that Cathay Williams was present at the [[Battle of Pea Ridge]] and the [[Red River Campaign]]. There is no evidence, however, that supports any claims to her service in the Civil War, although a soldier named \"Finis Cathay\" did enlist in the 32nd Missouri Infantry as early as 1862 and participated in most of the major campaigns in the west, including the Siege of Vicksburg and Sherman's March to the Sea, before helping to force Joseph E. Johnston's last Confederate army into surrender in North Carolina. This unit's history parallels many of the wartime stories told of Cathay Williams, including its presence in Washington, D.C., at the final Grand Review on May 24, 1865.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/civilwar/search-soldiers-detail.htm?soldierId=044C118C-DC7A-DF11-BF36-B8AC6F5D926A|title=Soldier Details - Cathay, Finis E|website=www.nps.gov}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. Army service==\nDespite the prohibition against women serving in the military, Cathay Williams enlisted in the United States Regular Army under the false name of \"William Cathay\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Amazons to Fighter Pilots - A Biographical Dictionary of Military Women|last=Pennington|first=Reina|publisher=Greenwood Press|year=2003|isbn=0-313-32708-4|location=Westport, Connecticut|pages=482\u2013483}}</ref> on November 15, 1866, at [[St. Louis, Missouri]], for a three-year engagement, passing herself off as a man. She was assigned to the [[38th Infantry Regiment (United States)|38th United States Infantry Regiment]] after she passed a cursory medical examination.<ref name=\":0\" /> Only two others are known to have been privy to the deception, her cousin and a friend, both of whom were fellow soldiers in her regiment.\n\nShortly after her enlistment, Williams contracted smallpox, was hospitalized and rejoined her unit, which by then was posted in [[New Mexico]]. Possibly due to the effects of smallpox, the New Mexico heat, or the cumulative effects of years of marching, her body began to show signs of strain. She was frequently hospitalized. The post surgeon finally discovered she was a woman, and informed the post commander. She was discharged from the Army by her commanding officer, Captain Charles E. Clarke, on October 14, 1868.\n\n==Post-military service years==\nCathay Williams went to work as a cook at [[Fort Union, New Mexico]], and later moved to [[Pueblo, Colorado]]. Williams married, but it ended disastrously when her husband stole her money and a team of horses. Williams had him arrested. She next moved to [[Trinidad, Colorado]], where she made her living as a seamstress. She may also have owned a boarding house. It was at this time that Williams' story first became public. A reporter from St. Louis heard rumors of an African-American woman who had served in the army, and came to interview her. Her life and military service narrative was published in ''The St. Louis Daily Times'' on January 2, 1876.\n\n[[File:Cathay Williams Pension 002.jpg|thumb|right|U.S. Army Pension records for Cathay Williams]]\n\nIn late 1889 or early 1890, Cathay Williams entered a local hospital where she remained for some time, and in June 1891, applied for a disability pension based on her military service. The nature of her illness and disability are unknown.  There was precedent for granting a pension to female soldiers. [[Deborah Sampson]] in 1816, [[Anna Maria Lane]], and Mary Hayes McCauley (better known as [[Molly Pitcher]]) had been granted pensions for their service in the [[American Revolutionary War]].\n\n==Declining health and death==\nIn September 1893, a doctor employed by the [[Pension Bureau|U.S. Pension Bureau]] examined Cathay Williams. Despite the fact that she suffered from [[neuralgia]] and [[diabetes]], she had all her toes amputated, and could only walk with a crutch, the doctor decided she did not qualify for disability payments. Her application was rejected.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Kwrf0SAM0hQC&lpg=PA33&ots=W0Jkx63pl2&dq=%22Female%20Buffalo%20Soldier%22%20by%20William%20Jennings&pg=PA33#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Voices of the Buffalo Soldier: Records, reports, and recollections of military life and service in the West'']. Edited by Frank N. Schubert. Albuquerque: University of New Mexico Press, 2003, p. 33.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.archives.gov/id/20848612|title=Disapproved Pension Application File for Cathay Williams (aka William Cathay), 38th U.S. Infantry Regiment, Company A (SO-1032593)|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe exact date of Williams' death is unknown, but it is assumed she died shortly after being denied a pension, probably sometime in 1893. Her simple grave marker would have been made of wood and deteriorated long ago. Thus her final resting place is now unknown.\n\n==Honors==\nIn 2016, a bronze bust of Cathay Williams, featuring information about her and with a small rose garden around it, was unveiled outside the [[Richard Allen Cultural Center]] in Leavenworth, Kansas.<ref>{{cite web|last=Davismirandadavis |first=Miranda |url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/local/article91412232.html |title=Monument to female Buffalo Soldier is dedicated in Leavenworth &#124; The Kansas City Star |publisher=Kansascity.com |date=2016-07-22 |accessdate=2016-07-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the Private Cathay Williams monument bench was unveiled on the Walk of Honor at the [[National Infantry Museum]].<ref>{{cite news  |url=https://www.wtvm.com/story/37527852/buffalo-soldiers-honor-first-female-documented-us-army-soldier/|title=Buffalo Soldiers honor first female, documented U.S. Army soldier |work=WTVM |date=17 February 2018 |accessdate=8 April 2020|last=Gunn|first=Olivia }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of African American firsts|African-American firsts]]\n*[[List of wartime crossdressers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.goarmy.com/bhm/profiles_williams.jsp | title=Profiles in Courage: Cathay Williams aka William Cathay |last=|first=| year=2008 | publisher=United States Army | author= | work=Heroes Among Us | accessdate=2008-11-13 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080616094119/http://www.goarmy.com/bhm/profiles_williams.jsp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-06-16}}\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.blackpast.org/?q=aaw/williams-cathay-1850 | title=Williams, Cathay (1850- ) | year=2008 | publisher=BlackPast.org  | author= Ramona L. Rand-Caplan (ed.)| work=African American History in the American West | accessdate=2008-11-13}}\n*{{cite web | url=http://www.buffalosoldier.net/CathayWilliamsFemaleBuffaloSoldierWithDocuments.htm | title=Female Buffalo Soldier- With Documents | date=25 June 2006 |website=| publisher=Buffalo Soldier.net | author=Stanford L. Davis | accessdate=2007-07-30}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.aframnews.com/html/2003-03-26/lead3.htm|title=William Cathay|date=3 September 2005|work=African-American News & Issues|accessdate=2007-01-15|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927151552/http://www.aframnews.com/html/2003-03-26/lead3.htm|archivedate=27 September 2007}}\n*{{cite web | url=https://www.poets.org/poetsorg/poem/ballad-cathay-williams-william-cathay | title=The Ballad of Cathay Williams William Cathay | year=2012 |website=| publisher=Poets.org  | author=Shane McCrae | accessdate