{"title_page": "Residential colleges of Rice University", "text_new": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n<!--  Commented out: [[File:Rice University seal.png|thumb|right|200px|The academic seal of Rice University]] -->\n[[Rice University]] contains '''eleven [[residential colleges]]''' which function as the primary housing, dining, and social organizations for undergraduate students. The system was established in 1957 and was inspired by the residential college systems at the [[University of Oxford]] and the [[University of Cambridge]] as well as the American adaptations of the same at [[Harvard]] and [[Yale]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/29/education/edlife/cornellweber3.html |title=The Residential Collage |website=The New York Times |date=July 29, 2007 |first=Bruce |last=Weber}}</ref> Each student is randomly affiliated with a residential college upon matriculation and becomes a lifetime member of the college.<ref name=\"Collage\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.professor.rice.edu/professor/Student_Life.asp |title=Student Life |publisher=Rice University |accessdate=2008-11-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218194538/http://www.professor.rice.edu/professor/Student_Life.asp |archivedate=2008-12-18 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://students.rice.edu/students/Colleges.asp |title=Residential Colleges |publisher=Rice University |accessdate=2009-04-11}}</ref> The residential college system takes the place of a [[Greek system]] and has contributed to a sense of community that other universities have sought to emulate.<ref name=\"Pride\">{{cite news|title=A place known as Rice: Students take great pride in college system |date=August 31, 1997 |website=Houston Chronicle |last=Lum |first=Lydia}}</ref><ref name=\"Community\">{{cite news|title=Rice undergrads share a sense of community: University's self- governing residential college |website=Houston Chronicle |last=Garza |first=Cynthia Leonor |date=March 5, 2007 | url = http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl?id=2007_4305297}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Universities Try Teaching Beyond the Classrooms |date=December 21, 1986 |website=The Philadelphia Inquirer |page=B3}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Turn Dorms into College 'Communes', UM Advised |publisher=Miami Herland |date=January 22, 1985 |page=2B}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=U. Mississippi eyes residential colleges |date=April 14, 2006 |publisher=University Wire |last=Livingston |first=Justin}}</ref>\n\nAt academic ceremonies, including matriculation and commencement, the colleges proceed first with the four original colleges in the order Baker, Will Rice, Hanszen, and Wiess, followed by the other colleges in order of founding: Jones, Brown, Lovett, Sid Richardson, Martel, McMurtry, and Duncan. For the original four colleges, which were founded simultaneously in 1957, the processional order reflects the order in which the original buildings were constructed. For McMurtry and Duncan, which were constructed and opened simultaneously in August 2009, the processional order reflects the order in which the founding gifts were made.\n\nThe colleges are often classified by geographical location: Jones, Brown, Martel, McMurtry, and Duncan are the '''North colleges'''; Baker, Will Rice, Hanszen, Wiess, Lovett, and Sid Richardson are the '''South colleges'''.\n\n== History of the college system ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2009}}\n\nThe residential college system was instated in 1957 by converting East, South, West, and North Halls into the men's colleges of Baker, Will Rice, Hanszen, and Wiess, respectively.<ref name=\"rice.edu\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rice.edu/sallyport/2007/fall/features/WhatsyourCollege.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-02-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091023110645/http://www.rice.edu/sallyport/2007/fall/features/WhatsyourCollege.html |archive-date=2009-10-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Jones, the first residential college built on campus for that purpose, was constructed the same year and became the singular women's college. Brown, Lovett, and Sid Richardson colleges composed the initial expansion founded between 1965 and 1971. To cope with increasing enrollment,<ref>[http://www.professor.rice.edu/professor/Enrollment-Total_Full_and_Part-Time.asp?SnID=2 Total enrollment '96-'08]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Martel, McMurtry, and Duncan colleges were constructed in the period between 2001 and 2009. Today, when undergraduates are asked where they are from, many respond with the name of their college, not their home state. This is a testament to the centrality of the residential college system to the social life on the Rice campus.\n\n==Common characteristics==\n\n=== Architecture ===\n\nEach college except Sid Richardson is built around a [[quadrangle (architecture)|quadrangle]], which serves as the central court of the college.\n\nEach college building includes three principal structures:\n\n* A residential building, where on-campus members of the college live.  In addition to student rooms in various configurations, the building includes at least two apartments for resident associates.  Resident associates are typically junior faculty members; their role is to serve as mentors and counselors to the students of the college.\n* A house, usually immediately adjacent to the residential building, in which the college Magister or Magisters live.  A Magister is typically a tenured or other senior faculty member who lives at the college with his or her spouse, providing leadership and guidance to the college as a whole and to individual students. (Historically the term Master was reserved for faculty members, while a non-faculty spouse held the title Co-Master. Today, both spouses are known as Magisters.)\n* A commons, where college members (including on-campus and off-campus students, Magisters, resident associates, and non-resident associates from the faculty and the community) take their meals and conduct other activities of college life, including study groups, lectures, theatrical productions, and parties. In addition to a large multi-purpose dining hall, each commons typically includes an administrative office, a private dining room for small group meetings, and other specialized areas.\n\nEach college has a unique architectural style, and as a result there are a great number of different room configurations, with varying levels of modernity and condition.\n\nEach college is also connected to a dining hall, known as a servery. Martel, Jones, and Brown colleges are served by the North Servery, while McMurtry and Duncan are served by the West Servery. In the South, Hanszen and Wiess colleges are served by the South Servery, and Will Rice and Lovett Colleges are served by the Seibel Servery. Baker and Sid Richardson each have their own servery, called college kitchens.\n\n=== Magisters and Resident Associates ===\n\nEach of the residential colleges at Rice has two College Magisters,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ricethresher.org/article/2017/04/master-title-changed-to-magister|title='Master' title changed to 'Magister'|work=The Rice Thresher|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref> a faculty member and his or her spouse. The Magisters reside in a home adjacent to the college, and help cultivate a variety of cultural and intellectual interests among the students, as well as support an effective system of self-government. They administer the college and serve as liaisons between the students of the college and Rice.\n\nResident Associates (RAs) are Rice faculty or staff members who reside on campus with students. While each college has many associates, the RAs are selected to live on campus at the college to interact more extensively with the students. They live in apartment suites at the colleges, regularly attend meals with students, and are generally active members of student life. McMurtry College and Duncan College, due to their population size, also have Head Resident Fellows, who are meant to ease communication between RAs, the Magisters, and the students.\n\nTwo of the longest-serving resident associates in Rice history are Dr. Gilbert Cuthbertson, professor of political science and resident associate at Will Rice College, and [[William L. Wilson (Rice University)|Dr. Bill Wilson]], professor of electrical engineering and resident associate at Wiess College.\n\n=== Governance ===\nEach college is in charge of an annual budget in excess of $50,000 and elects a government from its students to administer the college and the budget. The college governments can exert control over everything from event organization to upgrades to the college facilities. Governing documents for many of the colleges can be found online.<ref>[http://willrice.org/whitepaper/constitution-final-0409v1.pdf Will Rice Constitution]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://jones.rice.edu/files/constitution.pdf |title=Jones Constitution |access-date=2009-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080510134440/http://jones.rice.edu/files/constitution.pdf |archive-date=2008-05-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.brown.rice.edu/govt/policies?id=1&print=1 Brown Constitution]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lovett.rice.edu/docs/government.pdf|title=Rice University -- Web Services|work=Rice.edu|access-date=March 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605000548/http://www.lovett.rice.edu/docs/government.pdf|archive-date=2010-06-05|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sidrichardson.net/node/41|title=Sid Richardson Constitution|author=|date=|work=SidRichardson.net|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.martel.rice.edu/parliament.cfm?doc_id=9425 |title=Martel Constitution |access-date=2009-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070912051239/http://martel.rice.edu/parliament.cfm?doc_id=9425 |archive-date=2007-09-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Singular student presidents and chief justices are university mandated features of each college's government. Additional members vary per college, but typically include Treasurer, Secretary, and a plurality of representatives from each class. The executive officers, such as the President, Treasurer, and Secretary, form the Executive council, and the representatives combine with the council to form the college government, known by names such as Cabinet or Parliament, depending on the college. These councils meet weekly to dispense with business related to the organizational and social functioning of the college. The meetings are akin to town hall meetings and typically include refreshments; they also serve as a forum for members of the various clubs, theater groups, and intramural sporting clubs to announce and advertise upcoming events. In addition, each college elects and sends one senator to represent the college at the Student Association.\n\n=== Traditions ===\n{{see also|Traditions and student life at Rice University}}\n\nThe traditional campus-wide [[Beer Bike]] competition is the largest annual student event held on Rice campus and the source of many rivalries and traditions among the residential colleges.<ref name=\"Roll\">{{cite news|title=Letting the good times roll at Rice: Beer Bike's 50th bash |website=Houston Chronicle |date=April 14, 2007 |page=1 |last=Viren |first=Sarah}}</ref> In recent years, a tradition has emerged wherein the Sid Richardson men's team intentionally disqualify themselves using any of a variety of means, most recently with a fire extinguisher-powered \"rocket bike.\" Sid Richardson has been disqualified in at least one race each year since 2000, with the exception of 2003 and 2007 when the biking was replaced with running due to inclement weather. On the other end of this spectrum, Will Rice is known as the most competitive of the residential colleges and the only one to ever \"sweep\" (win the mens, women, and alumni race). However, Martel College is undefeated in Men's Beer Runs (alternate race due to inclement weather)\n\n==Baker College==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Baker College\n| established = 1957\n| namesake = James Addison Baker (1857{{endash}}1941)\n| president = James Alex Warner\n| chief_justice = Varsha Varghese\n| membership = 360 (approximate)\n| mascot = Devil\n| colors = Red {{Color box|#990000|border=darkgray}} Black {{Color box|#000000|border=darkgray}} Silver {{color box|#C0C0C0}}\n| location = 6320 Main St., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = {{URL|baker.rice.edu}}\n}}\n\n'''James Addison Baker College''' is named in honor of [[James A. Baker (born 1857)|Captain James A. Baker]], friend and attorney of [[William Marsh Rice]], and first chair of the Rice Board of Governors. He served as the Rice Institute's first chairman on the Board of Trustees from June 24, 1891, until his death in 1941.  He is known for having helped unravel the conspiracy surrounding the murder of the millionaire, who was chloroformed by his butler, Charles F. Jones, on September 23, 1900. The suspicious death of the Rice founder was concocted by Albert T. Patrick, a New York attorney, who forged a will naming himself the primary beneficiary to the large fortune, enlisting the Butler's help. Captain Baker, however, began an intensive investigation into the death of his employer, discovering the forgery, and returning the foundation to what would become Rice University.<ref name=\"Baker College\">{{cite web|title=Baker College|url=http://bakercollege.net/about.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120109165927/http://bakercollege.net/about.html|archivedate=9 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the university's original on-campus housing for male students, a dormitory (South Hall, now part of Will Rice College) and a dining room, library and residential tower (now part of Baker College) were built in 1912 by Cram, Goodhue, & Ferguson of Boston, Massachusetts, at the cost of $137,544.52. The now-Baker commons\u2014with beautiful engraved oak beams and the high vaulted ceilings of Elizabethan design\u2014served as the university's central dining hall for 43 years. East Hall, which contained dormitories and is now referred to as the \"Old Wing\" of Baker, was completed in summer 1915 (and West Hall (the \"Old Wing\" of Hanszen College) was completed in 1916).<ref name=\"ricehistoricalsociety.org\">http://ricehistoricalsociety.org/images/cornerstones/wrc06723.pdf</ref> These buildings remained virtually unchanged until the residential college system was instated in 1957. The [[neoclassical architecture]] of the former East Hall was joined by a new two-story brick-colored wing, the design of which was shared with equivalent new sections being constructed at Will Rice and Hanszen colleges, in preparation for becoming residential colleges. A house for Baker's Magister was also added. Baker was thus established as one of the five original colleges at Rice in the fall of 1957. In 1973, Baker and Hanszen became the first [[co-educational|co-ed]] colleges at Rice. To include upperclass women, a lottery was held for Jones and Brown women to transfer into Baker.\n\nBaker's colors are traditionally red, silver, and black, and the college associates itself with the [[devil]] and [[hell]] in its Beer Bike themes and college cheers, with the most popular cheer being \"Baker, hell yeah!\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Baker College Traditions |url=http://bakercollege.net/about_traditions.html |accessdate=2011-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110627065544/http://bakercollege.net/about_traditions.html |archivedate=2011-06-27 }}</ref> The crest was selected, by popular vote, in 1958. The main design is derived from the family crest of Captain Baker's mother, with the owls across the shield indicating the connection to Rice University, and is inscribed with a phrase from Epictetus, which says \"[d]ifficulties are things that show what men are.\" <ref name=\"Baker College\"/> Every year, Baker throws the Baker 90's public party, held in the spring. Some of the biggest social traditions include Baker Christmas in September, the annual Christmas Tree brought home by the freshmen after their camping trip, the Baker Shakespearean play, and of course Baker 13.\n\nIn 2009, construction began on a new residential wing. A portion of the former New Section was renovated and turned over to Lovett College. Baker's new wing is located between the Old Section and the Inner Loop road, and brought with it renovations to Baker's kitchen and the college coordinator's office. It was officially opened back to Baker students in the fall semester of 2010, who returned after a year of co-living with students from Duncan College. \n{{clear right}}\n\n== Will Rice College ==\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Will Rice College\n| image = Will_Rice_College.jpg\n| caption = Will Rice College, with Old Dorm (1912) at left, the commons building at center, and the quadrangle and New Dorm (2009) at right.\n| shield =\n| shield_size = 200px \n| established = {{start date|1957}}\n| namesake = William Marsh Rice, Jr.\n| magisters = Matthew Bennett, Rebekah Bennett\n| president = Rahul Popat\n| chief_justice = Jared Lyons\n| membership = 400 (approximate) \n| mascot = Phoenix\n<!-- | demonym = Will Ricer -->\n| colors = Rust {{Color box|#800000|border=darkgray}} Gold {{Color box|#FFBF00|border=darkgray}}\n| location = 6330 Main Street, [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://willrice.rice.edu willrice.rice.edu]\n}}\n'''William Marsh Rice Jr. College''', commonly known as Will Rice, is named for William M. Rice, Jr., the nephew of the university's founder [[William Marsh Rice]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://willrice.rice.edu/pages/williammarsh.html|title=William M. Rice Jr.|last=Saron|first=Veronica Rae|date=|website=Will Rice College|access-date=April 16, 2018}}</ref> It incorporates Rice's first dormitory, South Hall, which was built in 1912.<ref name=\"ricehistoricalsociety.org\"/> Will Rice College began as an all-male college when Rice created its residential college system in 1957 and became [[Mixed-sex education|co-ed]] in 1978.\n\nWill Rice shares architectural styles with Baker and Hanszen colleges; all three possess white-painted \"old\" buildings and more modern \"new\" wings. Will Rice's ''Old Dorm'' (former South Hall) features a unique fifth-floor tower which has recently become known as ''The Perch''.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nThe symbol of Will Rice college is the [[Phoenix (mythology)|Phoenix]], depicted in rust and gold colors. Members of the college are known as ''Will Ricers''. The college commonly refers to itself as the \"college of Gods and Goddesses.\" The elected governing body of Will Rice, the ''Diet'', administers a university-sponsored annual budget of approximately $50,000 which supports social, athletic, and entertainment programs for the college's nearly 400 resident and non-resident members.\n\nWill Rice is traditionally a strong contender in the university's annual campus-wide Beer Bike competition among the residential colleges. Will Rice has held the longest winning streak on record in the alumni race (11 years from 1996 to 2006).{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} Since the inclusion of an alumni race, Will Rice has been the only college to have won the men's, women's, and alumni races in a given year, called a \"sweep,\" which it has done on five occasions\u20141983, 1986, 1999, 2009, and 2013.<ref name=\"BB Stats\">{{Cite web | accessdate = 2009-03-31 | title = Beer-Bike Stats Galore | url = http://www.jencooper.com/jencooper/00sstats.htm}}</ref><ref name=\"Beer Bike 2013 Results\">{{cite web|url=http://rpc.rice.edu/beer-bike/beer-bike-results-2/ |title=Beer Bike 2013 results |accessdate=April 28, 2013 |publisher=Rice Program Council}}</ref> Additionally, Will Rice holds the current track records for the men's, women's, and alumni races.<ref name=\"BB Stats\" />\n\nIn 2009, work began on a new residential building for Will Rice, located on the site of the former New Section, built in 1957; this building was completely demolished.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://willrice.org/facilities.html|title=Facilities|website=willrice.org|access-date=2017-01-29}}</ref> A new servery, Abe and Anne Seibel Servery, was also part of the construction project. The new facility serves both Will Rice and Lovett, replacing two dated cafeterias at each college.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.architectmagazine.com/project-gallery/the-east-servery-rice-university_o|title=The East Servery, Rice University|last=|first=|date=|website=Architect Magazine|language=en|access-date=2017-01-29}}</ref> During construction, the population of Will Rice lived in McMurtry College, which was founded that year.\n\nNotable alumni include current [[CBS News]] president [[David Rhodes (CBS News President)|David Rhodes]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.rice.edu/2011/02/17/rice-alum-david-rhodes-takes-charge-at-an-american-institution-cbs-news/|title=Rice alum David Rhodes takes charge at an American institution, CBS News|website=news.rice.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref> former [[Major League Baseball]] player [[Lance Berkman]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.riceowls.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/063015aab.html|title=Berkman Inducted Into College Baseball Hall of Fame|last=|first=|date=|work=|publisher=Rice Owls|language=en|access-date=2017-01-30|via=}}</ref> and architect Charles Renfro of [[Diller Scofidio + Renfro]].<ref>http://www.ricethresher.org/article/2014/03/shepherd-to-build-new-opera-house-in-west-lot</ref>\n{{clear right}}\n\n== Hanszen College ==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Hanszen College\n| shield =\n| shield_size = 200px\n| established = 1957 (Original building constructed in 1919)\n| namesake = Harry Clay Hanszen\n| magisters = Paul Brace, Klaudia Brace<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2009/02/27/News/Griffins.To.Replace.Morrises.As.Hanszen.Masters.In.Fall-3651201.shtml |title=Griffins to replace Morrises as Hanszen masters in fall |publisher=Rice Thresher |last=Clemmons |first=Margeux |date=February 27, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409024745/http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2009/02/27/News/Griffins.To.Replace.Morrises.As.Hanszen.Masters.In.Fall-3651201.shtml |archivedate=April 9, 2009 }}</ref>\n| president = Landon Mabe\n| chief_justice = Nikhita Gangla \n| membership = 350 (approximate)\n| mascot = The Guardian\n<!-- | demonym = Hanszenite -->\n| colors = Royal Blue {{Color box|#4169E1|border=darkgray}} Yellow {{Color box|#FFEF00|border=darkgray}}\n| location = 6350 Main St., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://hanszen.rice.edu/ hanszen.rice.edu]\n}}\n[[File:Hanszen-new-section.jpg|left|thumb|The new wing of Hanszen college]]\n'''Harry Clay Hanszen College''' was named for a benefactor to the university and chairman of the Rice Board of Governors from 1946 to 1950.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.utexas.edu/taro/ricewrc/00077/rice-00077.html |title=Guide to the Rice University Harry Clay Hanszen College Records, 1963-2006 |publisher=Rice University Archives}}</ref> Hanszen's \"Old Wing\" was known as West Hall when it was built in 1916 as a part of the original campus construction plan by Boston architectural firm [[Cram, Goodhue & Ferguson]].<ref name=\"ricehistoricalsociety.org\"/> A new housing wing was built in 1957 in conjunction with the development of the [[residential college]] system at Rice in response to the expanding undergraduate enrollment.<ref name=\"Architecture\"/>\n\n[[KTRU-LP|KTRU Rice Radio]], the university's student-run radio station, and Rice Coffeehouse both began at Hanszen College.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nrcdxas.org/articles/KTRUtakeover.html |title=Spin Control The original name of the Rice Coffee House was \"The Corner of the Dreaming Monkey\".  Rice University's slow, systematic makeover of KTRU is just the latest example of a college determined to pattern itself after corporate America |first=Lauren |last=Kern |publisher=Houston Press |date=January 11, 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futureowls.rice.edu/futureowls/Hanszen.asp |title=Prospective Students - Hanszen College |publisher=Rice University |accessdate=2009-04-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409152823/http://www.futureowls.rice.edu/futureowls/Hanszen.asp |archivedate=2009-04-09 }}</ref> Hanszen was the first residential college at Rice to use its own crest. Shortly after the founding of the residential college system, the students created the blue, black, and yellow crest that in time became the symbol of the college, setting a precedent for the other colleges.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rice.edu/sallyport/2007/fall/features/Hanszen_College.html |title=Hanszen College |publisher=Rice Sallyport |date=Fall 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326101802/http://www.rice.edu/sallyport/2007/fall/features/Hanszen_College.html |archivedate=2009-03-26 }}</ref>\n\nHanszen often hosts guest lecturers; recent visitors include [[College World Series]] champion Coach [[Wayne Graham]], former Rice president and renowned economist [[S. Malcolm Gillis]], Kinder Institute for Urban Research director Stephen Klineberg, ''[[Texas Monthly]]'' senior editor and Hanszen alumnus Paul Burka (class of 1963), former writer and executive producer of ''[[The Daily Show]]'' [[Adam Lowitt]], and senior editor of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' Dr. James Hamblin.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} University courses recently offered by Hanszen College have included Analytics in Sports, Spirituality in Film, and The Culture of Philanthropy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://courses.rice.edu/admweb/swkscat.main?p_action=CATALIST&p_acyr_code=2010&p_subj=HANS |title=Course Catalogue |publisher=Rice University |accessdate=2010-01-22}}</ref>\n\nHanszen College is governed by the ''Cabinet'', a body consisting of the Executive Board and class representatives elected by members of the college annually. The Cabinet supervises an annual budget of nearly $60,000, regulates the use of public spaces within the college, and serves as an official liaison between the College membership and the university administration.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n\nHanszen's theme song is [[Hanson (band)|Hanson's]] \"[[MMMBop]]\", believed to have been chosen due to the band and the college being homophones.{{clear right}}\n\n== Wiess College ==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Wiess College\n| shield =\n| shield_size = 200px\n| established = 1957 (original building constructed 1949)\n| namesake = Harry Carothers Wiess\n| magisters = Andrew Schaefer, Laura Schaefer\n| president = Lauren Biegel\n| chief_justice = Drew Keefer\n| membership = 305 (approximate)\n| mascot = The War Pig\n<!-- | demonym = Wiessman -->\n| colors = Goldenrod {{Color box|#FFCC33|border=darkgray}} Black {{Color box|#000000|border=darkgray}}\n| location = 6340 Main St., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://www.teamwiess.com/ teamwiess.com]\n}}\n[[File:WiessCommons.JPG|left|thumb|The commons at Wiess College]]\n\n'''Harry Carothers Wiess College''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|w|a\u026a|s}} was one of the original four colleges created when the residential college system was implemented in 1957. In 2002, Wiess became the only college at Rice to relocate from one building to another.  Wiess is currently the southwesternmost residential college, located adjacent to Hanszen and the South Power Plant.  Male and female members of Wiess College are known equally as ''Wiessmen''.\n\nWiess College is named for Harry Carothers Wiess (1887\u20131948), one of the founders and one-time president of [[Humble Oil]], now [[ExxonMobil]]. He was elected as a life member of the Board of Trustees of Rice University in 1944 and appointed vice-chairman in 1946. He left money for the construction of a new dorm after his death in 1948.<ref name=\"HSLRU\">{{Cite book|last=Delany |first=Colin |chapter=Strength of Identity: The History of Wiess College |title=The History of Student Life at Rice University |editor=Michael Raphael |year=1990 |page=161}}</ref><ref name=\"HC\">{{Cite news|title=Dedication of Wiess Hall At Rice Planned |website=Houston Chronicle |date=March 9, 1950}}</ref>\n\nWiess Hall was completed in 1949, but carried the name \"North Hall\" until its dedication in March 1950.<ref name=\"HC\"/> It was laid out as a W-shaped building, with three north\u2013south wings, joined on the north ends by a long east\u2013west spine, forming two open quadrangles.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schoeffler|first1=Lauren|title=Wiess College: Team Family Wiess|url=http://www.ricestandard.org/wiess-college-team-family-wiess/|website=The Rice Standard|publisher=Rice University|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> The building was two stories high except for the three-story center wing. The hall was designed to house about 200 students in 20 single and 90 double rooms. Each room at Wiess opened directly to an exterior walkway that wrapped around the entire building. This design incorporated two features that were innovative at the time: every room had a semi-private bathroom and every room (except room 228, which was reserved for freshmen) had windows on at least two sides\u2014an important adaptation in the years before air conditioning.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Dormitory Nears Completion |publisher=The Houston Post |date=July 25, 1949}}</ref>\n\nWiess Hall became Wiess College in 1957. Converting the dormitory into a college included the creation of two Resident Associate suites, construction of Wiess House, the home of the Master and family, and construction of the Wiess Commons (designed by Wiess undergraduate architecture students Tim \"Frog\" Barry and Dan Canty for a class project{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}), the eating hall and round-the-clock gathering space for college members.<ref>Box 1, Folder 8, Harry Carothers Wiess College Records, 1950-1999 WRCUAwiess, Woodson Research Center, Fondren Library, Rice University</ref>{{Original research inline|date=March 2009}}<ref name=\"HSLRU\"/>\n\nBecause of Wiess's outward-facing architecture, life at Wiess centered on the outdoors. The two quadrangles developed distinct characters.  The quad between the center and west wings became known as the \"Acabowl\" and was the center of the college's social and recreational activity.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} At various times students installed a trampoline (\"Aca-tramp\") or above-ground pool (\"Aca-pool\"). The other quadrangle, between the center and east wings, was known by analogy as the \"Backabowl\" and tended to be used for quieter activities, such as sunbathing.<ref name=\"FO-Wiess\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.futureowls.rice.edu/futureowls/Wiess.asp?SnID=963453189 |title=Prospective Students - Residential Colleges - Wiess College |publisher=Office of Admissions, Rice University |accessdate=2009-04-24}}</ref>\n\nThe original residential building suffered from rapid deterioration in the 1990s.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} In 2002, the university opened a new building for the college, located south of the original building. New Wiess encloses a single large quadrangle, which retains the \"Acabowl\" name. The new building also preserved what Wiessmen considered a salient feature of the old:  the fact that all rooms at Wiess open directly onto exterior walkways or balconies.<ref name=\"Wiess opens\">{{cite news|title=Wiess College celebrates its new building at Oct. 5 dedication ceremony |url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=2422&SnID=2 |first=Jennifer |last=Evans |publisher=Rice News |date=October 2, 2002 |quote=Most important to Wiessmen, however, is that the new building includes many of the elements that made Old Wiess so distinct: motel-style suites, external balconies and an enclosed courtyard or 'Acabowl'.}}</ref> A glass-walled commons forms the north side of the Acabowl, with three four-story residence wings forming the other sides.  The portion of the Acabowl immediately adjacent to the commons is known as the Acaterrace.  The original Wiess Hall and its adjoining commons were razed during the winter break between Fall 2002 and Spring 2003.\n\nWiess considers itself to have an intense community spirit,<ref name=\"FO-Wiess\"/><ref name=\"Wiess opens\"/> signified by the slogan and cheer \"Team Wiess\", which has been used consistently since the 1970s.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Continuing the Wiess Tradition: New College Under Way With Reflections on Past |publisher=Rice News |url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=3769&SnID=2 |first=Philip |last=Montgomery |date=October 14, 1999 |quote=It is not just a catchy slogan, but it is the core idea of what Wiess is all about. It is this culture of community that ceremony is all about. This isn't just about building a new building. It is about the perseverance of the Team Wiess culture as we make the transition to this new building'.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607151143/http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=3769&SnID=2|archivedate=June 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAspects of Wiess life include Tabletop Theater, the Ubangee, pumpkin caroling, [[Night of Decadence]], ''Hello, Hamlet!'', the turning of the statue of university founder [[William Marsh Rice]], the [[Pace Mannion]] fan club, and the War Pig.<ref name=\"Wiess opens\"/><ref>http://www.futureowls.rice.edu/futureowls/Wiess.asp?SnID=963453189</ref>\n\nOne of the most influential persons in Wiess history was electrical engineering professor Bill Wilson, who served as resident associate from 1978 to 2006 and as interim Master in 1982\u201383, which was also the year in which Wiess became a co-ed college.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}  Wilson, known to generations of students as Dr. Bill, was a fixture of Rice's college system and the keeper of many Wiess traditions.  In addition to his many teaching awards, he is the only person to have won the Student Association's Mentor Recognition Award twice.  After his unexpected death in January 2009, his memorial service was held at the Wiess commons.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bill Wilson joins ranks of Emeritus Faculty |publisher=Rice News |date=June 29, 2006 |url=http://www.ece.rice.edu/wlwemeritus06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720002148/http://www.ece.rice.edu/wlwemeritus06 |archivedate=July 20, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dr. Bill receives Salgo award |publisher=Rice News |date=May 11, 2006 |url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=8540&SnID=641215845}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bill Wilson Celebrates 20 Years at Wiess With His 'Family' |publisher=Rice News |date=April 8, 1999 |url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=3633}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=Rice News |url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=12022&SnID=587347775 |title=Memorial service set for 'Dr. Bill' Saturday |first=Jade |last=Boyd |date=January 23, 2009}}</ref>  In December 2009, the Rice board of Trustees, with the consent of Wiess College, decided that the new Masters' residence at Wiess will be named Wilson House, in honor of Dr. Bill.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wiess Masters House to be named in honor of Wilson |publisher=Rice News |date=January 15, 2010 |url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=13580}}</ref>  Dedicated on March 11, 2011, Wilson House is the first building at Rice named after a college Master or Resident Associate, and the first Masters' residence to bear a name distinct from that of its associated college.\n\nNotable Wiessmen include Walter Loewenstern (1958),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=10449|title=Rice University News & Media - Rice University News & Media|author=|date=|work=Rice.edu|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref> [[Harold Solomon]], [[Ricky Pierce]] (1982), and [[Anthony Rendon]].\n{{clear right}}\n\n== Jones College ==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Jones College\n| shield = \n| established = 1957\n| namesake = Mary Gibbs Jones\n| magisters = Jason Hafner, Jennifer Trotter\n| president = Hannah Kim\n| chief_justice = Aaron Pathak\n| membership = 325 (approximate)\n| mascot = [[Jabberwocky]], JIBACat (unofficial), Marley Mackenzie\n<!-- | demonym = Jonesian -->\n| colors = {{Color box|#1E90FF|border=darkgray}} Light Blue<br />{{Color box|#008000|border=darkgray}} Green<br />{{Color box|#501A80|border=darkgray}} Purple\n| location = 23 Sunset Blvd., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States|\n| homepage = [http://jones.rice.edu/ jones.rice.edu]\n}}\n\n'''Mary Gibbs Jones College''', built as the first women's dormitory at Rice University, is named after [[Mary Gibbs Jones]], wife of prominent Houston philanthropist [[Jesse Holman Jones]].  Jesse H. Jones supported its initial construction with a $1 million donation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jones.rice.edu/page/history |title=Jones College - History |publisher=Jones College, Rice University |accessdate=2009-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331094220/http://jones.rice.edu/page/history |archivedate=2009-03-31 }}</ref>\n\nThe college was built in 1957, consisting of two four-story structures named \"North\" and \"South.\" It was designed by architects Lloyd & Morgan. Not only was it the first housing for women on campus, it was also the first building designed specifically as a residential college and also the first building to be centrally air-conditioned. \nLloyd & Morgan used pink marble in the construction of Jones College to indicate its status as housing for female students.<ref name=\"Architecture\"/> In 2002, an additional four-story building, \"Central,\" was built in between North and South.<ref name=\"Expansion\">{{Cite web | title = Year of campus construction signals expansion at Rice U.| work = Houston Chronicle| date = 2002-06-06| author = Betty L. Martin| accessdate = 2009-04-06 | url = http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl?id=2002_3553908}}</ref> The new building connects to both original buildings at every level except the ground floor (a short walk separates South and Central). The wing was designed by noted post-modern architect [[Michael Graves]].\n\nIn the early days, the culture of the all-female Jones College was quite conservative.<ref name=\"Community\"/>  At meals, each table had a hostess, and dinner was served family style. Strict rules were enforced by house mothers when men from the south colleges visited the female students. The students even had to abide by a strict curfew - 11 p.m. on weekdays and 2 a.m. on weekends.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n\nIn the 1970s, Jones began phasing out many of the strictest rules, and in the fall of 1980 Jones became co-ed.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} Male students from the south colleges were given the chance to apply for transfer to Jones. Lovett, another Rice residential college, went co-ed the same year, so many of the new Jones residents were former Lovett residents. Jones women who disagreed with the decision to go co-ed were allowed to transfer to Brown College, which remained all-female until 1987. In 2001, construction began on the new Jones Commons and Jones Central. The new Jones Commons opened for use in March 2002.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} Jones Central opened in August 2002. During the same time, Jones lost its parking lot to the newly constructed Martel College.\n\nJones' [[Students' union|student government]] is set up as a Cabinet comprising the Executive Officers, elected representatives from each floor, and one elected off-campus representative.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jones.rice.edu/page/cabinet |title=Jones College - Cabinet |publisher=Jones College, Rice University |accessdate=2009-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330221400/http://jones.rice.edu/page/cabinet |archivedate=2009-03-30 }}</ref> The Cabinet meets bi-weekly.\n\nJones is a college with an indoor setup which has two lounges on every floor. Jones is unique among the colleges due to its large number of singles. Jones also has four 4-single suites and two 6-single suites, along with regular doubles.\n\nPrevious Jones College Magisters include Dr. Franz Brotzen (former Rice University Dean of Engineering) and Dr. Robin Forman (former Rice University Dean of Undergraduates).\n\nNotable alumni from Jones include [[George P. Bush]] (1998),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/news/2000-08-11/78217/|title=Gorgeous George|author=|date=|work=AustinChronicle.com|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref> former [[Mayor of Houston]] [[Annise Parker]] (1978),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.rice.edu/2009/12/13/rice-alumna-annise-parker-elected-houston-mayor/|title=Rice alumna Annise Parker elected Houston mayor|author=|date=|work=Rice.edu|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref> and neuroscientist [[David Eagleman]] (1993).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.culture.rice.edu/Eagleman.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-03-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416155420/http://www.culture.rice.edu/Eagleman.aspx |archive-date=2016-04-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n{{clear right}}\n\n== Brown College ==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Brown College\n| shield =\n| shield_size = 200px\n| established = 1965\n| namesake = Margarett Root Brown\n| president = A Quokka\n| chief_justice = Frances Williamson \n| membership = 353\n| motto = Tende Bene Alta Pete\n| mascot = taylor morin\n<!-- | demonym = Brownie -->\n| colors = Maroon {{Color box|#800000|border=darkgray}} Gold {{Color box|#FFBF00|border=darkgray}}\n| location = 9 Sunset Blvd., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://www.brown.rice.edu/ brown.rice.edu]\n|masters=B.J. Fregly, Shirley Fregly}}\n[[File:BrownCommons.JPG|thumb|left|The new Brown College commons]]\n\n'''Margarett Root Brown College''' is currently the third largest of the eleven residential colleges at Rice, behind both McMurtry College and Duncan College. Founded in 1965 as an all-women's college, Brown became co-ed in 1987.\n\nThe history of Brown dates back to the early sixties, when Jones College was the only all women's college on campus.<ref name=\"Brown_history\">http://www.brown.rice.edu/about/history.php</ref> This caused such a severe housing shortage that some Rice women were housed in the dorms of nearby [[Texas Women's University]]. Through the generous $1 million donation of [[George R. Brown]] and his wife Alice Pratt Brown, a new women's residential college was established in the memory of their sister-in-law, Margarett Root Brown. Up until her death in 1985, Alice Pratt Brown was an active patron of the college, giving the college much of the furniture and art in the first floor lobbies and private dining room.\n\n[[File:BrownCollege.jpg|thumb|left|The old wing of Brown College]]\nIn the beginning, Brown College was filled primarily with women who had volunteered to leave Jones in order to start a new college. Brown had a housemother who lived in the [[Resident assistant|resident associate]]\u2019s apartment and required all women to check in and out of the building at night and on weekends. The first Master of Brown was [[Frank Vandiver]], who later became president of [[Texas A&M University|Texas A&M]]. In 1966 he resigned from Brown because of a \u201cscandal\u201d \u2013 the members of Brown voted to drink alcohol in their own rooms (provided they were of legal drinking age). Vandiver resigned because he considered it inappropriate behavior for young ladies.<ref name=\"Brown_history\"/>\n\nBrown was the last single-sex female college after Jones went co-ed in 1980; male members were first accepted into Brown in 1987.<ref name=\"Brown_history\"/> However, the community bathrooms on all floors remained coed {{dubious|date=November 2009}} until 1994, when the bathrooms were remodeled and separate facilities for men and women were built on each floor. Brown's main tower consists of mainly of double rooms whose residents share community bathrooms. Each floor also has one single room without a bathroom, as well as a double room with a bathroom, referred to as a suite. The new 4-story wing at Brown opened in 2002.<ref name=\"Expansion\"/> The new wing houses 56 additional students, making Brown the largest residential college on campus (it was previously the smallest) until the opening of McMurtry and Duncan. The new wing is made up of four-person suite, and each suite has four small single rooms, a large common room, and a private bathroom.<ref name=\"Brown_history\"/> Besides rooms, Brown offers other facilities. For instance, Brown's basement houses a communal laundry room and music practice rooms. Brown's first floor, referred to as \"Vator Lobby\" in reference to its use as an elevator lobby, contains a communal kitchen, a computer lab, couches, and amenities such as a projector and pool tables.\n{{clear right}}\n\n== Lovett College ==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Lovett College\n| shield =\n| established = 1968\n| namesake = [[Edgar Odell Lovett]]\n| magisters = Dr. Michael Gustin and Denise Klein\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.students.rice.edu/students/College_Masters.asp|title=College Masters : Rice University|author=|date=|work=Rice.edu|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| president = Chloe Oani\n| chief_justice = Laura Yordan\n| membership = 375 (approximate)\n| mascot = Stag\n<!-- | demonym = Lovetteer -->\n| colors = Navy Blue {{Color box|#000080|border=darkgray}} Yellow {{Color box|#FFEF00|border=darkgray}}\n| location = 6310 Main St., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://www.lovett.rice.edu/ lovett.rice.edu]\n}}\n[[File:Lovett.jpg|left|thumb|The residential building of Lovett College]]\n\n'''Edgar Odell Lovett College''' is the seventh-founded residential college, named after the university's first president.<ref name=\"Architecture\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Schwent |first1=J. |first2=G. |last2=Omid |year=2005 |title=Rice University College Prowler Off The Record |publisher=College Prowler, Inc.  |isbn=1-59658-107-7}}</ref>  Lovett opened in 1969 as an all-male college, becoming co-ed in 1980 when members of the college exchanged places with the female members of Jones College.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} Lovett's first class mostly comprised volunteers from other colleges. Lovett sponsors numerous community and social events throughout the year, including theater productions and the Lovett Undergraduate Research Symposium. Lovett's college crest is based upon the Lovat family crest<ref>Rice University Woodson Research Center Lovett College Records 1968-2007. Box 1, Folder 2</ref>{{Original research inline|date=April 2009}} although the Lovat family is not related to Edgar Odell Lovett.\n\n[[File:Lovett College being built.jpg|left|thumb|Lovett College during construction]]\nThe distinctive [[brutalist]] architecture of Lovett has led many to compare it to a giant [[toaster]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.rice.edu/collections/WRC/finding-aids/university-archives/lovett-college/ |title=Lovett College records, 1968-2007 |publisher=Fondren Library, Rice University |accessdate=2009-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423055450/https://library.rice.edu/collections/WRC/finding-aids/university-archives/lovett-college |archivedate=2009-04-23 }}</ref> This is due to the concrete grating that surrounds the third, fourth, and fifth floors, a design feature intended to make Lovett riot-proof in reaction to the student [[riot]]s of the late 1960s, most notably the [[Abbie Hoffman]] riot of 1967.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} Other riot-proofing features include the limited reach of the elevator, which does not reach the sixth floor, to prevent students from throwing furniture off of the only exposed higher floor, although that feature has not been completely successful in preventing furniture from being thrown from the building. Some have called Lovett's architecture style \"modern American prison\" because of the intersecting horizontal and vertical elements.\n\n\"The grating\" now protects Lovett students from hurricanes; in fall of 2005 Lovett students were among the only Rice students allowed to stay in their rooms during [[Hurricane Rita]] and [[Hurricane Ike]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} As a tongue-in-cheek homage to [[Communism]] and the purported Soviet architecture of the college, the men of the founding class named their college government the Central Committee.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} The main body of the crest was taken from the [[Clan Fraser of Lovat]] and modified by adding a stag to each side.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n\nLovett is made up of four buildings: a six-story residential building, an additional two-story residential building, which was acquired from Baker in fall of 2010, a single-story commons, and the Masters' house.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} All of these buildings are structurally connected but have separate entrances and spaces. The majority of the rooms in the residential building are two-person suites, connected in pairs by a shared bathroom. Lovett House is a full two-story home in which the masters reside. The masters often host dessert at their house for special occasions, as well as private Central Committee meetings. The Lovett basement contains a number of facilities for use by the college members, as well as storage space for the various committees. The basement has a game room with various gaming tables, a movie room with couches and a projector, a kitchen, computer room, music room, weight room, and other spaces. The Wiener Hole is Lovett's public study space. It contains the Lovett test file, which contains records of previous tests in various classes. Lyle's, named for former Lovett resident associate Lyle Angene and also known as the Lovett Undergrounds, is a combination bar and performance space located in Lovett's basement. Lyle's is equipped with a sound system, stage, and lights, as well as bar equipment, including a [[kegerator]]. Seating for more than two hundred people can be moved into the space for performances. Lovett Theater and various Rice-wide performance groups, such as the Rice Philharmonics and Spontaneous Combustion, often use Lyle's for their performances; it also often acts as a space for smaller private parties.\n\nIn 2009, work began on renovating a portion of Baker College's former New Section, which was transferred over to become Lovett's New Section starting in the 2010 fall semester.<ref>{{cite web\n |last=Swartz \n |first=Dale \n |title=Southern Reconstruction \n |work=The Rice Thresher \n |date=April 18, 2008 \n |url=http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2008/04/18/News/Southern.Reconstruction-3333058.shtml \n |accessdate=December 13, 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091210040321/http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2008/04/18/News/Southern.Reconstruction-3333058.shtml \n |archivedate=December 10, 2009 \n}}</ref> A new servery, shared with Will Rice College, was recently built as part of the construction project and named Seibel Servery.\n\nNotable alumni include [[James Casey (American football)|James Casey]], [[Luke Willson]], [[Jos\u00e9 Cruz, Jr.]],<ref>{{cite web\n |last=Fielder \n |first=Lindsey \n |title=Three with Rice ties to be inducted into the Texas Baseball Hall of Fame \n |work=Rice News \n |publisher=[[Rice University]] \n |date=October 23, 2003 \n |url=http://staff.rice.edu/staff/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=1867&SnID=2\n |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070515045514/http://staff.rice.edu/staff/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=1867&SnID=2\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=May 15, 2007\n |accessdate=March 30, 2009 \n}}</ref> [[John Doerr]],<ref>{{Cite web\n |title=John Doerr (Rice BSEE 1973, MSEE 1974) \n |accessdate=2009-03-31 \n |url=http://www.ece.rice.edu/aboutece/halloffame/hof_doerr \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100608040521/http://www.ece.rice.edu/aboutece/halloffame/hof_doerr \n |archivedate=2010-06-08 \n}}</ref> [[Brock Wagner]], [[John Kline (politician)|John Kline]], [[Ann Saterbak]], [[Alberto Gonzales]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=1796&SnID=2 |title=Alum Gonzales to give grads send-off |author=Jennifer Evans |date=12/11/2003 |accessdate=2009-08-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612172746/http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW |archivedate=2010-06-12 }}</ref> and [[Matt Anderson (baseball)|Matt Anderson]].<ref>{{Cite web\n |title=Berkman takes time to reflect on years at Rice \n |work=Sports, The Rice Thresher \n |date=2009-02-20 \n |accessdate=2009-03-31 \n |url=http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2009/02/20/Baseball09/Berkman.Takes.Time.To.Reflect.On.Years.At.Rice-3639269.shtml?refsource=collegeheadlines\n|archive-url=https://archive.is/20110817092628/http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2009/02/20/Baseball09/Berkman.Takes.Time.To.Reflect.On.Years.At.Rice-3639269.shtml?refsource=collegeheadlines\n|url-status=dead\n|archive-date=2011-08-17\n}}</ref> Nobel Laureate [[Robert Curl]] was the first college Master, and [[George H.W. Bush]] served as a community associate.<ref>{{Cite web \n| title = President Bush Slated as Commencement Speaker | work = Rice University, News & Media | date = 1999-09-30 | accessdate = 2009-03-31 | url = http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=3842&SnID=2}}</ref><ref>Raphael, Michael: ''The History of Student Life at Rice University: A Series of Papers'', Appendix A. Rice University Centennial Celebration Committee, 1990.</ref>\n{{clear right}}\n\n== Sid Richardson College ==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Sid Richardson College\n| shield =\n| established = 1971\n| namesake = [[Sid W. Richardson]]\n| magisters = Michel and Melanie Achard\n| president = Nia Prince\n| chief_justice = Johnston French \n| mascot = Tower\n| membership = 332\n| motto = Mors de Super\n<!-- | demonym = Sidizen -->\n| colors = Black {{Color box|#000000|border=darkgray}} Red {{Color box|#FF0000|border=darkgray}} Gold {{Color box|#FFEF00|border=darkgray}}\n| location = 6360 Main Street,\n[[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://sidrichcollege.org/ sidrichcollege.org]\n}}\n\n[[File:Sid Richardson College.jpg|thumb|Sid Richardson College as seen from the North side.]]\n\n'''Sid Richardson College''' (also referred to as '''Sid''', '''SRC''', or '''Sid Rich''') opened in 1971 as a men's residential college. Like the other residential colleges on the Rice campus, Sid Richardson College provides undergraduate residential and dining facilities, social organizations and student government, as well as faculty, alumni, and community associates. A $2 million pledge from the Sid Richardson Foundation, which was established by Texas oilman, cattleman, and philanthropist [[Sid W. Richardson]] (1891\u20131959), funded the construction of the college. The college became co-ed in 1987. Members of Sid Richardson College are called \"Sidizens.\"\n\nSid Richardson College is the tallest building on the Rice campus. It has seven floors, each of which is split into an upper and lower level, effectively giving the building fourteen stories. Unusual among Rice buildings, the {{convert|153|ft|m}} high-rise was a response to a shortage of University land and was designed by the architectural firm Neuhaus and Taylor.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Sid Richardson College records, 1969-2000 - Fondren Library | work = Fondren Library Woodson Research Center | accessdate = 2009-03-30 | url = http://library.rice.edu/collections/WRC/finding-aids/university-archives/sid-richardson-college#d0e59}}</ref> Sid Rich has enough beds to accommodate 229 students.<ref name=\"Community\"/> Original plans called for the eventual construction of a second tower, but the plan was never followed through.<ref name=\"Architecture\">{{Cite book| last1 = Fox | first1 = Stephen | last2 = Hester | first2 = Paul |title=Rice University: The Campus Guide |publisher=Princeton Architectural Press |year=2001 |isbn=1-56898-246-1}}</ref> In similar fashion to Lovett, the Sid Masters' house is connected to the residential tower; it comprises the first floor of the tower, while the [[Mezzanine (architecture)|mezzanine]] of the residential building is actually the second floor of the tower.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Rice Network Infrastructure Project- Sid Richardson College Masters House |work=The Rice Network Infrastructure Project |accessdate=2009-03-30 |url=http://www.rice.edu/ricenet/buildings/sidmasters.php |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326072647/http://www.rice.edu/ricenet/buildings/sidmasters.php |archivedate=2009-03-26 }}</ref>\nThe first floor of Sid features a commons, a private dining room, and an OC (off-campus) lounge.  The lounge consists of a pool table{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}, a ping pong table{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}, and a television set.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nAlthough Sid Richardson College is not built around a quad, there is a similar outdoor feature of the college known as the \"country club.\"  The country club consists of a field, [[volleyball]] court, hammock, an adult-sized swing set, and many picnic tables.\n\n[[File:Earlysid.jpeg|thumb|left|A banner hung from Sid during a game against the [[Texas A&M University|Aggies]] copyright [[Michael Petry]]]]\n\nIn addition to providing basic residential and social services to its residents, Sid Richardson College is rich with traditions, which have included some notorious pranks.  For example, Sidizens have made use of the six balconies towering above the main entrance of the college to \"douche\" unsuspecting visitors\u2014including past Rice University president [[George Rupp]] and his wife\u2014with buckets of water as they climb the steps to the double doors. While such \"free-flowing water\" is the only sanctioned projectile, rogue students have also flung flour tortillas, shrimp, and, in one particularly infamous situation, a couch.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Berkman takes time to reflect on years at Rice |work=The Rice Thresher |author=Yan Digilov |date=2000-02-20 |accessdate=2009-03-30 |url=http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2009/02/20/Baseball09/Berkman.Takes.Time.To.Reflect.On.Years.At.Rice-3639269.shtml |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402025159/http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2009/02/20/Baseball09/Berkman.Takes.Time.To.Reflect.On.Years.At.Rice-3639269.shtml |archivedate=2009-04-02 }}</ref> During the mid-1970s, students moved a Karman Ghia automobile into the dining area. Photographic evidence can be found in the Rice Campanile.\n\nAnother prank that is quickly becoming a tradition is the [[Orc]] Raid.  Orc Raids are held twice every year - once during the Orientation Week in August before the start of the Fall semester and a second time during Willy Week in the Spring semester. Sidizens dress up by smearing themselves with black paint, wearing black clothes and carrying around torches with doll heads.  They then proceed to run around campus at night to terrorize the other colleges and crash events, often shouting out cheers that boost the morale of the Sidizens as well as anti-cheers meant to belittle the 'lesser' colleges.\n\nSid Richardson College has a wealth of traditions. Every Friday afternoon from 3:00-6:00pm, the college's main speakers, affectionately known as the \"stacks,\" blast music in what is known as \"Radio Free Sid\" (the named derived from [[Radio Free Europe]] of the [[Cold War]] era) across the campus from the 7th floor balcony. Radio Free Sid begins and ends each roughly 3-hour-long set of music with [[AC/DC]]'s [[Back in Black (song)|\"Back in Black,\"]] widely considered to be the college's theme song.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Golden Anniversary | accessdate = 2009-03-31 | url = http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=9432}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Sid Richardson College |accessdate=2009-03-31 |url=http://www.rice.edu/sallyport/2007/fall/features/SidRich_College.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326101800/http://www.rice.edu/sallyport/2007/fall/features/SidRich_College.html |archivedate=2009-03-26 }}</ref> Other traditions include Night of Innocence (a showing of Disney movies in the commons the same night as NOD), Sid 80s (Sid's fall public party), Sid Hi-Liter (spring public party), vatoring of Sidizens who co-advise, Floor Wars (a series of competitive events between the floors), Squid Richardson Day, and more.\n\nSid Richardson has also hosted the five Houston Conferences on Theoretical Neuroscience (2004-2009), thanks to a relationship between the GCC and former Sid Richardson Master Steve Cox.<ref>{{Cite web | title = GCC for Theoretical and Computational Neuroscience | work = The Gulf Coast Consortium | accessdate = 2009-03-30 | url = http://cohesion.rice.edu/centersandinst/gcc/neuro_about.cfm?doc_id=5726}}</ref>\n\nNotable alumni include [[Steve Jackson (US game designer)|Steve Jackson]], [[Philip Humber]], White House Press Secretary [[Josh Earnest]],<ref>http://m.ricethresher.org/news/article_ec6e0d2f-f553-553d-9716-4aa3d78a9f6c.html?mode=jqm{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and Mark Durcan,<ref>[http://www.linkedin.com/pub/mark-durcan/5/755/419 Durcan's profile on LinkedIn]</ref> CEO of [[Micron Technology]].\n{{clear right}}\n\n== Martel College ==\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Martel College\n| shield =\n| established = 2002\n| namesake = Marian and Speros P. Martel\n| magisters = Carrie Toffoletto, Frank Toffoletto\n| president = Paras Gupta\n| chief_justice = Chris Yau\n| membership = 350 (approximate)\n| mascot = Beer Goat\n<!-- | demonym = Martelian -->\n| colors = Azure (sky blue) {{Color box|#87CEEB|border=darkgray}}, argent (white) {{color box|white}}, maroon {{Color box|#78184A|border=darkgray}}\n| location = 99 Sunset Blvd., [[Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://www.martel.rice.edu/ martel.rice.edu]\n}}\n\n[[File:Martel Sallyport.jpg|left|thumb|Martel's [[sally port]]]]\n[[File:Martel Rotunda.jpg|left|thumb|The [[Rotunda (architecture)|rotunda]], with the sundeck]]\n[[File:Martel Commons.jpg|left|thumb|The cathedral-like Commons]]\n[[File:Beergoat.JPG|left|thumb|The infamous \"Beer Goat\" [[keg]] holder]]\n\n'''Marian and Speros P. Martel College''' is the ninth-founded residential college. It was established with a $15 million donation from the eponymous Marian and Speros Martel Foundation, a longtime benefactor of Rice University. The college's building was designed by noted architect [[Michael Graves]] and housed its first students during the 2002\u20132003 school year.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Michael Graves, FAIA | work = The American Institute of Architects | accessdate = 2009-03-30 | url = http://www.aia150.org/aw_gm_2001.php | archive-url = http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20090707112617/http://www.aia150.org/aw_gm_2001.php | archive-date = 2009-07-07 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref name=\"MartelNews\">{{Cite web | title = Welcoming in the Martel Era | work = Rice University, News & Media | date = 2000-04-06| accessdate = 2009-03-29 | url = http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=5210&SnID=2}}</ref>  Martel is one of [[List of Rice University residential colleges|eleven residential colleges]] at Rice University, and it is the only one that has a Sallyport of its own; it is located adjacent to Jones and Duncan colleges on the north side of [[Rice University#Campus|campus]], sharing the North Servery with the former. The college prides itself on its adopted Greek heritage, a tribute to its benefactors' country of origin. Aspects of Greek culture are incorporated into a number of college events, and an interior staircase of the college features a four-story map of Athens painted by Joshua Krezinski (class of 2007). The second and fourth quadrants of Martel's crest represent the cross and stripes of the [[Flag of Greece|Greek flag]], while the other two are reserved for the [[Athena#Cult and attributes|Athenian owl]], a symbol of wisdom taken from the university's academic seal, and the \"MC\" glyph representing the College's name. The crest was designed by the building's architect.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} The Martel College colors are representative of the Greek flag and the building's architecture. The [[blazon]] of the Greek flag is \"[[Azure (heraldry)|Azure]], four bars [[Argent]]; on a canton of the field a Greek cross throughout of the second.\" While azure often associates with a deeper blue, Martel College uses a lighter [[Tincture (heraldry)|tincture]] of azure known as [[bleu celeste]] or \"sky blue\". Also, the argent used by the college favors a bright, reflective white instead of the more silvery tincture. Maroon represents the building's brick and paint scheme. Members of Martel college are known as \"Martelians\".\n\nAs the third-most-recently founded residential college, Martel's history is short, and commonly includes the story of Speros Martel, the Greek immigrant whose estate provided the funding necessary to build the college.<ref name=\"Martel Website\">{{Cite web|title=Martel in the Beginning |work=Rice University |access-date=March 30, 2009 |url=http://martel.rice.edu/about.cfm?doc_id=9499 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517215807/http://martel.rice.edu/about.cfm?doc_id=9499 |archivedate=May 17, 2008 }}</ref> The official groundbreaking of the new Martel college took place on April 10, 2000. Among those attending were the newly instated Martel Magisters Joan and Arthur Few, who had previously been Masters at Baker College from 1994 to 1999.\n\nThe first new students accepted as members of Martel were required to live off campus during the fall 2001 semester until the completion of the College's construction, which was scheduled for early 2002. However, in June 2001, [[Tropical Storm Allison]] struck the Houston area and delayed this by two months.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} Applications for freshman transfers were made available in October 2002. Sixty-three freshmen were accepted, five each from Brown and Jones Colleges, and up to 12 from each of the other colleges. Martel members named physics instructor Gary Morris and intramural sports director Tina Villard as Martel's first resident associates.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Guide to the Rice University Martel College Records, 2000-2003 | work = Texas Archival Resources Online | accessdate = 2009-03-29 | url = http://www.lib.utexas.edu/taro/ricewrc/00241/rice-00241.html}}</ref>{{Original research inline|date=April 2009}}\n\nMartel's student government is named the Parliament, and meets weekly in the College commons. Elected officials include President, Vice President, Prime Minister, Treasurer, Secretary, Chief Justice, and Class Representatives (4 per class).\n\n[[Michael Graves]], architect of Martel College, designed the four-story, {{convert|134000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} building.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Images of Martel College, Rice University by Michael Graves| work = Digital Imaging Project, Bluffton University | author = Mary Ann Sullivan | accessdate = 2009-03-29 | url = http://www.bluffton.edu/~sullivanm/texas/houston/ricemartel/graves.html}}</ref>  Formed around a central quadrangle, Graves's design follows the style of the 1910 general plan of Boston architect [[Ralph Adams Cram]] for the Rice campus. Martel is an open, four-sided shape. Each side of the shape forms a wing of the college. The wings terminate on the side closest to North Servery in a five-story rotunda, a spiral staircase enclosed within a stack of rounded floors, providing the college with its sundeck, where many events are held. The easternmost wing contains common areas, the game room, a kitchen, and the TV room. The rotunda leads into the Commons, a cathedral-like room with a high ceiling that serves as a cafeteria, meeting room, and auditorium, among other functions.<ref name=\"Expansion\"/> The college also includes two apartments for Martel's resident associates and a neighboring house for the College Magisters and their family. Nearly every room at Martel is suite style, and is either referred to as a hex, or a quad. There are two kinds of hexes, sally port and corner hexes. Corner hexes have 6 single rooms and sallyport hexes have 3 double rooms. Every suite at martel has a private bathroom. Rooming is overseen by the Vice President. Martel is also the only college to feature a [[Sally Port|sally port]] in its construction; newly matriculated students traditionally walk through it passing a torch between themselves as the final step to becoming new Martelians.\n\nAlumni include [[Chris Boswell]], [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] kicker, [[Jason Colwick]], 2009 NCAA pole vault champion, Andrew Chifari, [[Starbucks]] most expensive drink record breaker,<ref>{{cite web | title = New Starbucks Free Drink Record Set With $54 Sexagintuple Vanilla Bean Mocha Frappuccino  | work = Consumerist | publisher = [[Consumer Reports]]| url = http://consumerist.com/2014/05/27/new-starbucks-free-drink-record-set-with-54-sexagintuple-vanilla-bean-mocha-frappuccino/ | accessdate = June 25, 2014}}</ref> Mithun Mansinghani, the Oklahoma Solicitor General,<ref>{{cite web | title = Alva native appointed to Attorney General's staff | publisher = Alva Review-Courier | url = http://www.alvareviewcourier.com/story/2017/03/19/local/alva-native-appointed-to-attorney-generals-staff/10864.html | accessdate = November 7, 2017}}</ref> and [[Morris Almond]], a professional basketball player.<ref>{{cite web | title = Jason Colwick Profile  | work = Official Website of Rice Athletics | publisher = [[Rice University]]| url = http://riceowls.cstv.com/sports/m-track/mtt/colwick_jason00.html | accessdate = March 31, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web  | last = Manfull | first = Megan | title = Owls athletics: Ryan Berry & Jason Colwick | work = [[Houston Chronicle]] | date = March 13, 2009| url = http://blogs.chron.com/owls/2009/03/owls_baseball_ryan_berry_take.html | accessdate = March 31, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Smooth Shooter|url=http://news.rice.edu/2006/11/16/smooth-shooter/|work=Rice News|publisher=Rice University News & Media|accessdate=21 February 2014}}</ref>\n{{clear right}}\n\n== McMurtry College ==\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = McMurtry College\n| shield =\n| established = 2009\n| namesake = Burt and Deedee McMurtry\n| magisters =  Margaret Beier, Chris Stickney<ref>{{cite web|title=College Masters|url=http://www.students.rice.edu/students/College_Masters.asp|website=Rice University|accessdate=17 September 2015}}</ref>\n| president =  Joyce Chen\n| chief_justice = Augi Liebster \n| membership = 420 (approximate)\n| mascot = Lion\n<!-- | demonym = Murts -->\n| colors = Royal Purple {{Color box|#2A0054|border=darkgray}} Silver {{color box|#C0C0C0}}\n| location = 1605 Rice Blvd., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://mcmurtry.rice.edu mcmurtry.rice.edu]\n}}\n\n'''Burt and Deedee McMurtry College''' is the tenth college founded as part of Rice's residential college system.<ref name=\"11th\"/> McMurtry College was named after Burt and Deedee McMurtry, graduates of the Rice class of 1956.<ref>{{Cite news\n |title=Record $32 million pledged to Rice, Student residences are just one cause to benefit from alumni couple's gift \n |work=Houston Chronicle \n |date=June 17, 2006 \n |first=Todd \n |last=Ackerman \n |url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Record-32-million-pledged-to-Rice-1911588.php \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ZfFxNIHn?url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Record-32-million-pledged-to-Rice-1911588.php \n |archivedate=June 30, 2015 \n |accessdate=June 29, 2015 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref> Burt McMurtry was part of the student-faculty committee that evaluated the need for and eventually instituted the college system at Rice University, beginning in 1957 with the original five colleges. The college was conceived jointly with the adjacent Duncan College as part of Rice's vision for the 2nd century, which includes plans to increase the size of the student body by 30%.<ref name=\"professor.rice.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.professor.rice.edu/professor/Size.asp?SnID=1197319469|title=Size : Rice University|author=|date=|work=Rice.edu|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref> The college opened on August 16, 2009.\n\nDespite its status as a young college, McMurtry has already established its own unique culture. During the Spring 2009 Beer Bike, McMurtry was christened in the ''Thresher'' newspaper as the \"Mongol College\", as it had not been finished at the time yet it was involved in pranks during Willy Week, and it could not be pranked by any other college as McMurtry wasn't complete. This was due to O-Week coordinators and advisers and co-advisers of McMurtry (chosen a semester ahead) showing their spirit for the upcoming new college. McMurtry has been assuming much of this \"Mongol\" culture by referring to the round commons as \"Yurt,\" a name that also references the fact that due to construction delays caused by Hurricane Ike, McMurtry was forced to use a tent as its commons for weeks until the actual commons was completed. McMurtry is also known as the banana college, and the fruit is used as a popular symbol by students, including in college cheers like \"McMurtry is bananas, B-A-N-A-N-A-S.\"\n\nThe building was designed by [[Hopkins Architects]], a leading English firm specializing in sustainable architecture. It offers 324 beds for student housing. The college is constructed as a single, squared-off horseshoe-shaped wing surrounding a central quad, rising to a height of five stories. The college has double and single rooms that open directly out onto interior hallways, in contrast to the exterior hallways at Martel and Wiess, which were previously the two most recently renovated colleges. Common showers are located around the stairwells at each \"elbow\" in the building, and fully functional pod bathrooms are located in each double bedroom. The first floor contains study rooms, a game room, music room, other amenities, and the only circular commons on campus.\n\nMcMurtry College is across from Duncan Hall and the Inner Loop road. Duncan College is immediately north of it, connected to McMurtry by West Servery, which is parallel to Abercrombie Engineering Laboratory. It is also identical to Duncan College. The pair are commonly referred to as McDuncan.{{clear right}}\n\n== Duncan College ==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Duncan College\n| shield =\n| shield_size = 100px\n| established = 2009\n| namesake = Anne and Charles Duncan\n| magisters =  Caleb and Brandy McDaniel\n| president =  Louis Cole\n| chief_justice = Byron Benjamin Harris\n| membership = 420\n| motto = Classis et Germanitas (Team and Family)\n<!-- | demonym = Duncaroo -->\n| colors = Forest Green {{Color box|#014421|border=darkgray}} Ivory {{Color box|#FFFDD0|border=darkgray}} Gold {{Color box|#D4AF37|border=darkgray}} \n| location = 1601 Rice Blvd., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://duncan.rice.edu duncan.rice.edu]\n}}\n\n'''Anne and Charles Duncan College''' is the eleventh college founded as part of Rice's residential college system.<ref name=\"11th\">{{Cite web | title = Duncan College to be Rice\u2019s 11th Residential College | work = The Collegiate Way: Residential Colleges & the Renewal of University Life | author = R. J. O'Hara | date = 2007-08-21 | accessdate = 2009-03-30| url = http://collegiateway.org/news/2007-duncan-college}}</ref> Duncan College was named after Anne and [[Charles Duncan, Jr.]], long-standing contributors to Rice University who donated money for the new college. The college was conceived jointly with the adjacent McMurtry College as part of Rice's Vision for the 2nd century, which includes plans to increase the size of the student body by 30%.<ref name=\"professor.rice.edu\"/> Duncan opened its doors on August 16, 2009, right in time for O-Week 2009, which saw the arrival of the first Duncan freshman class. Due to renovations in Baker College and in order to help the new college adapt to the university, Baker College students lived in Duncan with the first freshman class. This led to the joint name of \"BaDunc\" for sporting and other events. Duncan began to operate by itself beginning in fall 2010 with a new freshman class, a returning sophomore class, and upperclassmen consisting of students from other colleges who accepted invitations to transfer. The college's first Masters, Marnie Hylton and Luis Duno-Gottberg, remained with Duncan for several years, and the final constitution went through its final stages before approval. It has also chosen its colors as forest green, white, and gold. It chose government officials, RAs, and a College Coordinator in the spring of 2010, and the crest was revealed during the fall 2010 semester at the dedication ceremony.\n\nDue to the request and contribution of Anne and Charles Duncan, Duncan College is one of the \"greenest\" buildings on Rice campus, as well as the entire city of Houston. Like nearby McMurtry College, the five-story building was designed by [[Hopkins Architects]] of London and offers 324 beds for student housing. The building is the first gold-level [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design]] (LEED) facility at Rice and the first LEED student residential-housing in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Duncan to receive LEED gold status |work = The Rice Thresher | accessdate = 2009-03-30 | url = http://the.ricethresher.org/news/2007/10/05/duncan_leed_gold#header }}</ref> The facility is designed to retain water for irrigation purposes and has motion detector lights which will turn on or off according to the flow of people. The building will decrease energy consumption by up to 25% as well as cut back on water usage. Air conditioners power off when windows are opened.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Rice announces $30M gift, plans for 'greenest' building yet | work = News and Media Relations, Rice University | date = 2007-08-21 | accessdate = 2009-03-30 | url = http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=9881&SnID=37427}}</ref>\n\n[[File:WR FLAG AS MY BLANKET.jpg|left|thumb| One of Duncan's favorite traditions is stealing Will Rice's flag.  Below is the flag draped across the bed of a certain Duncan lad in the Spring of 2016.]]\n\nDuncan College has also established a Monday night tradition, known as \"Monday Night Lights.\" When a few students went down to play ping-pong one night, they noticed that the ping pong table they had played on actually belonged to Baker College, who took its table back. Instead of going to bed, they made a makeshift table in the quad out of extra tables and using toilet paper as the net. People noticed the table and came down to the quad join in, watch and even play acoustic instruments. Monday Night Lights is now a monthly event. Other traditions include \"Duncing\" people in the DuncTank outside the commons on their birthdays, temporarily borrowing prized artifacts from other colleges including Will Rice's flag and Jones' trampoline, and a once a semester Nerf Gun capture the flag game throughout the building called Donnybrook.\n\nArchitecturally, Duncan has the same features as McMurtry with minor differences emphasized in order to establish its uniqueness. For example, Duncan Commons is rectangular in shape, contrasting the round McMurtry Commons. Also, Duncan quad has different features from McMurtry, such as a fountain by the Commons, smaller trees, and walkways that go across the quad. The interior, however, is virtually the same, as both colleges contain mostly doubles in the hallways and single rooms in the corners, with doubles having a pod bathroom inside and singles sharing common bathrooms. Both also have green roofs and fifth floor doubles and suites that open to the outside. The interior hallways of both Duncan and McMurtry were designed as contrasts to the other two most recently built residential colleges, Martel and Wiess, which have exterior hallways. The pair of McMurtry and Duncan are commonly referred to as McDuncan.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Texas}}\n* [http://students.rice.edu/students/Colleges.asp Residential College homepage]\n* [http://www.ruf.rice.edu/~program/beerbike/ About Beer Bike]\n* [http://beerbike.com/ Beer Bike History and Statistics]\n* [http://www.rice.edu/fondren/woodson/archives/willricecollege.html Will Rice College at the Woodson Research Center]\n* [http://www.edesigns-graphics.com/wiess/index.html Photographic study of Old Wiess]\n\n{{Rice University}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Residential Colleges Of Rice University}}\n[[Category:Rice University]]\n[[Category:University and college dormitories in the United States]]\n[[Category:Lists of university and college buildings in the United States|Rice University residential colleges]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n<!--  Commented out: [[File:Rice University seal.png|thumb|right|200px|The academic seal of Rice University]] -->\n[[Rice University]] contains '''eleven [[residential colleges]]''' which function as the primary housing, dining, and social organizations for undergraduate students. The system was established in 1957 and was inspired by the residential college systems at the [[University of Oxford]] and the [[University of Cambridge]] as well as the American adaptations of the same at [[Harvard]] and [[Yale]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/29/education/edlife/cornellweber3.html |title=The Residential Collage |website=The New York Times |date=July 29, 2007 |first=Bruce |last=Weber}}</ref> Each student is randomly affiliated with a residential college upon matriculation and becomes a lifetime member of the college.<ref name=\"Collage\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.professor.rice.edu/professor/Student_Life.asp |title=Student Life |publisher=Rice University |accessdate=2008-11-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218194538/http://www.professor.rice.edu/professor/Student_Life.asp |archivedate=2008-12-18 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://students.rice.edu/students/Colleges.asp |title=Residential Colleges |publisher=Rice University |accessdate=2009-04-11}}</ref> The residential college system takes the place of a [[Greek system]] and has contributed to a sense of community that other universities have sought to emulate.<ref name=\"Pride\">{{cite news|title=A place known as Rice: Students take great pride in college system |date=August 31, 1997 |website=Houston Chronicle |last=Lum |first=Lydia}}</ref><ref name=\"Community\">{{cite news|title=Rice undergrads share a sense of community: University's self- governing residential college |website=Houston Chronicle |last=Garza |first=Cynthia Leonor |date=March 5, 2007 | url = http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl?id=2007_4305297}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Universities Try Teaching Beyond the Classrooms |date=December 21, 1986 |website=The Philadelphia Inquirer |page=B3}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Turn Dorms into College 'Communes', UM Advised |publisher=Miami Herland |date=January 22, 1985 |page=2B}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=U. Mississippi eyes residential colleges |date=April 14, 2006 |publisher=University Wire |last=Livingston |first=Justin}}</ref>\n\nAt academic ceremonies, including matriculation and commencement, the colleges proceed first with the four original colleges in the order Baker, Will Rice, Hanszen, and Wiess, followed by the other colleges in order of founding: Jones, Brown, Lovett, Sid Richardson, Martel, McMurtry, and Duncan. For the original four colleges, which were founded simultaneously in 1957, the processional order reflects the order in which the original buildings were constructed. For McMurtry and Duncan, which were constructed and opened simultaneously in August 2009, the processional order reflects the order in which the founding gifts were made.\n\nThe colleges are often classified by geographical location: Jones, Brown, Martel, McMurtry, and Duncan are the '''North colleges'''; Baker, Will Rice, Hanszen, Wiess, Lovett, and Sid Richardson are the '''South colleges'''.\n\n== History of the college system ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2009}}\n\nThe residential college system was instated in 1957 by converting East, South, West, and North Halls into the men's colleges of Baker, Will Rice, Hanszen, and Wiess, respectively.<ref name=\"rice.edu\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rice.edu/sallyport/2007/fall/features/WhatsyourCollege.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-02-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091023110645/http://www.rice.edu/sallyport/2007/fall/features/WhatsyourCollege.html |archive-date=2009-10-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Jones, the first residential college built on campus for that purpose, was constructed the same year and became the singular women's college. Brown, Lovett, and Sid Richardson colleges composed the initial expansion founded between 1965 and 1971. To cope with increasing enrollment,<ref>[http://www.professor.rice.edu/professor/Enrollment-Total_Full_and_Part-Time.asp?SnID=2 Total enrollment '96-'08]{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Martel, McMurtry, and Duncan colleges were constructed in the period between 2001 and 2009. Today, when undergraduates are asked where they are from, many respond with the name of their college, not their home state. This is a testament to the centrality of the residential college system to the social life on the Rice campus.\n\n==Common characteristics==\n\n=== Architecture ===\n\nEach college except Sid Richardson is built around a [[quadrangle (architecture)|quadrangle]], which serves as the central court of the college.\n\nEach college building includes three principal structures:\n\n* A residential building, where on-campus members of the college live.  In addition to student rooms in various configurations, the building includes at least two apartments for resident associates.  Resident associates are typically junior faculty members; their role is to serve as mentors and counselors to the students of the college.\n* A house, usually immediately adjacent to the residential building, in which the college Magister or Magisters live.  A Magister is typically a tenured or other senior faculty member who lives at the college with his or her spouse, providing leadership and guidance to the college as a whole and to individual students. (Historically the term Master was reserved for faculty members, while a non-faculty spouse held the title Co-Master. Today, both spouses are known as Magisters.)\n* A commons, where college members (including on-campus and off-campus students, Magisters, resident associates, and non-resident associates from the faculty and the community) take their meals and conduct other activities of college life, including study groups, lectures, theatrical productions, and parties. In addition to a large multi-purpose dining hall, each commons typically includes an administrative office, a private dining room for small group meetings, and other specialized areas.\n\nEach college has a unique architectural style, and as a result there are a great number of different room configurations, with varying levels of modernity and condition.\n\nEach college is also connected to a dining hall, known as a servery. Martel, Jones, and Brown colleges are served by the North Servery, while McMurtry and Duncan are served by the West Servery. In the South, Hanszen and Wiess colleges are served by the South Servery, and Will Rice and Lovett Colleges are served by the Seibel Servery. Baker and Sid Richardson each have their own servery, called college kitchens.\n\n=== Magisters and Resident Associates ===\n\nEach of the residential colleges at Rice has two College Magisters,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ricethresher.org/article/2017/04/master-title-changed-to-magister|title='Master' title changed to 'Magister'|work=The Rice Thresher|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref> a faculty member and his or her spouse. The Magisters reside in a home adjacent to the college, and help cultivate a variety of cultural and intellectual interests among the students, as well as support an effective system of self-government. They administer the college and serve as liaisons between the students of the college and Rice.\n\nResident Associates (RAs) are Rice faculty or staff members who reside on campus with students. While each college has many associates, the RAs are selected to live on campus at the college to interact more extensively with the students. They live in apartment suites at the colleges, regularly attend meals with students, and are generally active members of student life. McMurtry College and Duncan College, due to their population size, also have Head Resident Fellows, who are meant to ease communication between RAs, the Magisters, and the students.\n\nTwo of the longest-serving resident associates in Rice history are Dr. Gilbert Cuthbertson, professor of political science and resident associate at Will Rice College, and [[William L. Wilson (Rice University)|Dr. Bill Wilson]], professor of electrical engineering and resident associate at Wiess College.\n\n=== Governance ===\nEach college is in charge of an annual budget in excess of $50,000 and elects a government from its students to administer the college and the budget. The college governments can exert control over everything from event organization to upgrades to the college facilities. Governing documents for many of the colleges can be found online.<ref>[http://willrice.org/whitepaper/constitution-final-0409v1.pdf Will Rice Constitution]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://jones.rice.edu/files/constitution.pdf |title=Jones Constitution |access-date=2009-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080510134440/http://jones.rice.edu/files/constitution.pdf |archive-date=2008-05-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.brown.rice.edu/govt/policies?id=1&print=1 Brown Constitution]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lovett.rice.edu/docs/government.pdf|title=Rice University -- Web Services|work=Rice.edu|access-date=March 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605000548/http://www.lovett.rice.edu/docs/government.pdf|archive-date=2010-06-05|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sidrichardson.net/node/41|title=Sid Richardson Constitution|author=|date=|work=SidRichardson.net|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.martel.rice.edu/parliament.cfm?doc_id=9425 |title=Martel Constitution |access-date=2009-05-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070912051239/http://martel.rice.edu/parliament.cfm?doc_id=9425 |archive-date=2007-09-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Singular student presidents and chief justices are university mandated features of each college's government. Additional members vary per college, but typically include Treasurer, Secretary, and a plurality of representatives from each class. The executive officers, such as the President, Treasurer, and Secretary, form the Executive council, and the representatives combine with the council to form the college government, known by names such as Cabinet or Parliament, depending on the college. These councils meet weekly to dispense with business related to the organizational and social functioning of the college. The meetings are akin to town hall meetings and typically include refreshments; they also serve as a forum for members of the various clubs, theater groups, and intramural sporting clubs to announce and advertise upcoming events. In addition, each college elects and sends one senator to represent the college at the Student Association.\n\n=== Traditions ===\n{{see also|Traditions and student life at Rice University}}\n\nThe traditional campus-wide [[Beer Bike]] competition is the largest annual student event held on Rice campus and the source of many rivalries and traditions among the residential colleges.<ref name=\"Roll\">{{cite news|title=Letting the good times roll at Rice: Beer Bike's 50th bash |website=Houston Chronicle |date=April 14, 2007 |page=1 |last=Viren |first=Sarah}}</ref> In recent years, a tradition has emerged wherein the Sid Richardson men's team intentionally disqualify themselves using any of a variety of means, most recently with a fire extinguisher-powered \"rocket bike.\" Sid Richardson has been disqualified in at least one race each year since 2000, with the exception of 2003 and 2007 when the biking was replaced with running due to inclement weather. On the other end of this spectrum, Will Rice is known as the most competitive of the residential colleges and the only one to ever \"sweep\" (win the mens, women, and alumni race). However, Martel College is undefeated in Men's Beer Runs (alternate race due to inclement weather)\n\n==Baker College==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Baker College\n| established = 1957\n| namesake = James Addison Baker (1857{{endash}}1941)\n| president = James Alex Warner\n| chief_justice = Varsha Varghese\n| membership = 360 (approximate)\n| mascot = Devil\n| colors = Red {{Color box|#990000|border=darkgray}} Black {{Color box|#000000|border=darkgray}} Silver {{color box|#C0C0C0}}\n| location = 6320 Main St., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = {{URL|baker.rice.edu}}\n}}\n\n'''James Addison Baker College''' is named in honor of [[James A. Baker (born 1857)|Captain James A. Baker]], friend and attorney of [[William Marsh Rice]], and first chair of the Rice Board of Governors. He served as the Rice Institute's first chairman on the Board of Trustees from June 24, 1891, until his death in 1941.  He is known for having helped unravel the conspiracy surrounding the murder of the millionaire, who was chloroformed by his butler, Charles F. Jones, on September 23, 1900. The suspicious death of the Rice founder was concocted by Albert T. Patrick, a New York attorney, who forged a will naming himself the primary beneficiary to the large fortune, enlisting the Butler's help. Captain Baker, however, began an intensive investigation into the death of his employer, discovering the forgery, and returning the foundation to what would become Rice University.<ref name=\"Baker College\">{{cite web|title=Baker College|url=http://bakercollege.net/about.html|accessdate=21 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120109165927/http://bakercollege.net/about.html|archivedate=9 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the university's original on-campus housing for male students, a dormitory (South Hall, now part of Will Rice College) and a dining room, library and residential tower (now part of Baker College) were built in 1912 by Cram, Goodhue, & Ferguson of Boston, Massachusetts, at the cost of $137,544.52. The now-Baker commons\u2014with beautiful engraved oak beams and the high vaulted ceilings of Elizabethan design\u2014served as the university's central dining hall for 43 years. East Hall, which contained dormitories and is now referred to as the \"Old Wing\" of Baker, was completed in summer 1915 (and West Hall (the \"Old Wing\" of Hanszen College) was completed in 1916).<ref name=\"ricehistoricalsociety.org\">http://ricehistoricalsociety.org/images/cornerstones/wrc06723.pdf</ref> These buildings remained virtually unchanged until the residential college system was instated in 1957. The [[neoclassical architecture]] of the former East Hall was joined by a new two-story brick-colored wing, the design of which was shared with equivalent new sections being constructed at Will Rice and Hanszen colleges, in preparation for becoming residential colleges. A house for Baker's Magister was also added. Baker was thus established as one of the five original colleges at Rice in the fall of 1957. In 1973, Baker and Hanszen became the first [[co-educational|co-ed]] colleges at Rice. To include upperclass women, a lottery was held for Jones and Brown women to transfer into Baker.\n\nBaker's colors are traditionally red, silver, and black, and the college associates itself with the [[devil]] and [[hell]] in its Beer Bike themes and college cheers, with the most popular cheer being \"Baker, hell yeah!\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Baker College Traditions |url=http://bakercollege.net/about_traditions.html |accessdate=2011-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110627065544/http://bakercollege.net/about_traditions.html |archivedate=2011-06-27 }}</ref> The crest was selected, by popular vote, in 1958. The main design is derived from the family crest of Captain Baker's mother, with the owls across the shield indicating the connection to Rice University, and is inscribed with a phrase from Epictetus, which says \"[d]ifficulties are things that show what men are.\" <ref name=\"Baker College\"/> Every year, Baker throws the Baker 90's public party, held in the spring. Some of the biggest social traditions include Baker Christmas in September, the annual Christmas Tree brought home by the freshmen after their camping trip, the Baker Shakespearean play, and of course Baker 13.\n\nIn 2009, construction began on a new residential wing. A portion of the former New Section was renovated and turned over to Lovett College. Baker's new wing is located between the Old Section and the Inner Loop road, and brought with it renovations to Baker's kitchen and the college coordinator's office. It was officially opened back to Baker students in the fall semester of 2010, who returned after a year of co-living with students from Duncan College. \n{{clear right}}\n\n== Will Rice College ==\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Will Rice College\n| image = Will_Rice_College.jpg\n| caption = Will Rice College, with Old Dorm (1912) at left, the commons building at center, and the quadrangle and New Dorm (2009) at right.\n| shield =\n| shield_size = 200px \n| established = {{start date|1957}}\n| namesake = William Marsh Rice, Jr.\n| magisters = Matthew Bennett, Rebekah Bennett\n| president = Juliette Richert\n| chief_justice = Jake Lesher\n| membership = 400 (approximate) \n| mascot = Phoenix\n<!-- | demonym = Will Ricer -->\n| colors = Rust {{Color box|#800000|border=darkgray}} Gold {{Color box|#FFBF00|border=darkgray}}\n| location = 6330 Main Street, [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://willrice.rice.edu willrice.rice.edu]\n}}\n'''William Marsh Rice Jr. College''', commonly known as Will Rice, is named for William M. Rice, Jr., the nephew of the university's founder [[William Marsh Rice]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://willrice.rice.edu/pages/williammarsh.html|title=William M. Rice Jr.|last=Saron|first=Veronica Rae|date=|website=Will Rice College|access-date=April 16, 2018}}</ref> It incorporates Rice's first dormitory, South Hall, which was built in 1912.<ref name=\"ricehistoricalsociety.org\"/> Will Rice College began as an all-male college when Rice created its residential college system in 1957 and became [[Mixed-sex education|co-ed]] in 1978.\n\nWill Rice shares architectural styles with Baker and Hanszen colleges; all three possess white-painted \"old\" buildings and more modern \"new\" wings. Will Rice's ''Old Dorm'' (former South Hall) features a unique fifth-floor tower which has recently become known as ''The Perch''.{{Citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nThe symbol of Will Rice college is the [[Phoenix (mythology)|Phoenix]], depicted in rust and gold colors. Members of the college are known as ''Will Ricers''. The college commonly refers to itself as the \"college of Gods and Goddesses.\" The elected governing body of Will Rice, the ''Diet'', administers a university-sponsored annual budget of approximately $50,000 which supports social, athletic, and entertainment programs for the college's nearly 400 resident and non-resident members.\n\nWill Rice is traditionally a strong contender in the university's annual campus-wide Beer Bike competition among the residential colleges. Will Rice has held the longest winning streak on record in the alumni race (11 years from 1996 to 2006).{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} Since the inclusion of an alumni race, Will Rice has been the only college to have won the men's, women's, and alumni races in a given year, called a \"sweep,\" which it has done on five occasions\u20141983, 1986, 1999, 2009, and 2013.<ref name=\"BB Stats\">{{Cite web | accessdate = 2009-03-31 | title = Beer-Bike Stats Galore | url = http://www.jencooper.com/jencooper/00sstats.htm}}</ref><ref name=\"Beer Bike 2013 Results\">{{cite web|url=http://rpc.rice.edu/beer-bike/beer-bike-results-2/ |title=Beer Bike 2013 results |accessdate=April 28, 2013 |publisher=Rice Program Council}}</ref> Additionally, Will Rice holds the current track records for the men's, women's, and alumni races.<ref name=\"BB Stats\" />\n\nIn 2009, work began on a new residential building for Will Rice, located on the site of the former New Section, built in 1957; this building was completely demolished.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://willrice.org/facilities.html|title=Facilities|website=willrice.org|access-date=2017-01-29}}</ref> A new servery, Abe and Anne Seibel Servery, was also part of the construction project. The new facility serves both Will Rice and Lovett, replacing two dated cafeterias at each college.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.architectmagazine.com/project-gallery/the-east-servery-rice-university_o|title=The East Servery, Rice University|last=|first=|date=|website=Architect Magazine|language=en|access-date=2017-01-29}}</ref> During construction, the population of Will Rice lived in McMurtry College, which was founded that year.\n\nNotable alumni include current [[CBS News]] president [[David Rhodes (CBS News President)|David Rhodes]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.rice.edu/2011/02/17/rice-alum-david-rhodes-takes-charge-at-an-american-institution-cbs-news/|title=Rice alum David Rhodes takes charge at an American institution, CBS News|website=news.rice.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref> former [[Major League Baseball]] player [[Lance Berkman]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.riceowls.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/063015aab.html|title=Berkman Inducted Into College Baseball Hall of Fame|last=|first=|date=|work=|publisher=Rice Owls|language=en|access-date=2017-01-30|via=}}</ref> and architect Charles Renfro of [[Diller Scofidio + Renfro]].<ref>http://www.ricethresher.org/article/2014/03/shepherd-to-build-new-opera-house-in-west-lot</ref>\n{{clear right}}\n\n== Hanszen College ==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Hanszen College\n| shield =\n| shield_size = 200px\n| established = 1957 (Original building constructed in 1919)\n| namesake = Harry Clay Hanszen\n| magisters = Paul Brace, Klaudia Brace<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2009/02/27/News/Griffins.To.Replace.Morrises.As.Hanszen.Masters.In.Fall-3651201.shtml |title=Griffins to replace Morrises as Hanszen masters in fall |publisher=Rice Thresher |last=Clemmons |first=Margeux |date=February 27, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409024745/http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2009/02/27/News/Griffins.To.Replace.Morrises.As.Hanszen.Masters.In.Fall-3651201.shtml |archivedate=April 9, 2009 }}</ref>\n| president = Landon Mabe\n| chief_justice = Nikhita Gangla \n| membership = 350 (approximate)\n| mascot = The Guardian\n<!-- | demonym = Hanszenite -->\n| colors = Royal Blue {{Color box|#4169E1|border=darkgray}} Yellow {{Color box|#FFEF00|border=darkgray}}\n| location = 6350 Main St., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://hanszen.rice.edu/ hanszen.rice.edu]\n}}\n[[File:Hanszen-new-section.jpg|left|thumb|The new wing of Hanszen college]]\n'''Harry Clay Hanszen College''' was named for a benefactor to the university and chairman of the Rice Board of Governors from 1946 to 1950.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.utexas.edu/taro/ricewrc/00077/rice-00077.html |title=Guide to the Rice University Harry Clay Hanszen College Records, 1963-2006 |publisher=Rice University Archives}}</ref> Hanszen's \"Old Wing\" was known as West Hall when it was built in 1916 as a part of the original campus construction plan by Boston architectural firm [[Cram, Goodhue & Ferguson]].<ref name=\"ricehistoricalsociety.org\"/> A new housing wing was built in 1957 in conjunction with the development of the [[residential college]] system at Rice in response to the expanding undergraduate enrollment.<ref name=\"Architecture\"/>\n\n[[KTRU-LP|KTRU Rice Radio]], the university's student-run radio station, and Rice Coffeehouse both began at Hanszen College.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nrcdxas.org/articles/KTRUtakeover.html |title=Spin Control The original name of the Rice Coffee House was \"The Corner of the Dreaming Monkey\".  Rice University's slow, systematic makeover of KTRU is just the latest example of a college determined to pattern itself after corporate America |first=Lauren |last=Kern |publisher=Houston Press |date=January 11, 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futureowls.rice.edu/futureowls/Hanszen.asp |title=Prospective Students - Hanszen College |publisher=Rice University |accessdate=2009-04-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409152823/http://www.futureowls.rice.edu/futureowls/Hanszen.asp |archivedate=2009-04-09 }}</ref> Hanszen was the first residential college at Rice to use its own crest. Shortly after the founding of the residential college system, the students created the blue, black, and yellow crest that in time became the symbol of the college, setting a precedent for the other colleges.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rice.edu/sallyport/2007/fall/features/Hanszen_College.html |title=Hanszen College |publisher=Rice Sallyport |date=Fall 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326101802/http://www.rice.edu/sallyport/2007/fall/features/Hanszen_College.html |archivedate=2009-03-26 }}</ref>\n\nHanszen often hosts guest lecturers; recent visitors include [[College World Series]] champion Coach [[Wayne Graham]], former Rice president and renowned economist [[S. Malcolm Gillis]], Kinder Institute for Urban Research director Stephen Klineberg, ''[[Texas Monthly]]'' senior editor and Hanszen alumnus Paul Burka (class of 1963), former writer and executive producer of ''[[The Daily Show]]'' [[Adam Lowitt]], and senior editor of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' Dr. James Hamblin.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} University courses recently offered by Hanszen College have included Analytics in Sports, Spirituality in Film, and The Culture of Philanthropy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://courses.rice.edu/admweb/swkscat.main?p_action=CATALIST&p_acyr_code=2010&p_subj=HANS |title=Course Catalogue |publisher=Rice University |accessdate=2010-01-22}}</ref>\n\nHanszen College is governed by the ''Cabinet'', a body consisting of the Executive Board and class representatives elected by members of the college annually. The Cabinet supervises an annual budget of nearly $60,000, regulates the use of public spaces within the college, and serves as an official liaison between the College membership and the university administration.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}\n\nHanszen's theme song is [[Hanson (band)|Hanson's]] \"[[MMMBop]]\", believed to have been chosen due to the band and the college being homophones.{{clear right}}\n\n== Wiess College ==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Wiess College\n| shield =\n| shield_size = 200px\n| established = 1957 (original building constructed 1949)\n| namesake = Harry Carothers Wiess\n| magisters = Andrew Schaefer, Laura Schaefer\n| president = Lauren Biegel\n| chief_justice = Drew Keefer\n| membership = 305 (approximate)\n| mascot = The War Pig\n<!-- | demonym = Wiessman -->\n| colors = Goldenrod {{Color box|#FFCC33|border=darkgray}} Black {{Color box|#000000|border=darkgray}}\n| location = 6340 Main St., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://www.teamwiess.com/ teamwiess.com]\n}}\n[[File:WiessCommons.JPG|left|thumb|The commons at Wiess College]]\n\n'''Harry Carothers Wiess College''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|w|a\u026a|s}} was one of the original four colleges created when the residential college system was implemented in 1957. In 2002, Wiess became the only college at Rice to relocate from one building to another.  Wiess is currently the southwesternmost residential college, located adjacent to Hanszen and the South Power Plant.  Male and female members of Wiess College are known equally as ''Wiessmen''.\n\nWiess College is named for Harry Carothers Wiess (1887\u20131948), one of the founders and one-time president of [[Humble Oil]], now [[ExxonMobil]]. He was elected as a life member of the Board of Trustees of Rice University in 1944 and appointed vice-chairman in 1946. He left money for the construction of a new dorm after his death in 1948.<ref name=\"HSLRU\">{{Cite book|last=Delany |first=Colin |chapter=Strength of Identity: The History of Wiess College |title=The History of Student Life at Rice University |editor=Michael Raphael |year=1990 |page=161}}</ref><ref name=\"HC\">{{Cite news|title=Dedication of Wiess Hall At Rice Planned |website=Houston Chronicle |date=March 9, 1950}}</ref>\n\nWiess Hall was completed in 1949, but carried the name \"North Hall\" until its dedication in March 1950.<ref name=\"HC\"/> It was laid out as a W-shaped building, with three north\u2013south wings, joined on the north ends by a long east\u2013west spine, forming two open quadrangles.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schoeffler|first1=Lauren|title=Wiess College: Team Family Wiess|url=http://www.ricestandard.org/wiess-college-team-family-wiess/|website=The Rice Standard|publisher=Rice University|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> The building was two stories high except for the three-story center wing. The hall was designed to house about 200 students in 20 single and 90 double rooms. Each room at Wiess opened directly to an exterior walkway that wrapped around the entire building. This design incorporated two features that were innovative at the time: every room had a semi-private bathroom and every room (except room 228, which was reserved for freshmen) had windows on at least two sides\u2014an important adaptation in the years before air conditioning.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Dormitory Nears Completion |publisher=The Houston Post |date=July 25, 1949}}</ref>\n\nWiess Hall became Wiess College in 1957. Converting the dormitory into a college included the creation of two Resident Associate suites, construction of Wiess House, the home of the Master and family, and construction of the Wiess Commons (designed by Wiess undergraduate architecture students Tim \"Frog\" Barry and Dan Canty for a class project{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}), the eating hall and round-the-clock gathering space for college members.<ref>Box 1, Folder 8, Harry Carothers Wiess College Records, 1950-1999 WRCUAwiess, Woodson Research Center, Fondren Library, Rice University</ref>{{Original research inline|date=March 2009}}<ref name=\"HSLRU\"/>\n\nBecause of Wiess's outward-facing architecture, life at Wiess centered on the outdoors. The two quadrangles developed distinct characters.  The quad between the center and west wings became known as the \"Acabowl\" and was the center of the college's social and recreational activity.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} At various times students installed a trampoline (\"Aca-tramp\") or above-ground pool (\"Aca-pool\"). The other quadrangle, between the center and east wings, was known by analogy as the \"Backabowl\" and tended to be used for quieter activities, such as sunbathing.<ref name=\"FO-Wiess\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.futureowls.rice.edu/futureowls/Wiess.asp?SnID=963453189 |title=Prospective Students - Residential Colleges - Wiess College |publisher=Office of Admissions, Rice University |accessdate=2009-04-24}}</ref>\n\nThe original residential building suffered from rapid deterioration in the 1990s.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} In 2002, the university opened a new building for the college, located south of the original building. New Wiess encloses a single large quadrangle, which retains the \"Acabowl\" name. The new building also preserved what Wiessmen considered a salient feature of the old:  the fact that all rooms at Wiess open directly onto exterior walkways or balconies.<ref name=\"Wiess opens\">{{cite news|title=Wiess College celebrates its new building at Oct. 5 dedication ceremony |url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=2422&SnID=2 |first=Jennifer |last=Evans |publisher=Rice News |date=October 2, 2002 |quote=Most important to Wiessmen, however, is that the new building includes many of the elements that made Old Wiess so distinct: motel-style suites, external balconies and an enclosed courtyard or 'Acabowl'.}}</ref> A glass-walled commons forms the north side of the Acabowl, with three four-story residence wings forming the other sides.  The portion of the Acabowl immediately adjacent to the commons is known as the Acaterrace.  The original Wiess Hall and its adjoining commons were razed during the winter break between Fall 2002 and Spring 2003.\n\nWiess considers itself to have an intense community spirit,<ref name=\"FO-Wiess\"/><ref name=\"Wiess opens\"/> signified by the slogan and cheer \"Team Wiess\", which has been used consistently since the 1970s.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Continuing the Wiess Tradition: New College Under Way With Reflections on Past |publisher=Rice News |url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=3769&SnID=2 |first=Philip |last=Montgomery |date=October 14, 1999 |quote=It is not just a catchy slogan, but it is the core idea of what Wiess is all about. It is this culture of community that ceremony is all about. This isn't just about building a new building. It is about the perseverance of the Team Wiess culture as we make the transition to this new building'.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607151143/http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=3769&SnID=2|archivedate=June 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAspects of Wiess life include Tabletop Theater, the Ubangee, pumpkin caroling, [[Night of Decadence]], ''Hello, Hamlet!'', the turning of the statue of university founder [[William Marsh Rice]], the [[Pace Mannion]] fan club, and the War Pig.<ref name=\"Wiess opens\"/><ref>http://www.futureowls.rice.edu/futureowls/Wiess.asp?SnID=963453189</ref>\n\nOne of the most influential persons in Wiess history was electrical engineering professor Bill Wilson, who served as resident associate from 1978 to 2006 and as interim Master in 1982\u201383, which was also the year in which Wiess became a co-ed college.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}  Wilson, known to generations of students as Dr. Bill, was a fixture of Rice's college system and the keeper of many Wiess traditions.  In addition to his many teaching awards, he is the only person to have won the Student Association's Mentor Recognition Award twice.  After his unexpected death in January 2009, his memorial service was held at the Wiess commons.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bill Wilson joins ranks of Emeritus Faculty |publisher=Rice News |date=June 29, 2006 |url=http://www.ece.rice.edu/wlwemeritus06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720002148/http://www.ece.rice.edu/wlwemeritus06 |archivedate=July 20, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dr. Bill receives Salgo award |publisher=Rice News |date=May 11, 2006 |url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=8540&SnID=641215845}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bill Wilson Celebrates 20 Years at Wiess With His 'Family' |publisher=Rice News |date=April 8, 1999 |url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=3633}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=Rice News |url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=12022&SnID=587347775 |title=Memorial service set for 'Dr. Bill' Saturday |first=Jade |last=Boyd |date=January 23, 2009}}</ref>  In December 2009, the Rice board of Trustees, with the consent of Wiess College, decided that the new Masters' residence at Wiess will be named Wilson House, in honor of Dr. Bill.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wiess Masters House to be named in honor of Wilson |publisher=Rice News |date=January 15, 2010 |url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=13580}}</ref>  Dedicated on March 11, 2011, Wilson House is the first building at Rice named after a college Master or Resident Associate, and the first Masters' residence to bear a name distinct from that of its associated college.\n\nNotable Wiessmen include Walter Loewenstern (1958),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=10449|title=Rice University News & Media - Rice University News & Media|author=|date=|work=Rice.edu|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref> [[Harold Solomon]], [[Ricky Pierce]] (1982), and [[Anthony Rendon]].\n{{clear right}}\n\n== Jones College ==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Jones College\n| shield = \n| established = 1957\n| namesake = Mary Gibbs Jones\n| magisters = Jason Hafner, Jennifer Trotter\n| president = Hannah Kim\n| chief_justice = Aaron Pathak\n| membership = 325 (approximate)\n| mascot = [[Jabberwocky]], JIBACat (unofficial), Marley Mackenzie\n<!-- | demonym = Jonesian -->\n| colors = {{Color box|#1E90FF|border=darkgray}} Light Blue<br />{{Color box|#008000|border=darkgray}} Green<br />{{Color box|#501A80|border=darkgray}} Purple\n| location = 23 Sunset Blvd., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States|\n| homepage = [http://jones.rice.edu/ jones.rice.edu]\n}}\n\n'''Mary Gibbs Jones College''', built as the first women's dormitory at Rice University, is named after [[Mary Gibbs Jones]], wife of prominent Houston philanthropist [[Jesse Holman Jones]].  Jesse H. Jones supported its initial construction with a $1 million donation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jones.rice.edu/page/history |title=Jones College - History |publisher=Jones College, Rice University |accessdate=2009-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331094220/http://jones.rice.edu/page/history |archivedate=2009-03-31 }}</ref>\n\nThe college was built in 1957, consisting of two four-story structures named \"North\" and \"South.\" It was designed by architects Lloyd & Morgan. Not only was it the first housing for women on campus, it was also the first building designed specifically as a residential college and also the first building to be centrally air-conditioned. \nLloyd & Morgan used pink marble in the construction of Jones College to indicate its status as housing for female students.<ref name=\"Architecture\"/> In 2002, an additional four-story building, \"Central,\" was built in between North and South.<ref name=\"Expansion\">{{Cite web | title = Year of campus construction signals expansion at Rice U.| work = Houston Chronicle| date = 2002-06-06| author = Betty L. Martin| accessdate = 2009-04-06 | url = http://www.chron.com/CDA/archives/archive.mpl?id=2002_3553908}}</ref> The new building connects to both original buildings at every level except the ground floor (a short walk separates South and Central). The wing was designed by noted post-modern architect [[Michael Graves]].\n\nIn the early days, the culture of the all-female Jones College was quite conservative.<ref name=\"Community\"/>  At meals, each table had a hostess, and dinner was served family style. Strict rules were enforced by house mothers when men from the south colleges visited the female students. The students even had to abide by a strict curfew - 11 p.m. on weekdays and 2 a.m. on weekends.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n\nIn the 1970s, Jones began phasing out many of the strictest rules, and in the fall of 1980 Jones became co-ed.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} Male students from the south colleges were given the chance to apply for transfer to Jones. Lovett, another Rice residential college, went co-ed the same year, so many of the new Jones residents were former Lovett residents. Jones women who disagreed with the decision to go co-ed were allowed to transfer to Brown College, which remained all-female until 1987. In 2001, construction began on the new Jones Commons and Jones Central. The new Jones Commons opened for use in March 2002.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} Jones Central opened in August 2002. During the same time, Jones lost its parking lot to the newly constructed Martel College.\n\nJones' [[Students' union|student government]] is set up as a Cabinet comprising the Executive Officers, elected representatives from each floor, and one elected off-campus representative.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jones.rice.edu/page/cabinet |title=Jones College - Cabinet |publisher=Jones College, Rice University |accessdate=2009-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330221400/http://jones.rice.edu/page/cabinet |archivedate=2009-03-30 }}</ref> The Cabinet meets bi-weekly.\n\nJones is a college with an indoor setup which has two lounges on every floor. Jones is unique among the colleges due to its large number of singles. Jones also has four 4-single suites and two 6-single suites, along with regular doubles.\n\nPrevious Jones College Magisters include Dr. Franz Brotzen (former Rice University Dean of Engineering) and Dr. Robin Forman (former Rice University Dean of Undergraduates).\n\nNotable alumni from Jones include [[George P. Bush]] (1998),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/news/2000-08-11/78217/|title=Gorgeous George|author=|date=|work=AustinChronicle.com|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref> former [[Mayor of Houston]] [[Annise Parker]] (1978),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.rice.edu/2009/12/13/rice-alumna-annise-parker-elected-houston-mayor/|title=Rice alumna Annise Parker elected Houston mayor|author=|date=|work=Rice.edu|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref> and neuroscientist [[David Eagleman]] (1993).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.culture.rice.edu/Eagleman.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-03-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416155420/http://www.culture.rice.edu/Eagleman.aspx |archive-date=2016-04-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n{{clear right}}\n\n== Brown College ==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Brown College\n| shield =\n| shield_size = 200px\n| established = 1965\n| namesake = Margarett Root Brown\n| president = A Quokka\n| chief_justice = Frances Williamson \n| membership = 353\n| motto = Tende Bene Alta Pete\n| mascot = taylor morin\n<!-- | demonym = Brownie -->\n| colors = Maroon {{Color box|#800000|border=darkgray}} Gold {{Color box|#FFBF00|border=darkgray}}\n| location = 9 Sunset Blvd., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://www.brown.rice.edu/ brown.rice.edu]\n|masters=B.J. Fregly, Shirley Fregly}}\n[[File:BrownCommons.JPG|thumb|left|The new Brown College commons]]\n\n'''Margarett Root Brown College''' is currently the third largest of the eleven residential colleges at Rice, behind both McMurtry College and Duncan College. Founded in 1965 as an all-women's college, Brown became co-ed in 1987.\n\nThe history of Brown dates back to the early sixties, when Jones College was the only all women's college on campus.<ref name=\"Brown_history\">http://www.brown.rice.edu/about/history.php</ref> This caused such a severe housing shortage that some Rice women were housed in the dorms of nearby [[Texas Women's University]]. Through the generous $1 million donation of [[George R. Brown]] and his wife Alice Pratt Brown, a new women's residential college was established in the memory of their sister-in-law, Margarett Root Brown. Up until her death in 1985, Alice Pratt Brown was an active patron of the college, giving the college much of the furniture and art in the first floor lobbies and private dining room.\n\n[[File:BrownCollege.jpg|thumb|left|The old wing of Brown College]]\nIn the beginning, Brown College was filled primarily with women who had volunteered to leave Jones in order to start a new college. Brown had a housemother who lived in the [[Resident assistant|resident associate]]\u2019s apartment and required all women to check in and out of the building at night and on weekends. The first Master of Brown was [[Frank Vandiver]], who later became president of [[Texas A&M University|Texas A&M]]. In 1966 he resigned from Brown because of a \u201cscandal\u201d \u2013 the members of Brown voted to drink alcohol in their own rooms (provided they were of legal drinking age). Vandiver resigned because he considered it inappropriate behavior for young ladies.<ref name=\"Brown_history\"/>\n\nBrown was the last single-sex female college after Jones went co-ed in 1980; male members were first accepted into Brown in 1987.<ref name=\"Brown_history\"/> However, the community bathrooms on all floors remained coed {{dubious|date=November 2009}} until 1994, when the bathrooms were remodeled and separate facilities for men and women were built on each floor. Brown's main tower consists of mainly of double rooms whose residents share community bathrooms. Each floor also has one single room without a bathroom, as well as a double room with a bathroom, referred to as a suite. The new 4-story wing at Brown opened in 2002.<ref name=\"Expansion\"/> The new wing houses 56 additional students, making Brown the largest residential college on campus (it was previously the smallest) until the opening of McMurtry and Duncan. The new wing is made up of four-person suite, and each suite has four small single rooms, a large common room, and a private bathroom.<ref name=\"Brown_history\"/> Besides rooms, Brown offers other facilities. For instance, Brown's basement houses a communal laundry room and music practice rooms. Brown's first floor, referred to as \"Vator Lobby\" in reference to its use as an elevator lobby, contains a communal kitchen, a computer lab, couches, and amenities such as a projector and pool tables.\n{{clear right}}\n\n== Lovett College ==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Lovett College\n| shield =\n| established = 1968\n| namesake = [[Edgar Odell Lovett]]\n| magisters = Dr. Michael Gustin and Denise Klein\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.students.rice.edu/students/College_Masters.asp|title=College Masters : Rice University|author=|date=|work=Rice.edu|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| president = Chloe Oani\n| chief_justice = Laura Yordan\n| membership = 375 (approximate)\n| mascot = Stag\n<!-- | demonym = Lovetteer -->\n| colors = Navy Blue {{Color box|#000080|border=darkgray}} Yellow {{Color box|#FFEF00|border=darkgray}}\n| location = 6310 Main St., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://www.lovett.rice.edu/ lovett.rice.edu]\n}}\n[[File:Lovett.jpg|left|thumb|The residential building of Lovett College]]\n\n'''Edgar Odell Lovett College''' is the seventh-founded residential college, named after the university's first president.<ref name=\"Architecture\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Schwent |first1=J. |first2=G. |last2=Omid |year=2005 |title=Rice University College Prowler Off The Record |publisher=College Prowler, Inc.  |isbn=1-59658-107-7}}</ref>  Lovett opened in 1969 as an all-male college, becoming co-ed in 1980 when members of the college exchanged places with the female members of Jones College.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} Lovett's first class mostly comprised volunteers from other colleges. Lovett sponsors numerous community and social events throughout the year, including theater productions and the Lovett Undergraduate Research Symposium. Lovett's college crest is based upon the Lovat family crest<ref>Rice University Woodson Research Center Lovett College Records 1968-2007. Box 1, Folder 2</ref>{{Original research inline|date=April 2009}} although the Lovat family is not related to Edgar Odell Lovett.\n\n[[File:Lovett College being built.jpg|left|thumb|Lovett College during construction]]\nThe distinctive [[brutalist]] architecture of Lovett has led many to compare it to a giant [[toaster]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.rice.edu/collections/WRC/finding-aids/university-archives/lovett-college/ |title=Lovett College records, 1968-2007 |publisher=Fondren Library, Rice University |accessdate=2009-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423055450/https://library.rice.edu/collections/WRC/finding-aids/university-archives/lovett-college |archivedate=2009-04-23 }}</ref> This is due to the concrete grating that surrounds the third, fourth, and fifth floors, a design feature intended to make Lovett riot-proof in reaction to the student [[riot]]s of the late 1960s, most notably the [[Abbie Hoffman]] riot of 1967.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} Other riot-proofing features include the limited reach of the elevator, which does not reach the sixth floor, to prevent students from throwing furniture off of the only exposed higher floor, although that feature has not been completely successful in preventing furniture from being thrown from the building. Some have called Lovett's architecture style \"modern American prison\" because of the intersecting horizontal and vertical elements.\n\n\"The grating\" now protects Lovett students from hurricanes; in fall of 2005 Lovett students were among the only Rice students allowed to stay in their rooms during [[Hurricane Rita]] and [[Hurricane Ike]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} As a tongue-in-cheek homage to [[Communism]] and the purported Soviet architecture of the college, the men of the founding class named their college government the Central Committee.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} The main body of the crest was taken from the [[Clan Fraser of Lovat]] and modified by adding a stag to each side.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n\nLovett is made up of four buildings: a six-story residential building, an additional two-story residential building, which was acquired from Baker in fall of 2010, a single-story commons, and the Masters' house.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} All of these buildings are structurally connected but have separate entrances and spaces. The majority of the rooms in the residential building are two-person suites, connected in pairs by a shared bathroom. Lovett House is a full two-story home in which the masters reside. The masters often host dessert at their house for special occasions, as well as private Central Committee meetings. The Lovett basement contains a number of facilities for use by the college members, as well as storage space for the various committees. The basement has a game room with various gaming tables, a movie room with couches and a projector, a kitchen, computer room, music room, weight room, and other spaces. The Wiener Hole is Lovett's public study space. It contains the Lovett test file, which contains records of previous tests in various classes. Lyle's, named for former Lovett resident associate Lyle Angene and also known as the Lovett Undergrounds, is a combination bar and performance space located in Lovett's basement. Lyle's is equipped with a sound system, stage, and lights, as well as bar equipment, including a [[kegerator]]. Seating for more than two hundred people can be moved into the space for performances. Lovett Theater and various Rice-wide performance groups, such as the Rice Philharmonics and Spontaneous Combustion, often use Lyle's for their performances; it also often acts as a space for smaller private parties.\n\nIn 2009, work began on renovating a portion of Baker College's former New Section, which was transferred over to become Lovett's New Section starting in the 2010 fall semester.<ref>{{cite web\n |last=Swartz \n |first=Dale \n |title=Southern Reconstruction \n |work=The Rice Thresher \n |date=April 18, 2008 \n |url=http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2008/04/18/News/Southern.Reconstruction-3333058.shtml \n |accessdate=December 13, 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091210040321/http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2008/04/18/News/Southern.Reconstruction-3333058.shtml \n |archivedate=December 10, 2009 \n}}</ref> A new servery, shared with Will Rice College, was recently built as part of the construction project and named Seibel Servery.\n\nNotable alumni include [[James Casey (American football)|James Casey]], [[Luke Willson]], [[Jos\u00e9 Cruz, Jr.]],<ref>{{cite web\n |last=Fielder \n |first=Lindsey \n |title=Three with Rice ties to be inducted into the Texas Baseball Hall of Fame \n |work=Rice News \n |publisher=[[Rice University]] \n |date=October 23, 2003 \n |url=http://staff.rice.edu/staff/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=1867&SnID=2\n |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070515045514/http://staff.rice.edu/staff/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=1867&SnID=2\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=May 15, 2007\n |accessdate=March 30, 2009 \n}}</ref> [[John Doerr]],<ref>{{Cite web\n |title=John Doerr (Rice BSEE 1973, MSEE 1974) \n |accessdate=2009-03-31 \n |url=http://www.ece.rice.edu/aboutece/halloffame/hof_doerr \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100608040521/http://www.ece.rice.edu/aboutece/halloffame/hof_doerr \n |archivedate=2010-06-08 \n}}</ref> [[Brock Wagner]], [[John Kline (politician)|John Kline]], [[Ann Saterbak]], [[Alberto Gonzales]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=1796&SnID=2 |title=Alum Gonzales to give grads send-off |author=Jennifer Evans |date=12/11/2003 |accessdate=2009-08-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612172746/http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW |archivedate=2010-06-12 }}</ref> and [[Matt Anderson (baseball)|Matt Anderson]].<ref>{{Cite web\n |title=Berkman takes time to reflect on years at Rice \n |work=Sports, The Rice Thresher \n |date=2009-02-20 \n |accessdate=2009-03-31 \n |url=http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2009/02/20/Baseball09/Berkman.Takes.Time.To.Reflect.On.Years.At.Rice-3639269.shtml?refsource=collegeheadlines\n|archive-url=https://archive.is/20110817092628/http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2009/02/20/Baseball09/Berkman.Takes.Time.To.Reflect.On.Years.At.Rice-3639269.shtml?refsource=collegeheadlines\n|url-status=dead\n|archive-date=2011-08-17\n}}</ref> Nobel Laureate [[Robert Curl]] was the first college Master, and [[George H.W. Bush]] served as a community associate.<ref>{{Cite web \n| title = President Bush Slated as Commencement Speaker | work = Rice University, News & Media | date = 1999-09-30 | accessdate = 2009-03-31 | url = http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=3842&SnID=2}}</ref><ref>Raphael, Michael: ''The History of Student Life at Rice University: A Series of Papers'', Appendix A. Rice University Centennial Celebration Committee, 1990.</ref>\n{{clear right}}\n\n== Sid Richardson College ==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Sid Richardson College\n| shield =\n| established = 1971\n| namesake = [[Sid W. Richardson]]\n| magisters = Michel and Melanie Achard\n| president = Nia Prince\n| chief_justice = Johnston French \n| mascot = Tower\n| membership = 332\n| motto = Mors de Super\n<!-- | demonym = Sidizen -->\n| colors = Black {{Color box|#000000|border=darkgray}} Red {{Color box|#FF0000|border=darkgray}} Gold {{Color box|#FFEF00|border=darkgray}}\n| location = 6360 Main Street,\n[[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://sidrichcollege.org/ sidrichcollege.org]\n}}\n\n[[File:Sid Richardson College.jpg|thumb|Sid Richardson College as seen from the North side.]]\n\n'''Sid Richardson College''' (also referred to as '''Sid''', '''SRC''', or '''Sid Rich''') opened in 1971 as a men's residential college. Like the other residential colleges on the Rice campus, Sid Richardson College provides undergraduate residential and dining facilities, social organizations and student government, as well as faculty, alumni, and community associates. A $2 million pledge from the Sid Richardson Foundation, which was established by Texas oilman, cattleman, and philanthropist [[Sid W. Richardson]] (1891\u20131959), funded the construction of the college. The college became co-ed in 1987. Members of Sid Richardson College are called \"Sidizens.\"\n\nSid Richardson College is the tallest building on the Rice campus. It has seven floors, each of which is split into an upper and lower level, effectively giving the building fourteen stories. Unusual among Rice buildings, the {{convert|153|ft|m}} high-rise was a response to a shortage of University land and was designed by the architectural firm Neuhaus and Taylor.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Sid Richardson College records, 1969-2000 - Fondren Library | work = Fondren Library Woodson Research Center | accessdate = 2009-03-30 | url = http://library.rice.edu/collections/WRC/finding-aids/university-archives/sid-richardson-college#d0e59}}</ref> Sid Rich has enough beds to accommodate 229 students.<ref name=\"Community\"/> Original plans called for the eventual construction of a second tower, but the plan was never followed through.<ref name=\"Architecture\">{{Cite book| last1 = Fox | first1 = Stephen | last2 = Hester | first2 = Paul |title=Rice University: The Campus Guide |publisher=Princeton Architectural Press |year=2001 |isbn=1-56898-246-1}}</ref> In similar fashion to Lovett, the Sid Masters' house is connected to the residential tower; it comprises the first floor of the tower, while the [[Mezzanine (architecture)|mezzanine]] of the residential building is actually the second floor of the tower.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The Rice Network Infrastructure Project- Sid Richardson College Masters House |work=The Rice Network Infrastructure Project |accessdate=2009-03-30 |url=http://www.rice.edu/ricenet/buildings/sidmasters.php |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326072647/http://www.rice.edu/ricenet/buildings/sidmasters.php |archivedate=2009-03-26 }}</ref>\nThe first floor of Sid features a commons, a private dining room, and an OC (off-campus) lounge.  The lounge consists of a pool table{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}, a ping pong table{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}, and a television set.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nAlthough Sid Richardson College is not built around a quad, there is a similar outdoor feature of the college known as the \"country club.\"  The country club consists of a field, [[volleyball]] court, hammock, an adult-sized swing set, and many picnic tables.\n\n[[File:Earlysid.jpeg|thumb|left|A banner hung from Sid during a game against the [[Texas A&M University|Aggies]] copyright [[Michael Petry]]]]\n\nIn addition to providing basic residential and social services to its residents, Sid Richardson College is rich with traditions, which have included some notorious pranks.  For example, Sidizens have made use of the six balconies towering above the main entrance of the college to \"douche\" unsuspecting visitors\u2014including past Rice University president [[George Rupp]] and his wife\u2014with buckets of water as they climb the steps to the double doors. While such \"free-flowing water\" is the only sanctioned projectile, rogue students have also flung flour tortillas, shrimp, and, in one particularly infamous situation, a couch.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Berkman takes time to reflect on years at Rice |work=The Rice Thresher |author=Yan Digilov |date=2000-02-20 |accessdate=2009-03-30 |url=http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2009/02/20/Baseball09/Berkman.Takes.Time.To.Reflect.On.Years.At.Rice-3639269.shtml |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402025159/http://media.www.ricethresher.org/media/storage/paper1290/news/2009/02/20/Baseball09/Berkman.Takes.Time.To.Reflect.On.Years.At.Rice-3639269.shtml |archivedate=2009-04-02 }}</ref> During the mid-1970s, students moved a Karman Ghia automobile into the dining area. Photographic evidence can be found in the Rice Campanile.\n\nAnother prank that is quickly becoming a tradition is the [[Orc]] Raid.  Orc Raids are held twice every year - once during the Orientation Week in August before the start of the Fall semester and a second time during Willy Week in the Spring semester. Sidizens dress up by smearing themselves with black paint, wearing black clothes and carrying around torches with doll heads.  They then proceed to run around campus at night to terrorize the other colleges and crash events, often shouting out cheers that boost the morale of the Sidizens as well as anti-cheers meant to belittle the 'lesser' colleges.\n\nSid Richardson College has a wealth of traditions. Every Friday afternoon from 3:00-6:00pm, the college's main speakers, affectionately known as the \"stacks,\" blast music in what is known as \"Radio Free Sid\" (the named derived from [[Radio Free Europe]] of the [[Cold War]] era) across the campus from the 7th floor balcony. Radio Free Sid begins and ends each roughly 3-hour-long set of music with [[AC/DC]]'s [[Back in Black (song)|\"Back in Black,\"]] widely considered to be the college's theme song.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Golden Anniversary | accessdate = 2009-03-31 | url = http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=9432}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Sid Richardson College |accessdate=2009-03-31 |url=http://www.rice.edu/sallyport/2007/fall/features/SidRich_College.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326101800/http://www.rice.edu/sallyport/2007/fall/features/SidRich_College.html |archivedate=2009-03-26 }}</ref> Other traditions include Night of Innocence (a showing of Disney movies in the commons the same night as NOD), Sid 80s (Sid's fall public party), Sid Hi-Liter (spring public party), vatoring of Sidizens who co-advise, Floor Wars (a series of competitive events between the floors), Squid Richardson Day, and more.\n\nSid Richardson has also hosted the five Houston Conferences on Theoretical Neuroscience (2004-2009), thanks to a relationship between the GCC and former Sid Richardson Master Steve Cox.<ref>{{Cite web | title = GCC for Theoretical and Computational Neuroscience | work = The Gulf Coast Consortium | accessdate = 2009-03-30 | url = http://cohesion.rice.edu/centersandinst/gcc/neuro_about.cfm?doc_id=5726}}</ref>\n\nNotable alumni include [[Steve Jackson (US game designer)|Steve Jackson]], [[Philip Humber]], White House Press Secretary [[Josh Earnest]],<ref>http://m.ricethresher.org/news/article_ec6e0d2f-f553-553d-9716-4aa3d78a9f6c.html?mode=jqm{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and Mark Durcan,<ref>[http://www.linkedin.com/pub/mark-durcan/5/755/419 Durcan's profile on LinkedIn]</ref> CEO of [[Micron Technology]].\n{{clear right}}\n\n== Martel College ==\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Martel College\n| shield =\n| established = 2002\n| namesake = Marian and Speros P. Martel\n| magisters = Carrie Toffoletto, Frank Toffoletto\n| president = Paras Gupta\n| chief_justice = Chris Yau\n| membership = 350 (approximate)\n| mascot = Beer Goat\n<!-- | demonym = Martelian -->\n| colors = Azure (sky blue) {{Color box|#87CEEB|border=darkgray}}, argent (white) {{color box|white}}, maroon {{Color box|#78184A|border=darkgray}}\n| location = 99 Sunset Blvd., [[Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://www.martel.rice.edu/ martel.rice.edu]\n}}\n\n[[File:Martel Sallyport.jpg|left|thumb|Martel's [[sally port]]]]\n[[File:Martel Rotunda.jpg|left|thumb|The [[Rotunda (architecture)|rotunda]], with the sundeck]]\n[[File:Martel Commons.jpg|left|thumb|The cathedral-like Commons]]\n[[File:Beergoat.JPG|left|thumb|The infamous \"Beer Goat\" [[keg]] holder]]\n\n'''Marian and Speros P. Martel College''' is the ninth-founded residential college. It was established with a $15 million donation from the eponymous Marian and Speros Martel Foundation, a longtime benefactor of Rice University. The college's building was designed by noted architect [[Michael Graves]] and housed its first students during the 2002\u20132003 school year.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Michael Graves, FAIA | work = The American Institute of Architects | accessdate = 2009-03-30 | url = http://www.aia150.org/aw_gm_2001.php | archive-url = http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20090707112617/http://www.aia150.org/aw_gm_2001.php | archive-date = 2009-07-07 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref name=\"MartelNews\">{{Cite web | title = Welcoming in the Martel Era | work = Rice University, News & Media | date = 2000-04-06| accessdate = 2009-03-29 | url = http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=5210&SnID=2}}</ref>  Martel is one of [[List of Rice University residential colleges|eleven residential colleges]] at Rice University, and it is the only one that has a Sallyport of its own; it is located adjacent to Jones and Duncan colleges on the north side of [[Rice University#Campus|campus]], sharing the North Servery with the former. The college prides itself on its adopted Greek heritage, a tribute to its benefactors' country of origin. Aspects of Greek culture are incorporated into a number of college events, and an interior staircase of the college features a four-story map of Athens painted by Joshua Krezinski (class of 2007). The second and fourth quadrants of Martel's crest represent the cross and stripes of the [[Flag of Greece|Greek flag]], while the other two are reserved for the [[Athena#Cult and attributes|Athenian owl]], a symbol of wisdom taken from the university's academic seal, and the \"MC\" glyph representing the College's name. The crest was designed by the building's architect.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} The Martel College colors are representative of the Greek flag and the building's architecture. The [[blazon]] of the Greek flag is \"[[Azure (heraldry)|Azure]], four bars [[Argent]]; on a canton of the field a Greek cross throughout of the second.\" While azure often associates with a deeper blue, Martel College uses a lighter [[Tincture (heraldry)|tincture]] of azure known as [[bleu celeste]] or \"sky blue\". Also, the argent used by the college favors a bright, reflective white instead of the more silvery tincture. Maroon represents the building's brick and paint scheme. Members of Martel college are known as \"Martelians\".\n\nAs the third-most-recently founded residential college, Martel's history is short, and commonly includes the story of Speros Martel, the Greek immigrant whose estate provided the funding necessary to build the college.<ref name=\"Martel Website\">{{Cite web|title=Martel in the Beginning |work=Rice University |access-date=March 30, 2009 |url=http://martel.rice.edu/about.cfm?doc_id=9499 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517215807/http://martel.rice.edu/about.cfm?doc_id=9499 |archivedate=May 17, 2008 }}</ref> The official groundbreaking of the new Martel college took place on April 10, 2000. Among those attending were the newly instated Martel Magisters Joan and Arthur Few, who had previously been Masters at Baker College from 1994 to 1999.\n\nThe first new students accepted as members of Martel were required to live off campus during the fall 2001 semester until the completion of the College's construction, which was scheduled for early 2002. However, in June 2001, [[Tropical Storm Allison]] struck the Houston area and delayed this by two months.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} Applications for freshman transfers were made available in October 2002. Sixty-three freshmen were accepted, five each from Brown and Jones Colleges, and up to 12 from each of the other colleges. Martel members named physics instructor Gary Morris and intramural sports director Tina Villard as Martel's first resident associates.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Guide to the Rice University Martel College Records, 2000-2003 | work = Texas Archival Resources Online | accessdate = 2009-03-29 | url = http://www.lib.utexas.edu/taro/ricewrc/00241/rice-00241.html}}</ref>{{Original research inline|date=April 2009}}\n\nMartel's student government is named the Parliament, and meets weekly in the College commons. Elected officials include President, Vice President, Prime Minister, Treasurer, Secretary, Chief Justice, and Class Representatives (4 per class).\n\n[[Michael Graves]], architect of Martel College, designed the four-story, {{convert|134000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} building.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Images of Martel College, Rice University by Michael Graves| work = Digital Imaging Project, Bluffton University | author = Mary Ann Sullivan | accessdate = 2009-03-29 | url = http://www.bluffton.edu/~sullivanm/texas/houston/ricemartel/graves.html}}</ref>  Formed around a central quadrangle, Graves's design follows the style of the 1910 general plan of Boston architect [[Ralph Adams Cram]] for the Rice campus. Martel is an open, four-sided shape. Each side of the shape forms a wing of the college. The wings terminate on the side closest to North Servery in a five-story rotunda, a spiral staircase enclosed within a stack of rounded floors, providing the college with its sundeck, where many events are held. The easternmost wing contains common areas, the game room, a kitchen, and the TV room. The rotunda leads into the Commons, a cathedral-like room with a high ceiling that serves as a cafeteria, meeting room, and auditorium, among other functions.<ref name=\"Expansion\"/> The college also includes two apartments for Martel's resident associates and a neighboring house for the College Magisters and their family. Nearly every room at Martel is suite style, and is either referred to as a hex, or a quad. There are two kinds of hexes, sally port and corner hexes. Corner hexes have 6 single rooms and sallyport hexes have 3 double rooms. Every suite at martel has a private bathroom. Rooming is overseen by the Vice President. Martel is also the only college to feature a [[Sally Port|sally port]] in its construction; newly matriculated students traditionally walk through it passing a torch between themselves as the final step to becoming new Martelians.\n\nAlumni include [[Chris Boswell]], [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] kicker, [[Jason Colwick]], 2009 NCAA pole vault champion, Andrew Chifari, [[Starbucks]] most expensive drink record breaker,<ref>{{cite web | title = New Starbucks Free Drink Record Set With $54 Sexagintuple Vanilla Bean Mocha Frappuccino  | work = Consumerist | publisher = [[Consumer Reports]]| url = http://consumerist.com/2014/05/27/new-starbucks-free-drink-record-set-with-54-sexagintuple-vanilla-bean-mocha-frappuccino/ | accessdate = June 25, 2014}}</ref> Mithun Mansinghani, the Oklahoma Solicitor General,<ref>{{cite web | title = Alva native appointed to Attorney General's staff | publisher = Alva Review-Courier | url = http://www.alvareviewcourier.com/story/2017/03/19/local/alva-native-appointed-to-attorney-generals-staff/10864.html | accessdate = November 7, 2017}}</ref> and [[Morris Almond]], a professional basketball player.<ref>{{cite web | title = Jason Colwick Profile  | work = Official Website of Rice Athletics | publisher = [[Rice University]]| url = http://riceowls.cstv.com/sports/m-track/mtt/colwick_jason00.html | accessdate = March 31, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web  | last = Manfull | first = Megan | title = Owls athletics: Ryan Berry & Jason Colwick | work = [[Houston Chronicle]] | date = March 13, 2009| url = http://blogs.chron.com/owls/2009/03/owls_baseball_ryan_berry_take.html | accessdate = March 31, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Smooth Shooter|url=http://news.rice.edu/2006/11/16/smooth-shooter/|work=Rice News|publisher=Rice University News & Media|accessdate=21 February 2014}}</ref>\n{{clear right}}\n\n== McMurtry College ==\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = McMurtry College\n| shield =\n| established = 2009\n| namesake = Burt and Deedee McMurtry\n| magisters =  Margaret Beier, Chris Stickney<ref>{{cite web|title=College Masters|url=http://www.students.rice.edu/students/College_Masters.asp|website=Rice University|accessdate=17 September 2015}}</ref>\n| president =  Joyce Chen\n| chief_justice = Augi Liebster \n| membership = 420 (approximate)\n| mascot = Lion\n<!-- | demonym = Murts -->\n| colors = Royal Purple {{Color box|#2A0054|border=darkgray}} Silver {{color box|#C0C0C0}}\n| location = 1605 Rice Blvd., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://mcmurtry.rice.edu mcmurtry.rice.edu]\n}}\n\n'''Burt and Deedee McMurtry College''' is the tenth college founded as part of Rice's residential college system.<ref name=\"11th\"/> McMurtry College was named after Burt and Deedee McMurtry, graduates of the Rice class of 1956.<ref>{{Cite news\n |title=Record $32 million pledged to Rice, Student residences are just one cause to benefit from alumni couple's gift \n |work=Houston Chronicle \n |date=June 17, 2006 \n |first=Todd \n |last=Ackerman \n |url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Record-32-million-pledged-to-Rice-1911588.php \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ZfFxNIHn?url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Record-32-million-pledged-to-Rice-1911588.php \n |archivedate=June 30, 2015 \n |accessdate=June 29, 2015 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref> Burt McMurtry was part of the student-faculty committee that evaluated the need for and eventually instituted the college system at Rice University, beginning in 1957 with the original five colleges. The college was conceived jointly with the adjacent Duncan College as part of Rice's vision for the 2nd century, which includes plans to increase the size of the student body by 30%.<ref name=\"professor.rice.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.professor.rice.edu/professor/Size.asp?SnID=1197319469|title=Size : Rice University|author=|date=|work=Rice.edu|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref> The college opened on August 16, 2009.\n\nDespite its status as a young college, McMurtry has already established its own unique culture. During the Spring 2009 Beer Bike, McMurtry was christened in the ''Thresher'' newspaper as the \"Mongol College\", as it had not been finished at the time yet it was involved in pranks during Willy Week, and it could not be pranked by any other college as McMurtry wasn't complete. This was due to O-Week coordinators and advisers and co-advisers of McMurtry (chosen a semester ahead) showing their spirit for the upcoming new college. McMurtry has been assuming much of this \"Mongol\" culture by referring to the round commons as \"Yurt,\" a name that also references the fact that due to construction delays caused by Hurricane Ike, McMurtry was forced to use a tent as its commons for weeks until the actual commons was completed. McMurtry is also known as the banana college, and the fruit is used as a popular symbol by students, including in college cheers like \"McMurtry is bananas, B-A-N-A-N-A-S.\"\n\nThe building was designed by [[Hopkins Architects]], a leading English firm specializing in sustainable architecture. It offers 324 beds for student housing. The college is constructed as a single, squared-off horseshoe-shaped wing surrounding a central quad, rising to a height of five stories. The college has double and single rooms that open directly out onto interior hallways, in contrast to the exterior hallways at Martel and Wiess, which were previously the two most recently renovated colleges. Common showers are located around the stairwells at each \"elbow\" in the building, and fully functional pod bathrooms are located in each double bedroom. The first floor contains study rooms, a game room, music room, other amenities, and the only circular commons on campus.\n\nMcMurtry College is across from Duncan Hall and the Inner Loop road. Duncan College is immediately north of it, connected to McMurtry by West Servery, which is parallel to Abercrombie Engineering Laboratory. It is also identical to Duncan College. The pair are commonly referred to as McDuncan.{{clear right}}\n\n== Duncan College ==\n\n{{Infobox residential college\n| name = Duncan College\n| shield =\n| shield_size = 100px\n| established = 2009\n| namesake = Anne and Charles Duncan\n| magisters =  Caleb and Brandy McDaniel\n| president =  Louis Cole\n| chief_justice = Byron Benjamin Harris\n| membership = 420\n| motto = Classis et Germanitas (Team and Family)\n<!-- | demonym = Duncaroo -->\n| colors = Forest Green {{Color box|#014421|border=darkgray}} Ivory {{Color box|#FFFDD0|border=darkgray}} Gold {{Color box|#D4AF37|border=darkgray}} \n| location = 1601 Rice Blvd., [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], [[Texas]], United States\n| homepage = [http://duncan.rice.edu duncan.rice.edu]\n}}\n\n'''Anne and Charles Duncan College''' is the eleventh college founded as part of Rice's residential college system.<ref name=\"11th\">{{Cite web | title = Duncan College to be Rice\u2019s 11th Residential College | work = The Collegiate Way: Residential Colleges & the Renewal of University Life | author = R. J. O'Hara | date = 2007-08-21 | accessdate = 2009-03-30| url = http://collegiateway.org/news/2007-duncan-college}}</ref> Duncan College was named after Anne and [[Charles Duncan, Jr.]], long-standing contributors to Rice University who donated money for the new college. The college was conceived jointly with the adjacent McMurtry College as part of Rice's Vision for the 2nd century, which includes plans to increase the size of the student body by 30%.<ref name=\"professor.rice.edu\"/> Duncan opened its doors on August 16, 2009, right in time for O-Week 2009, which saw the arrival of the first Duncan freshman class. Due to renovations in Baker College and in order to help the new college adapt to the university, Baker College students lived in Duncan with the first freshman class. This led to the joint name of \"BaDunc\" for sporting and other events. Duncan began to operate by itself beginning in fall 2010 with a new freshman class, a returning sophomore class, and upperclassmen consisting of students from other colleges who accepted invitations to transfer. The college's first Masters, Marnie Hylton and Luis Duno-Gottberg, remained with Duncan for several years, and the final constitution went through its final stages before approval. It has also chosen its colors as forest green, white, and gold. It chose government officials, RAs, and a College Coordinator in the spring of 2010, and the crest was revealed during the fall 2010 semester at the dedication ceremony.\n\nDue to the request and contribution of Anne and Charles Duncan, Duncan College is one of the \"greenest\" buildings on Rice campus, as well as the entire city of Houston. Like nearby McMurtry College, the five-story building was designed by [[Hopkins Architects]] of London and offers 324 beds for student housing. The building is the first gold-level [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design]] (LEED) facility at Rice and the first LEED student residential-housing in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Duncan to receive LEED gold status |work = The Rice Thresher | accessdate = 2009-03-30 | url = http://the.ricethresher.org/news/2007/10/05/duncan_leed_gold#header }}</ref> The facility is designed to retain water for irrigation purposes and has motion detector lights which will turn on or off according to the flow of people. The building will decrease energy consumption by up to 25% as well as cut back on water usage. Air conditioners power off when windows are opened.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Rice announces $30M gift, plans for 'greenest' building yet | work = News and Media Relations, Rice University | date = 2007-08-21 | accessdate = 2009-03-30 | url = http://www.media.rice.edu/media/NewsBot.asp?MODE=VIEW&ID=9881&SnID=37427}}</ref>\n\n[[File:WR FLAG AS MY BLANKET.jpg|left|thumb| One of Duncan's favorite traditions is stealing Will Rice's flag.  Below is the flag draped across the bed of a certain Duncan lad in the Spring of 2016.]]\n\nDuncan College has also established a Monday night tradition, known as \"Monday Night Lights.\" When a few students went down to play ping-pong one night, they noticed that the ping pong table they had played on actually belonged to Baker College, who took its table back. Instead of going to bed, they made a makeshift table in the quad out of extra tables and using toilet paper as the net. People noticed the table and came down to the quad join in, watch and even play acoustic instruments. Monday Night Lights is now a monthly event. Other traditions include \"Duncing\" people in the DuncTank outside the commons on their birthdays, temporarily borrowing prized artifacts from other colleges including Will Rice's flag and Jones' trampoline, and a once a semester Nerf Gun capture the flag game throughout the building called Donnybrook.\n\nArchitecturally, Duncan has the same features as McMurtry with minor differences emphasized in order to establish its uniqueness. For example, Duncan Commons is rectangular in shape, contrasting the round McMurtry Commons. Also, Duncan quad has different features from McMurtry, such as a fountain by the Commons, smaller trees, and walkways that go across the quad. The interior, however, is virtually the same, as both colleges contain mostly doubles in the hallways and single rooms in the corners, with doubles having a pod bathroom inside and singles sharing common bathrooms. Both also have green roofs and fifth floor doubles and suites that open to the outside. The interior hallways of both Duncan and McMurtry were designed as contrasts to the other two most recently built residential colleges, Martel and Wiess, which have exterior hallways. The pair of McMurtry and Duncan are commonly referred to as McDuncan.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Texas}}\n* [http://students.rice.edu/students/Colleges.asp Residential College homepage]\n* [http://www.ruf.rice.edu/~program/beerbike/ About Beer Bike]\n* [http://beerbike.com/ Beer Bike History and Statistics]\n* [http://www.rice.edu/fondren/woodson/archives/willricecollege.html Will Rice College at the Woodson Research Center]\n* [http://www.edesigns-graphics.com/wiess/index.html Photographic study of Old Wiess]\n\n{{Rice University}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Residential Colleges Of Rice University}}\n[[Category:Rice University]]\n[[Category:University and college dormitories in the United States]]\n[[Category:Lists of university and college buildings in the United States|Rice University residential colleges]]\n", "name_user": "Rpopat1999", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWill Rice College:changed president and cj", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Residential_colleges_of_Rice_University"}
{"title_page": "Imbi the Girl", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = imbi (fka imbi the girl)\n| birth_name       = Imbar Nassi\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=y|1997|4|16}}\n| birth_place      = [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n}}\n| background       = solo_singer\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Singer-songwriter\n* rapper\n* poet\n }}\n| years_active     = 2017\u2013present\n| website          = {{URL|imbithegirl.com/}}\n| image            = \n}}\n\n'''Imbi''' (styled as '''imbi''') is a [[non-binary]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/114147/imbi-the-girl-is-a-non-binary-artist-exploring-the-complexities-of-gender-identity/|title=imbi the girl is a non-binary artist exploring the \"complexities of gender identity\"}}</ref> singer-songwriter, rapper and poet who was born and raised in Sydney.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8469380/imbi-the-girl-swell-video|title=Rising Aussie Singer Imbi the Girl Finds Their Peace in Intimate 'Swell' Video: Watch}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn June 2017, imbi the girl's debut single \"acidic\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.purplesneakers.com.au/2017/08/listen-imbi-the-girl-acidic/|title=Jump onboard Imbi the Girl's energetic debut 'Acidic'}}</ref> was released which was soon followed by the release of \"V.I.P.\" in September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_au/article/xw48nq/imbi-the-girls-vip-is-a-musical-treat-yo-self|title=Imbi the Girl's \"V.I.P.\" Is a Musical 'Treat Yo Self'}}</ref>\n\nimbi the girl is listed as a feature artist on [[Esoterik]]'s 2018 single \"Wide Awake\", part of his EP ''My Astral Plane'' which was nominated for the 2018 [[ARIA Award]] for [[ARIA Award for Best Urban Album|Best Urban Release]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ariaawards.com.au/news/2018/2018-aria-award-nominees-announced|title=2018 ARIA Award Nominees Announced \u2013 ARIA Awards}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, imbi the girl was announced as a winner of the [[Triple J Unearthed]] and [[National Institute of Dramatic Art|NIDA]] competition that saw students direct and produce a music video which was premiered on the television show [[Rage (TV program)|''rage'']] later in the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/meet-your-unearthed-nida-comp-winners/9637182|title=Meet your Unearthed NIDA comp winners!}}</ref>\n\nimbi the girl's debut EP, ''for me'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tonedeaf.com.au/imbi-the-girl-new-ep-interview/|title=A chat with imbi the girl about their new EP 'For Me'}}</ref> was released in September 2018, shortly after the release of their third single \"swell\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stoneyroads.com/2018/06/imbi-the-girl-returns-with-personal-new-track-swell/|title=Imbi The Girl returns with personal new track 'swell'}}</ref> imbi the girl describes the EP as \"a small taste of the goodness that is yet to come.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sniffers.co.nz/article/trip-imbi-girls-mellow-indie-rap-ep|title=Trip out on Imbi The Girl's mellow indie rap EP 'for me'}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, imbi the girl travelled to [[London]] after being chosen by [[Australasian Performing Right Association|APRA]] [[Australasian Mechanical Copyright Owners Society|AMCOS]] to take part in SongHubs, which aims to connect local and international songwriters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://themusicnetwork.com/songhubs-london-brings-creatives-together-at-legendary-rak-studios/|title=SongHubs London brings creatives together at legendary RAK Studios}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, imbi the girl was nominated for Live Voice of the Year (NSW) at the [[National Live Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scenestr.com.au/music/national-live-music-awards-2019-nominees-20191024|title=National Live Music Awards 2019 Nominees}}</ref>\n\n==Touring==\nimbi the girl has performed at festivals such as [[Groovin The Moo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tonedeaf.com.au/groovin-the-moo-fresh-produce-additions/|title=Groovin The Moo have announced their Fresh Produce additions for 2018}}</ref> BIGSOUND,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theindustryobserver.com.au/select-music-signs-sydney-artist-imbi-the-girl/|title=Select Music signs Sydney artist imbi the girl}}</ref> [[St Jerome's Laneway Festival|Laneway]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/laneway-festival-2019-lineup-girls-rock-camp-stage/10725766/|title=Laneway just added a bunch of Girls Rock! bands to the line-up}}</ref> [[Party In The Paddock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/party-in-the-paddock-2019-lineup-tasmania-festival/10351914|title=Tassie's Party In The Paddock drops huge 2019 line-up}}</ref> and [[Festival of the Sun]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.theaureview.com/news/mild-west-and-imbi-the-girl-join-festival-of-the-sun-next-month/|title=MILD WEST and Imbi The Girl join Festival of the Sun next month}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, imbi the girl toured nationally with [[Listen Out (festival)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beat.com.au/music/hip-hop-get-know-imbi-girl-new-tunes-internet-twenty-years-lauryn-hill|title=Hip hop: get to know Imbi The Girl. new tunes from The Internet, and twenty years of Lauryn Hill}}</ref> which saw performances in Melbourne, Perth, Sydney and Brisbane.\n\nimbi the girl has supported artists such as [[French Kiwi Juice|FKJ]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amnplify.com.au/portfolio-items/fkj-pomo-buoy-imbi-the-girl-oaf-05-01-18/|title=FKJ + Pomo + Buoy + Imbi The Girl @ OAF 05/01/18}}</ref> [[Sampa the Great]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fbiradio.com/soundcheck-april-16-22-sampa-the-great-freda-marcus-whale-tracks-3-ruby-fields-more/|title=Soundcheck April 16\u201322: Sampa The Great, Freda, Marcus Whale, Tracks No. 3, Ruby Fields & more}}</ref> [[Horrorshow (band)|Horrorshow]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://airit.org.au/imbi-the-girl-Swell.html|title=imbi the girl - Swell - Amrap's AirIt}}</ref> as well as [[Odette (musician)|Odette]] on her national tour throughout March and April in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicfeeds.com.au/news/odette-announces-lotus-eaters-national-tour/|title=Odette Announces 'Lotus Eaters' 2019 National Tour}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, imbi the girl announced their first headline tour, visiting venues in Sydney, Melbourne and Brisbane in June.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ausmusicscene.com.au/news/imbi-the-girl-announces-headline-tour|title=imbi the girl announces headline tour}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nIn an interview with [[Oyster (magazine)|Oyster]], imbi the girl said they \"grew up listening to [[Amy Winehouse]] and [[Macy Gray]] with my mum, and [[Wyclef Jean|Wyclef Jean]] and [[The Fugees]] with my dad\". As Imbar got older, they \"started listening to [[Chance the Rapper]], [[Childish Gambino]], [[Noname (rapper)|Noname]] and [[Lizzo]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oystermag.com/2019/06/imbi-the-girl-on-their-gender-crisis-and-the-music-that-came-from-it/|title=Imbi The Girl On Their 'Gender Crisis' And The Music That Came From It}}</ref> imbi the girl credits [[Allen Ginsberg]] and [[Sarah Kay (poet)|Sarah Kay]] as notable poetic influences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.purplesneakers.com.au/2018/09/interview-imbi-the-girl/|title=Getting to know Imbi The Girl}}</ref> imbi the girl told ''[[Gay Times]] Magazine'' that they've \"always looked up to [[Missy Elliot]] and her ability to be who she was unapologetically and express herself truthfully through not only her music but her fashion and her whole demeanour\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/114147/imbi-the-girl-is-a-non-binary-artist-exploring-the-complexities-of-gender-identity/|title=imbi the girl is a non-binary artist exploring the \"complexities of gender identity\"}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width:5em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width:16em;\" | Album details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''for me''\n|\n*Released: September 14, 2018\n*Format: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''back then''\n|\n*Released: November 14, 2019\n*Format: Digital download\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n====As lead artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"acidic\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2017\n| rowspan=\"3\"|''for me''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"V.I.P.\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"swell\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2018\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"i used to\"<br />{{small|(featuring SUPEREGO)}}\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2019\n| rowspan=\"3\"|''back then''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"our room\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"peaches & scream\"<br />{{small|(featuring [[Genesis Owusu]])}}\n|}\n\n====As featured artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:17em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Contraband & Conversation\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/contraband-conversation-feat-imbi-the-girl-kai-single/1368447207|title=Contraband & Conversation (feat. imbi the girl & Kai) \u2013 Single}}</ref><br />{{small|([[Spit Syndicate]] featuring imbi the girl & Kai)}}\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2018\n| rowspan=\"1\"|''Orbit''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Wide Awake\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/wide-awake-feat-spazzy-d-imbi-the-girl-single/1370707050|title=Wide Awake (feat. & imbi the girl & Spazzy D) \u2013 Single}}</ref><br />{{small|([[Esoterik]] featuring imbi the girl & Spazzy D)}}\n| rowspan=\"1\"|''My Astral Plane''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"You See Me\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/you-see-me-feat-imbi-the-girl-single/1370999959|title=You See Me (feat. imbi the girl) \u2013 Single}}</ref><br />{{small|(Oh Boy featuring imbi the girl)}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" {{n/a|Non-album single}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Singers from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Genderqueer people]]\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Queer musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT songwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from Australia]]\n[[Category:LGBT rappers]]\n[[Category:Non-binary musicians]]\n[[Category:Alternative hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian singers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Australian musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = imbi (fka imbi the girl)\n| birth_name       = Imbar Nassi\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=y|1997|4|16}}\n| birth_place      = [[Eora Land (sydney)]], so called 'australia'\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n}}\n| background       = solo_singer\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Singer-songwriter\n* rapper\n* poet\n }}\n| years_active     = 2017\u2013present\n| website          = {{URL|imbithegirl.com/}}\n| image            = https://www.triplejunearthed.com/node/6012951\n}}\n\n'''Imbi''' (styled as '''imbi''') is a [[non-binary]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/114147/imbi-the-girl-is-a-non-binary-artist-exploring-the-complexities-of-gender-identity/|title=imbi the girl is a non-binary artist exploring the \"complexities of gender identity\"}}</ref> singer-songwriter, rapper and poet who was born and raised in Sydney.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8469380/imbi-the-girl-swell-video|title=Rising Aussie Singer Imbi the Girl Finds Their Peace in Intimate 'Swell' Video: Watch}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nIn June 2017, imbi the girl's debut single \"acidic\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.purplesneakers.com.au/2017/08/listen-imbi-the-girl-acidic/|title=Jump onboard Imbi the Girl's energetic debut 'Acidic'}}</ref> was released which was soon followed by the release of \"V.I.P.\" in September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_au/article/xw48nq/imbi-the-girls-vip-is-a-musical-treat-yo-self|title=Imbi the Girl's \"V.I.P.\" Is a Musical 'Treat Yo Self'}}</ref>\n\nimbi the girl is listed as a feature artist on [[Esoterik]]'s 2018 single \"Wide Awake\", part of his EP ''My Astral Plane'' which was nominated for the 2018 [[ARIA Award]] for [[ARIA Award for Best Urban Album|Best Urban Release]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ariaawards.com.au/news/2018/2018-aria-award-nominees-announced|title=2018 ARIA Award Nominees Announced \u2013 ARIA Awards}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, imbi the girl was announced as a winner of the [[Triple J Unearthed]] and [[National Institute of Dramatic Art|NIDA]] competition that saw students direct and produce a music video which was premiered on the television show [[Rage (TV program)|''rage'']] later in the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/meet-your-unearthed-nida-comp-winners/9637182|title=Meet your Unearthed NIDA comp winners!}}</ref>\n\nimbi the girl's debut EP, ''for me'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tonedeaf.com.au/imbi-the-girl-new-ep-interview/|title=A chat with imbi the girl about their new EP 'For Me'}}</ref> was released in September 2018, shortly after the release of their third single \"swell\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stoneyroads.com/2018/06/imbi-the-girl-returns-with-personal-new-track-swell/|title=Imbi The Girl returns with personal new track 'swell'}}</ref> imbi the girl describes the EP as \"a small taste of the goodness that is yet to come.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sniffers.co.nz/article/trip-imbi-girls-mellow-indie-rap-ep|title=Trip out on Imbi The Girl's mellow indie rap EP 'for me'}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, imbi the girl travelled to [[London]] after being chosen by [[Australasian Performing Right Association|APRA]] [[Australasian Mechanical Copyright Owners Society|AMCOS]] to take part in SongHubs, which aims to connect local and international songwriters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://themusicnetwork.com/songhubs-london-brings-creatives-together-at-legendary-rak-studios/|title=SongHubs London brings creatives together at legendary RAK Studios}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, imbi the girl was nominated for Live Voice of the Year (NSW) at the [[National Live Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scenestr.com.au/music/national-live-music-awards-2019-nominees-20191024|title=National Live Music Awards 2019 Nominees}}</ref>\n\n==Touring==\n\nimbi the girl has performed at festivals such as [[Groovin The Moo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tonedeaf.com.au/groovin-the-moo-fresh-produce-additions/|title=Groovin The Moo have announced their Fresh Produce additions for 2018}}</ref> BIGSOUND,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theindustryobserver.com.au/select-music-signs-sydney-artist-imbi-the-girl/|title=Select Music signs Sydney artist imbi the girl}}</ref> [[St Jerome's Laneway Festival|Laneway]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/laneway-festival-2019-lineup-girls-rock-camp-stage/10725766/|title=Laneway just added a bunch of Girls Rock! bands to the line-up}}</ref> [[Party In The Paddock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/party-in-the-paddock-2019-lineup-tasmania-festival/10351914|title=Tassie's Party In The Paddock drops huge 2019 line-up}}</ref> and [[Festival of the Sun]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.theaureview.com/news/mild-west-and-imbi-the-girl-join-festival-of-the-sun-next-month/|title=MILD WEST and Imbi The Girl join Festival of the Sun next month}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, imbi the girl toured nationally with [[Listen Out (festival)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beat.com.au/music/hip-hop-get-know-imbi-girl-new-tunes-internet-twenty-years-lauryn-hill|title=Hip hop: get to know Imbi The Girl. new tunes from The Internet, and twenty years of Lauryn Hill}}</ref> which saw performances in Melbourne, Perth, Sydney and Brisbane.\n\nimbi the girl has supported artists such as [[French Kiwi Juice|FKJ]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amnplify.com.au/portfolio-items/fkj-pomo-buoy-imbi-the-girl-oaf-05-01-18/|title=FKJ + Pomo + Buoy + Imbi The Girl @ OAF 05/01/18}}</ref> [[Sampa the Great]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fbiradio.com/soundcheck-april-16-22-sampa-the-great-freda-marcus-whale-tracks-3-ruby-fields-more/|title=Soundcheck April 16\u201322: Sampa The Great, Freda, Marcus Whale, Tracks No. 3, Ruby Fields & more}}</ref> [[Horrorshow (band)|Horrorshow]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://airit.org.au/imbi-the-girl-Swell.html|title=imbi the girl - Swell - Amrap's AirIt}}</ref> as well as [[Odette (musician)|Odette]] on her national tour throughout March and April in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicfeeds.com.au/news/odette-announces-lotus-eaters-national-tour/|title=Odette Announces 'Lotus Eaters' 2019 National Tour}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, imbi the girl announced their first headline tour, visiting venues in Sydney, Melbourne and Brisbane in June.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ausmusicscene.com.au/news/imbi-the-girl-announces-headline-tour|title=imbi the girl announces headline tour}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\n\nIn an interview with [[Oyster (magazine)|Oyster]], imbi the girl said they \"grew up listening to [[Amy Winehouse]] and [[Macy Gray]] with my mum, and [[Wyclef Jean|Wyclef Jean]] and [[The Fugees]] with my dad\". As Imbar got older, they \"started listening to [[Chance the Rapper]], [[Childish Gambino]], [[Noname (rapper)|Noname]] and [[Lizzo]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oystermag.com/2019/06/imbi-the-girl-on-their-gender-crisis-and-the-music-that-came-from-it/|title=Imbi The Girl On Their 'Gender Crisis' And The Music That Came From It}}</ref> imbi the girl credits [[Allen Ginsberg]] and [[Sarah Kay (poet)|Sarah Kay]] as notable poetic influences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.purplesneakers.com.au/2018/09/interview-imbi-the-girl/|title=Getting to know Imbi The Girl}}</ref> imbi the girl told ''[[Gay Times]] Magazine'' that they've \"always looked up to [[Missy Elliot]] and her ability to be who she was unapologetically and express herself truthfully through not only her music but her fashion and her whole demeanour\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gaytimes.co.uk/culture/114147/imbi-the-girl-is-a-non-binary-artist-exploring-the-complexities-of-gender-identity/|title=imbi the girl is a non-binary artist exploring the \"complexities of gender identity\"}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width:5em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width:16em;\" | Album details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''for me''\n|\n*Released: September 14, 2018\n*Format: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''back then''\n|\n*Released: November 14, 2019\n*Format: Digital download\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n====As lead artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"acidic\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2017\n| rowspan=\"3\"|''for me''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"V.I.P.\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"swell\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2018\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"i used to\"<br />{{small|(featuring SUPEREGO)}}\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2019\n| rowspan=\"3\"|''back then''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"our room\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"peaches & scream\"<br />{{small|(featuring [[Genesis Owusu]])}}\n|}\n\n====As featured artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:17em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Contraband & Conversation\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/contraband-conversation-feat-imbi-the-girl-kai-single/1368447207|title=Contraband & Conversation (feat. imbi the girl & Kai) \u2013 Single}}</ref><br />{{small|([[Spit Syndicate]] featuring imbi the girl & Kai)}}\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2018\n| rowspan=\"1\"|''Orbit''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Wide Awake\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/wide-awake-feat-spazzy-d-imbi-the-girl-single/1370707050|title=Wide Awake (feat. & imbi the girl & Spazzy D) \u2013 Single}}</ref><br />{{small|([[Esoterik]] featuring imbi the girl & Spazzy D)}}\n| rowspan=\"1\"|''My Astral Plane''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"You See Me\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/you-see-me-feat-imbi-the-girl-single/1370999959|title=You See Me (feat. imbi the girl) \u2013 Single}}</ref><br />{{small|(Oh Boy featuring imbi the girl)}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" {{n/a|Non-album single}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Singers from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Genderqueer people]]\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Queer musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT songwriters]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from Australia]]\n[[Category:LGBT rappers]]\n[[Category:Non-binary musicians]]\n[[Category:Alternative hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian singers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Sydney]]\n[[Category:Australian musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Heyitsstevo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imbi_the_Girl"}
{"title_page": "Alan Hewitt", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Alan Hewitt\n| image       = Allan Hewitt in Perry Mason 1961.jpg\n| caption     = Alan Hewitt in Perry Mason 1961\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1915|1|21}}\n| birth_place  = New York City, New York\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1986|11|7|1915|1|21}}\n| death_place  = New York City, New York\n| occupation  = Actor\n| years_active = \n| spouse      = \n| website     = \n}}\n\n{{short description|American film, television and stage actor}}\n{{for|the American keyboardist|Alan Hewitt (musician)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=October 2015}}\n\n'''Alan Hewitt''' (January 21, 1915 \u2013 November 7, 1986) was an American film, television, and stage actor. His most prominent TV roles were Detective Brennan in ''[[My Favorite Martian]]'' and the [[district attorney]] in ''[[How to Murder Your Wife]]''.\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in [[New York City]], Hewitt was educated there<ref name=nyt/> and entered [[Dartmouth College]] when he was 15, graduating in 1934.<ref name=d/> His acting debut was in a school production at age 10.<ref name=lat>{{cite news|title=Alan Hewitt, Actor and Director in Stage, Film and TV, Dies at Age 71|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-11-18/local/me-7999_1_alan-hewitt|accessdate=June 17, 2015|agency=Los Angeles Times|date=November 18, 1986}}</ref>\n\n==Stage==\nHewitt first appeared on the New York stage in ''[[The Taming of the Shrew]]'' in 1935, starring [[Alfred Lunt]] and [[Lynn Fontanne]]. He later toured with them in that play.<ref name=lat/> in 1936-37, he appeared again with Lunt and Fontanne in productions of ''[[Amphitryon 38]]'' and ''[[The Sea Gull]]''.<ref name=d>{{cite web|title=The Papers of Alan Hewitt at Dartmouth College|url=http://ead.dartmouth.edu/html/ml66.html|website=Dartmouth|accessdate=June 17, 2015}}</ref> His obituary in [[The New York Times]] noted that he \"scored his biggest successes on Broadway in [[William Saroyan]]'s ''Love's Old Sweet Song'' and [[John Steinbeck]]'s ''[[The Moon Is Down]].''\"<ref name=nyt/>\n\nDuring World War II Hewitt served in the US Army's [[Armed Forces Radio Service]] from 1943-1946.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ead.dartmouth.edu/html/ml66.html|title=The Papers of Alan Hewitt at Dartmouth College: Full Finding Aid|website=ead.dartmouth.edu}}</ref>\n\n==Film==\nAmong the movies Hewitt appeared in are ''[[A Private's Affair]]'', ''[[That Touch of Mink]]'', ''[[Days of Wine and Roses (film)|Days of Wine and Roses]]'', ''[[Follow That Dream]]'', ''[[How to Murder Your Wife]]'', ''[[Sweet Charity (film)|Sweet Charity]]'', and ''[[The Barefoot Executive]]''.<ref name=d/>\n\n==Television==\nHe never became a major star, but he did have a lengthy career which included smaller parts in several well-known programs, including ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'', ''[[Maverick (TV series)|Maverick]]'', ''[[77 Sunset Strip]]'', ''[[Daktari]]'', ''[[Leave It to Beaver]]'', ''[[The Donna Reed Show]]'', ''[[Dr. Kildare]]'', ''[[Lost in Space]]'', ''[[Bewitched]]'', ''[[I Dream Of Jeannie]]'', ''[[The Lucy Show]]'', ''[[F Troop]]'', ''[[The Wild Wild West]]'', ''[[Ironside (TV series)|Ironside]]'', ''[[The Bob Newhart Show]]''  and ''[[The Phil Silvers Show]]''. He made four guest appearances on ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', in three of which he portrayed the murderer: in 1961 he played Bruce Sheridan in \u201cThe Case of the Wintry Wife\u201d and Dr. Marcus Tate in \u201cThe Case of the Brazen Bequest,\u201d and in 1965 he played the role of Curt Ordway in \u201cThe Case of the Fatal Fetish\u201d.  The only episode where he was not the murderer was 1959\u2019s \u201cThe Case of the Golden Fraud\u201d.\n\n==Actors' Equity Association==\nHewitt became a member of [[Actors' Equity Association]] in 1934, gaining membership on its council in 1940. He served on the council until 1951 and was also on several committees during that span.<ref name=d/> An obituary noted, \"He helped to establish the employment survey for performers in the American theater and frequently wrote letters and articles about actors' rights as professionals.\"<ref name=nyt/>\n\n==Death==\nHewitt died of cancer on November 7, 1986, at [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]] in New York City.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news|title=Alan Hewitt, Actor for 50 Years|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/11/11/obituaries/alan-hewitt-actor-for-50-years.html|accessdate=June 17, 2015|agency=The New York Times|date=November 11, 1986}}</ref> He was survived by his mother, Hortense B. (Baum) Hewitt (1892-1988) of Englewood, N.J., and a brother, Robert W. Hewitt (1919-2013) of Hillsdale, N.J.<ref name=nyt/> His father William predeceased him by about 40 years.\n\n==Papers==\nHewitt's papers were donated to Dartmouth College by his estate. The material housed at the Dartmouth College Library includes \"programs, scripts, clippings, sides, reviews, correspondence, playbills, photographs and tapes.\" It occupies 22 boxes.<ref name=d/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n*''[[A Private's Affair]]'' (1959) - Maj. R.C. Hanley\n*''[[Career (1959 film)|Career]]'' (1959) - Matt Helmsley\n*''[[The Absent Minded Professor]]'' (1961) - General Hotchkiss\n*''[[Bachelor in Paradise (film)|Bachelor in Paradise]]'' (1961) - Attorney Backett\n*''[[Follow That Dream]]'' (1962) - H. Arthur King\n*''[[That Touch of Mink]]'' (1962) - Doctor Gruber\n*''[[Days of Wine and Roses (film)|Days of Wine and Roses]]'' (1962) - Rad Leland\n*''[[Son of Flubber]]'' (1963) - Prosecutor\n*''[[The Misadventures of Merlin Jones]]'' (1964) - Professor Shattuck\n*''[[How to Murder Your Wife]]'' (1965) - District Attorney\n*''[[The Monkey's Uncle]]'' (1965) - Professor Shattuck\n*''[[The Horse in the Gray Flannel Suit]]'' (1968) - Harry Tomis\n*''[[The Brotherhood (1968 film)|The Brotherhood]]'' (1968) - Sol Levin\n*''[[Sweet Charity (film)|Sweet Charity]]'' (1969) - Nicholsby\n*''[[The Computer Wore Tennis Shoes]]'' (1969) - Dean Collingsgood\n*''[[R. P. M.]]'' (1970) - Hewlett\n*''[[The Barefoot Executive]]'' (1971) - Farnsworth\n*''[[Now You See Him, Now You Don't]]'' (1972) - Dean Collingsgood\n*''[[The Seniors]]'' (1978) - The Inspector (final film role)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0382003}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n*[http://archives.nypl.org/the/22599 Alan Hewitt papers, 1936-1985], held by the Billy Rose Theatre Division, [[New York Public Library for the Performing Arts]]\n* [https://archives-manuscripts.dartmouth.edu/repositories/2/resources/953 The Papers of Alan Hewitt] at Dartmouth College Library\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hewitt, Alan}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Alan Hewitt\n| image       = Allan Hewitt in Perry Mason 1961.jpg\n| caption     = Alan Hewitt in Perry Mason 1961\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1915|1|21}}\n| birth_place  = New York City, New York\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|1986|11|7|1915|1|21}}\n| death_place  = New York City, New York\n| occupation  = Actor\n| years_active = \n| spouse      = \n| website     = \n}}\n\n\n{{short description|American film, television and stage actor}}\n{{for|the American keyboardist|Alan Hewitt (musician)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=October 2015}}\n\n'''Alan Hewitt''' (January 21, 1915 \u2013 November 7, 1986) was an American film, television, and stage actor. His most prominent TV roles were Detective Brennan in ''[[My Favorite Martian]]'' and the [[district attorney]] in ''[[How to Murder Your Wife]]''.\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in [[New York City]], Hewitt was educated there<ref name=nyt/> and entered [[Dartmouth College]] when he was 15, graduating in 1934.<ref name=d/> His acting debut was in a school production at age 10.<ref name=lat>{{cite news|title=Alan Hewitt, Actor and Director in Stage, Film and TV, Dies at Age 71|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-11-18/local/me-7999_1_alan-hewitt|accessdate=June 17, 2015|agency=Los Angeles Times|date=November 18, 1986}}</ref>\n\n==Stage==\nHewitt first appeared on the New York stage in ''[[The Taming of the Shrew]]'' in 1935, starring [[Alfred Lunt]] and [[Lynn Fontanne]]. He later toured with them in that play.<ref name=lat/> in 1936-37, he appeared again with Lunt and Fontanne in productions of ''[[Amphitryon 38]]'' and ''[[The Sea Gull]]''.<ref name=d>{{cite web|title=The Papers of Alan Hewitt at Dartmouth College|url=http://ead.dartmouth.edu/html/ml66.html|website=Dartmouth|accessdate=June 17, 2015}}</ref> His obituary in [[The New York Times]] noted that he \"scored his biggest successes on Broadway in [[William Saroyan]]'s ''Love's Old Sweet Song'' and [[John Steinbeck]]'s ''[[The Moon Is Down]].''\"<ref name=nyt/>\n\nDuring World War II Hewitt served in the US Army's [[Armed Forces Radio Service]] from 1943-1946.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ead.dartmouth.edu/html/ml66.html|title=The Papers of Alan Hewitt at Dartmouth College: Full Finding Aid|website=ead.dartmouth.edu}}</ref>\n\n==Film==\nAmong the movies Hewitt appeared in are ''[[A Private's Affair]]'', ''[[That Touch of Mink]]'', ''[[Days of Wine and Roses (film)|Days of Wine and Roses]]'', ''[[Follow That Dream]]'', ''[[How to Murder Your Wife]]'', ''[[Sweet Charity (film)|Sweet Charity]]'', and ''[[The Barefoot Executive]]''.<ref name=d/>\n\n==Television==\nHe never became a major star, but he did have a lengthy career which included smaller parts in several well-known programs, including ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'', ''[[Maverick (TV series)|Maverick]]'', ''[[77 Sunset Strip]]'', ''[[Daktari]]'', ''[[Leave It to Beaver]]'', ''[[The Donna Reed Show]]'', ''[[Dr. Kildare]]'', ''[[Lost in Space]]'', ''[[Bewitched]]'', ''[[I Dream Of Jeannie]]'', ''[[The Lucy Show]]'', ''[[F Troop]]'', ''[[The Wild Wild West]]'', ''[[Ironside (TV series)|Ironside]]'', ''[[The Bob Newhart Show]]''  and ''[[The Phil Silvers Show]]''. He made four guest appearances on ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', in three of which he portrayed the murderer: in 1961 he played Bruce Sheridan in \u201cThe Case of the Wintry Wife\u201d and Dr. Marcus Tate in \u201cThe Case of the Brazen Bequest,\u201d and in 1965 he played the role of Curt Ordway in \u201cThe Case of the Fatal Fetish\u201d.  The only episode where he was not the murderer was 1959\u2019s \u201cThe Case of the Golden Fraud\u201d.\n\n==Actors' Equity Association==\nHewitt became a member of [[Actors' Equity Association]] in 1934, gaining membership on its council in 1940. He served on the council until 1951 and was also on several committees during that span.<ref name=d/> An obituary noted, \"He helped to establish the employment survey for performers in the American theater and frequently wrote letters and articles about actors' rights as professionals.\"<ref name=nyt/>\n\n==Death==\nHewitt died of cancer on November 7, 1986, at [[Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center]] in New York City.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news|title=Alan Hewitt, Actor for 50 Years|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/11/11/obituaries/alan-hewitt-actor-for-50-years.html|accessdate=June 17, 2015|agency=The New York Times|date=November 11, 1986}}</ref> He was survived by his mother, Hortense B. (Baum) Hewitt (1892-1988) of Englewood, N.J., and a brother, Robert W. Hewitt (1919-2013) of Hillsdale, N.J.<ref name=nyt/> His father William predeceased him by about 40 years.\n\n==Papers==\nHewitt's papers were donated to Dartmouth College by his estate. The material housed at the Dartmouth College Library includes \"programs, scripts, clippings, sides, reviews, correspondence, playbills, photographs and tapes.\" It occupies 22 boxes.<ref name=d/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n*''[[A Private's Affair]]'' (1959) - Maj. R.C. Hanley\n*''[[Career (1959 film)|Career]]'' (1959) - Matt Helmsley\n*''[[The Absent Minded Professor]]'' (1961) - General Hotchkiss\n*''[[Bachelor in Paradise (film)|Bachelor in Paradise]]'' (1961) - Attorney Backett\n*''[[Follow That Dream]]'' (1962) - H. Arthur King\n*''[[That Touch of Mink]]'' (1962) - Doctor Gruber\n*''[[Days of Wine and Roses (film)|Days of Wine and Roses]]'' (1962) - Rad Leland\n*''[[Son of Flubber]]'' (1963) - Prosecutor\n*''[[The Misadventures of Merlin Jones]]'' (1964) - Professor Shattuck\n*''[[How to Murder Your Wife]]'' (1965) - District Attorney\n*''[[The Monkey's Uncle]]'' (1965) - Professor Shattuck\n*''[[The Horse in the Gray Flannel Suit]]'' (1968) - Harry Tomis\n*''[[The Brotherhood (1968 film)|The Brotherhood]]'' (1968) - Sol Levin\n*''[[Sweet Charity (film)|Sweet Charity]]'' (1969) - Nicholsby\n*''[[The Computer Wore Tennis Shoes]]'' (1969) - Dean Collingsgood\n*''[[R. P. M.]]'' (1970) - Hewlett\n*''[[The Barefoot Executive]]'' (1971) - Farnsworth\n*''[[Now You See Him, Now You Don't]]'' (1972) - Dean Collingsgood\n*''[[The Seniors]]'' (1978) - The Inspector (final film role)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0382003}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n*[http://archives.nypl.org/the/22599 Alan Hewitt papers, 1936-1985], held by the Billy Rose Theatre Division, [[New York Public Library for the Performing Arts]]\n* [https://archives-manuscripts.dartmouth.edu/repositories/2/resources/953 The Papers of Alan Hewitt] at Dartmouth College Library\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hewitt, Alan}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1986 deaths]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n", "name_user": "NatGertler", "label": "safe", "comment": "whitespace correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Hewitt"}
